  // IND AS 2 – INVENTORIES
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  { id:1, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Objective & Scope\n\nWhat is the objective of Ind AS 2?\nWhich inventories are EXCLUDED from its scope?",
    back:"Objective: Prescribe accounting treatment for inventories — how to determine cost, recognise it as an expense (including write-down to NRV), and which cost formula to apply.\n\nExcludes from scope entirely:\n(a) Financial instruments (Ind AS 32 & 109)\n(b) Biological assets related to agricultural activity (Ind AS 41)\n\nExcludes from MEASUREMENT only:\n(a) Producers of agricultural & forest products, minerals — measured at NRV per industry practice\n(b) Commodity broker-traders — measured at FV less costs to sell\n\nChanges in NRV / FV less costs to sell → recognised in P&L in the period of change." },

  { id:2, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Key Definitions\n\nDefine: Inventories | Net Realisable Value | Fair Value\n\nState the key difference between NRV and Fair Value.",
    back:"Inventories: Assets held for SALE in ordinary course of business (finished goods); in process of production for such sale (WIP); or materials/supplies to be CONSUMED in production or rendering of services.\n\nNRV: Estimated selling price in ordinary course of business LESS estimated costs of completion LESS estimated costs to make the sale.\n→ Entity-specific value.\n\nFair Value: Price received to sell an asset in an orderly transaction between market participants at measurement date (Ind AS 113).\n→ Market-based measurement.\n\nKey difference:\n• NRV = what THIS entity expects to realise\n• FV = what market participants would pay\n• NRV for inventories may NOT equal Fair Value less costs to sell\n\nExample: Market FV = ₹10, order in hand @ ₹11, incremental cost = ₹0.50 → FV = ₹10, NRV = ₹10.50" },

  { id:3, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Measurement Principle\n\nAt what value are inventories measured?\nState the 3 components that make up the COST of inventories.",
    back:"Measurement: Inventories shall be measured at the LOWER OF COST and NET REALISABLE VALUE.\n\nCost of Inventories comprises:\n\n1. Costs of Purchase\n   • Purchase price + import duties + non-recoverable taxes + transport & handling\n   • Less: trade discounts, rebates and similar items\n   (Settlement/cash discounts → NOT deducted from cost)\n\n2. Costs of Conversion\n   • Direct materials, direct labour, other direct costs\n   • Systematic allocation of fixed & variable production overheads\n\n3. Other Costs\n   • Only if incurred in bringing inventories to present location & condition\n   • Borrowing costs → only if qualifies as qualifying asset under Ind AS 23\n   • Deferred payment → financing element recognised as interest expense, NOT added to inventory" },

  { id:4, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Fixed Production Overheads\n\nHow are FIXED production overheads allocated?\nWhat happens when actual production is BELOW normal capacity? ABOVE?",
    back:"Fixed O/H: Relatively constant regardless of production volume (e.g., factory depreciation, factory management).\n\nAllocation basis: NORMAL CAPACITY\n• Normal capacity = average production expected over several periods under normal circumstances (accounting for planned maintenance)\n\nIf AP = NC:\n→ Allocated fixed O/H = Total fixed O/H → ₹0 unallocated\n\nIf AP < NC (abnormally low):\n→ Rate = Total FO/H ÷ NC (maintained)\n→ Allocated to inventory = AP × rate\n→ UNALLOCATED O/H → expensed to P&L immediately\n\nIf AP > NC (abnormally high):\n→ Rate = Total FO/H ÷ AP (reduced)\n→ All O/H absorbed → ₹0 expensed separately\n→ Inventory per unit reduced so inventory ≤ cost\n\nVariable O/H: Allocated on basis of ACTUAL USE of production facilities.\n\n📌 NEVER over-absorb fixed overheads into inventory." },

  { id:5, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Costs EXCLUDED from Inventory\n\nList the costs that must be EXCLUDED from inventory cost and expensed in the period incurred.",
    back:"Must NEVER be included in inventory cost:\n\n(a) Abnormal amounts of wasted materials, labour or other production costs\n\n(b) Storage costs — UNLESS necessary in the production process BEFORE a further production stage\n   ✅ Ageing of whiskey in cask (essential to product)\n   ❌ Warehouse storage of finished goods\n\n(c) Administrative overheads NOT contributing to bringing inventories to present location & condition\n\n(d) Selling costs\n   Including: sales commission, distribution costs, after-sale warranty, advertising\n\n(e) Financing element in deferred payment (→ interest expense)\n\n📌 Common exam traps:\n✅ Import duties, freight, brokerage to indenting agents, insurance on purchases → INCLUDED\n❌ Accounts dept salaries, sales commission, warranty costs → P&L expense" },

  { id:6, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Joint Products & By-Products\n\nHow is cost allocated when a process produces joint products?\nHow are by-products treated?",
    back:"Joint Products:\n\nIf conversion costs are SEPARATELY identifiable:\n→ Each product bears its own separately identified cost\n\nIf costs are NOT separately identifiable:\n→ Allocate on RATIONAL & CONSISTENT basis:\n   • Relative sales value at split-off point, OR\n   • Relative sales value at completion of production\n\nBy-Products:\n\nImmaterial by-product:\n→ Measured at NRV\n→ NRV deducted from COST OF MAIN PRODUCT\n→ Carrying amount of main product = not materially different from its cost\n\nMaterial by-product:\n→ Treated as a JOINT PRODUCT\n→ Costs allocated on rational & consistent basis\n\nScrap/waste:\n→ Usually immaterial → measured at NRV → deducted from joint cost\n\n📌 By-product NRV always reduces cost of main product first." },

  { id:7, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Cost Formulas\n\nWhat are the permitted cost formulas?\nWhich is NOT permitted? Why?\nState the consistency rule.",
    back:"Permitted formulas:\n\n1. FIFO (First-In, First-Out):\n   Items purchased/produced first → sold first\n   Closing inventory = most recently purchased costs\n\n2. Weighted Average Cost:\n   Average cost of similar items at beginning + purchased during period\n   Computed periodically or after each receipt (moving average)\n   Formula: (Cost in store + Cost of new items) ÷ (Units in store + New units)\n\n3. Specific Identification:\n   Actual cost attributed to individually identified items\n   Used for: non-interchangeable items, goods for specific projects\n   Examples: Jewellery, tailor-made goods\n\nNOT Permitted: LIFO\n→ Inventory values may bear little relationship to recent cost levels\n\nConsistency rule:\n→ SAME formula for all inventories of SIMILAR nature and use\n→ DIFFERENT nature or use → may justify different formula\n→ Different geographic location ALONE → does NOT justify different formula" },

  { id:8, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Cost Measurement Techniques\n\nName and describe the two TECHNIQUES allowed for measuring cost of inventories.",
    back:"Two approximation techniques are permitted if results approximate actual cost:\n\n1. Standard Cost Method:\n   • Cost based on NORMAL levels of materials & supplies, labour efficiency, capacity utilisation\n   • Standards regularly reviewed and revised\n   • Used for manufacturing companies with reliable data\n\n2. Retail Method:\n   • Used in retail industry for large numbers of rapidly changing items with similar margins\n   • Cost = Sales value of inventory LESS appropriate gross margin %\n   • % takes into account inventory marked down below original selling price\n   • An average % for each retail department often used\n\n📌 Key difference:\n• Techniques = approximation methods to arrive at cost\n• Cost formulas (FIFO/WA) = how to assign actual costs to specific units" },

  { id:9, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Service Provider Inventories\n\nHow does Ind AS 2 apply to inventories of SERVICE PROVIDERS?\nWhat costs are included vs excluded?",
    back:"Service provider inventories = described as WORK IN PROGRESS.\n\nCost includes:\n✅ Labour and other costs of PERSONNEL DIRECTLY engaged in providing the service (including supervisory)\n✅ ATTRIBUTABLE OVERHEADS\n\nCost excludes:\n❌ Labour relating to SALES and GENERAL ADMINISTRATIVE personnel\n❌ Profit margins\n\nRecognition:\n→ WIP accumulates only for INCOMPLETE services\n→ Once service is complete / revenue recognised → recognised as COST OF SERVICES (expense)\n\nBalance sheet:\n→ Described as 'Work in Progress'\n\nExample:\nConsulting firm accumulates staff costs + directly attributable overheads for an incomplete engagement as WIP → expensed when engagement completes and revenue is recognised." },

  { id:10, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Agricultural Produce & Deferred Payment\n\nHow is agricultural produce initially measured at harvest?\n\nAlso: How is a FINANCING ELEMENT in deferred payment treated?",
    back:"Agricultural produce (Ind AS 41 interface):\n\n→ Harvested produce measured at FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL at point of harvest\n→ This FV less costs to sell = DEEMED COST for Ind AS 2 purposes\n→ From harvest date: normal Ind AS 2 rules apply (lower of deemed cost and NRV)\n\nExamples: Cotton, grapes, timber — all measured at FV less CTS at harvest, then Ind AS 2 applies thereafter.\n\nDeferred Payment (financing element):\n\nWhen arrangement contains a financing element:\n→ Inventory recorded at the CASH PRICE EQUIVALENT\n→ Difference between deferred price and cash price = INTEREST EXPENSE over financing period\n\nExample:\n• Deferred price: ₹3,00,000 (₹25,000/month × 12)\n• Cash price: ₹2,80,000\n• Financing element: ₹20,000 → interest expense\n• Inventory cost: ₹2,80,000\n\nBorrowing costs (Ind AS 23):\n→ Included ONLY if inventory is a qualifying asset (substantial period to get ready)\n→ Large quantities on REPETITIVE basis → NOT qualifying assets" },

  { id:11, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – NRV: Firm Sales Contracts\n\nAn entity holds 100 units. Firm contract to sell 60 units @ ₹11/unit (incremental selling cost ₹1/unit). Market price for remaining 40 units = ₹8/unit (incremental cost ₹1/unit). Cost = ₹10/unit.\n\nCalculate NRV and inventory value for each group.",
    back:"Rule: NRV estimates take into account the PURPOSE for which inventory is held.\n\n→ Inventory under FIRM SALES CONTRACTS → NRV based on CONTRACT PRICE\n→ EXCESS inventory → NRV based on GENERAL SELLING PRICES\n\nApplication:\n\n60 units (under firm contract):\n→ NRV = ₹11 − ₹1 = ₹10/unit\n→ Cost = ₹10/unit → Lower of cost/NRV = ₹10 → No write-down\n→ Inventory value = 60 × ₹10 = ₹600\n\n40 units (excess — no firm contract):\n→ NRV = ₹8 − ₹1 = ₹7/unit\n→ Cost = ₹10/unit → NRV < Cost → Write-down to ₹7\n→ Inventory value = 40 × ₹7 = ₹280\n\nTotal inventory = ₹600 + ₹280 = ₹880\nWrite-down recognised = 40 × ₹3 = ₹120\n\n📌 If firm contracts are for MORE than inventory held → consider Ind AS 37 onerous contract provisions for the shortfall." },

  { id:12, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – NRV: Writing Down Raw Materials\n\nAn entity holds raw materials. The selling price of FINISHED GOODS has fallen below cost. Should the raw materials be written down?\n\nWhat is the measure of NRV for raw materials?",
    back:"General rule: Raw materials NOT written down below cost if finished goods are expected to be sold AT OR ABOVE COST.\n\nException – write-down applies:\nDecline in price of raw materials indicates cost of finished product will EXCEED its NRV → raw materials ARE written down to NRV.\n\nMeasure of NRV for raw materials:\n→ REPLACEMENT COST is the best available measure of NRV\n(Cannot determine a selling price for raw materials in isolation when they feed into multiple products)\n\nImportant:\n→ No write-down just because anticipated profit will be LESS THAN NORMAL\n→ Write-down only if finished goods expected to be sold AT A LOSS\n\nDiagram:\n• Finished goods sold at or above cost → Raw materials at COST\n• Finished goods sold below cost (at NRV) → Raw materials at REPLACEMENT COST (= NRV proxy)" },

  { id:13, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – NRV Write-Down Reversal\n\nWhen is a previous write-down REVERSED?\nWhat is the ceiling for reversal?",
    back:"Reversal trigger:\nNew assessment of NRV in each subsequent period shows circumstances previously causing write-down NO LONGER EXIST, or there is clear evidence of INCREASE in NRV.\n\nReversal amount:\n→ Limited to the amount of the ORIGINAL WRITE-DOWN\n→ New carrying amount = LOWER of (original cost) and (revised NRV)\n\nRecognition:\n→ Recognised as a REDUCTION in inventory expense in the period of reversal\n\nExample:\n→ Item written down from ₹50 (cost) to ₹25 (NRV)\n→ Next year NRV rises to ₹60\n→ Reversal = ₹25 (restoring to cost of ₹50, NOT to ₹60)\n→ New carrying amount = ₹50 (original cost)\n\n📌 Write-down done item by item. Reversal also item by item.\n📌 Passage of time alone (without changed circumstances) → NOT sufficient." },

  { id:14, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Recognition as Expense & Disclosure\n\nHow is inventory carrying amount recognised as expense?\nList the 5 key DISCLOSURE requirements.",
    back:"Recognition as Expense:\n→ Carrying amount of inventories sold → recognised in period related REVENUE is recognised\n→ Write-downs to NRV + losses → expense in period incurred\n→ Reversals → reduce inventory expense in period of reversal\n\nNote: Inventory used in self-constructed PPE → capitalised, then depreciated over useful life of PPE.\n\n5 Key Disclosures:\n1. Accounting policies (including COST FORMULA used)\n2. Total carrying amount + carrying amount by classification (merchandise, production supplies, materials, WIP, finished goods)\n3. Carrying amount of inventories carried at FV less costs to sell\n4. Amount recognised as expense; write-down amounts; reversal amounts + circumstances\n5. Carrying amount of inventories PLEDGED AS SECURITY for liabilities" },

  { id:15, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Practical: Cost of Purchase\n\nA company buys 1,000 units. Quoted price ₹1,200/unit; trade discount 5%; settlement discount 2% (intends to take); import duty ₹60/unit; delivery ₹5,000.\n\nCalculate cost of inventory. Which discount is deducted?",
    back:"Cost of inventory calculation:\n\nPurchase price: 1,000 × ₹1,200 × 95% = ₹11,40,000\nImport duties: 1,000 × ₹60         = ₹60,000\nDelivery cost                       = ₹5,000\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nCost of inventory                   = ₹12,05,000\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n\nCost per unit = ₹12,05,000 ÷ 1,000 = ₹1,205/unit\n\n📌 KEY RULES:\n→ TRADE DISCOUNT (5%) → DEDUCTED ✅ (reduces purchase price)\n→ SETTLEMENT/CASH DISCOUNT (2%) → NOT DEDUCTED ❌\n   Even though entity intends to take it, cash discounts are NOT deducted from inventory cost. They represent a financial decision, not a trade price reduction.\n→ Import duties → INCLUDED ✅\n→ Delivery/freight → INCLUDED ✅\n\n📌 Exam trap: Only TRADE discounts reduce cost. Settlement discounts do not." },

  { id:16, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Primary vs Secondary Packing & Variable Overheads\n\nDistinguish primary and secondary packing. Which is included in inventory cost?\n\nAlso: How are VARIABLE production overheads allocated?",
    back:"Primary packing material:\n→ ESSENTIAL to bring inventory to SALEABLE CONDITION\n→ Without it, product cannot be sold (e.g., bottles/cans for food, sealed packets for medicines)\n→ INCLUDED in cost of inventories ✅\n\nSecondary packing material:\n→ Used for TRANSPORTING and FORWARDING after product is saleable (outer cartons, shipping crates)\n→ Nature of SELLING COST → EXCLUDED ❌\n→ Recognised as expense in P&L\n\nPublicity/marketing materials → EXCLUDED ❌ (selling costs)\n\nTest: Does the packing make the product SALEABLE? ✅ Or facilitate DELIVERY of an already-saleable product? ❌\n\nVariable production overheads:\n→ Vary directly (or nearly directly) with volume of production\n→ Examples: Indirect materials, indirect labour\n→ Allocation basis: ACTUAL USE of production facilities\n→ Always fully absorbed — no concept of under-absorption for variable overheads under Ind AS 2" },

  { id:17, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Formula Card: NRV & Weighted Average\n\n1. Write the NRV formula\n2. Write the inventory write-down formula\n3. Write the weighted average cost formula after a new purchase",
    back:"1. Net Realisable Value:\nNRV = Estimated Selling Price − Estimated Costs of Completion − Estimated Costs to Make the Sale\n\n(Trade discounts expected → deducted from selling price)\n(Cash discounts for prompt payment → NOT deducted)\n\n2. Inventory Write-Down:\nWrite-down = Cost − NRV (only when NRV < Cost; applied item by item)\n\n3. New Weighted Average after purchase:\nNew WA = (Cost of units in store + Cost of new items received)\n         ÷ (Units in store + New units received)\n\nExample:\n• In store: 25 units @ ₹2.10 = ₹52.50\n• New receipt: 150 units @ ₹2.80 = ₹420.00\n• New WA = (₹52.50 + ₹420) ÷ (25 + 150) = ₹472.50 ÷ 175 = ₹2.70 per unit\n\n📌 Under moving average: new WA computed after each purchase. Sales at most recent WA." },

  { id:18, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Formula Card: Fixed Overhead Absorption\n\nNormal capacity = 1,00,000 units. Total fixed O/H = ₹15,00,000.\n\nCase 1: Actual = 1,00,000\nCase 2: Actual = 75,000\nCase 3: Actual = 1,25,000\n\nFor each: (a) O/H per unit in inventory, (b) Amount expensed to P&L",
    back:"Fixed O/H rate (based on NC) = ₹15,00,000 ÷ 1,00,000 = ₹15/unit\n\nCase 1: AP = NC = 1,00,000\n(a) ₹15 per unit\n(b) ₹0 expensed (fully absorbed)\n\nCase 2: AP = 75,000 < NC\n(a) ₹15 per unit (normal rate maintained)\n(b) Allocated = 75,000 × ₹15 = ₹11,25,000\n    Expensed to P&L = ₹15,00,000 − ₹11,25,000 = ₹3,75,000\n    (Unabsorbed overheads → P&L immediately)\n\nCase 3: AP = 1,25,000 > NC\n(a) ₹12 per unit (= ₹15,00,000 ÷ 1,25,000)\n    (Rate reduced so inventory not above cost)\n(b) All ₹15,00,000 absorbed → ₹0 expensed separately\n\n📌 Rule: Inventory per unit = ₹15 in Case 1 & 2. Reduced in Case 3. Unallocated O/H always → P&L." },

  { id:19, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Quick Fire\n\n1. LIFO is ___ under Ind AS 2.\n2. NRV estimates take into account events ___ period end that confirm conditions ___ at period end.\n3. Write-down is done on ___ basis, NOT ___ basis.\n4. Storage costs included in inventory ONLY if ___.\n5. Settlement discounts ___ deducted from cost.",
    back:"1. LIFO is NOT PERMITTED under Ind AS 2.\n\n2. NRV estimates take into account events AFTER period end that confirm conditions EXISTING at period end.\n\n3. Write-down is done on ITEM-BY-ITEM basis, NOT total inventory or classification basis.\n\n4. Storage costs included in inventory ONLY if necessary in the PRODUCTION PROCESS before a further production stage.\n\n5. Settlement discounts are NOT deducted from cost.\n   (Only TRADE discounts are deducted.)\n\nBonus:\n→ By-product NRV → deducted from MAIN PRODUCT cost\n→ Retail method: cost = sales value LESS appropriate gross margin %\n→ Same cost formula must be used for inventories of similar nature and use\n→ Agricultural produce at harvest = FV less costs to sell = DEEMED COST for Ind AS 2" },

  { id:20, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – AS 2 vs Ind AS 2: Key Differences\n\nState 4 significant differences between Ind AS 2 and old AS 2.",
    back:"1. Subsequent Recognition:\n   Ind AS 2 → explicitly deals with subsequent recognition of carrying amount as expense\n   AS 2 → does NOT provide the same\n\n2. Commodity Broker-Traders:\n   Ind AS 2 → scopes out measurement of inventories held by commodity broker-traders (FV less costs to sell)\n   AS 2 → no such provision\n\n3. Definition of Fair Value & Distinction from NRV:\n   Ind AS 2 → defines FV; explains difference between NRV and FV\n   AS 2 → does not contain FV definition\n\n4. NRV Reversal:\n   Ind AS 2 → detailed guidance on subsequent NRV assessment + reversal (limited to original write-down)\n   AS 2 → does not deal with reversal\n\n5. Cost Formulas:\n   Ind AS 2 → requires consistent formula for inventories of similar nature and use\n   AS 2 → formula should 'reflect fairest possible approximation to cost incurred'\n\n6. LIFO:\n   Both Ind AS 2 and AS 2 → PROHIBIT LIFO" },

  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // IND AS 36 – IMPAIRMENT OF ASSETS
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  { id:21, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Objective & Scope\n\nWhat is the objective?\nList 6 asset types EXCLUDED from scope.",
    back:"Objective: Ensure assets are carried at NO MORE than their RECOVERABLE AMOUNT. Prescribe when to recognise and reverse impairment losses.\n\nExcludes from scope:\n(a) Inventories (Ind AS 2)\n(b) Contract assets & costs to obtain/fulfill contracts (Ind AS 115)\n(c) Deferred tax assets (Ind AS 12)\n(d) Employee benefit assets (Ind AS 19)\n(e) Financial assets (Ind AS 109)\n(f) Non-current assets held for sale (Ind AS 105)\n(g) Biological assets at FV less costs to sell (Ind AS 41)\n(h) Insurance acquisition cash flows (Ind AS 117)\n\nApplies to:\n• PPE, intangible assets, investment property (cost model)\n• Investments in subsidiaries, associates, JVs (separate FS)\n• Goodwill from business combinations\n\nNote: All excluded assets are covered by other Ind AS with equivalent impairment provisions." },

  { id:22, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Key Definitions\n\nDefine:\n• Impairment Loss\n• Recoverable Amount\n• Cash-Generating Unit (CGU)\n• Value in Use\n• Carrying Amount\n• Corporate Assets\n• Costs of Disposal",
    back:"Impairment Loss: Amount by which CARRYING AMOUNT > RECOVERABLE AMOUNT\nFormula: IL = CA − RA\n\nRecoverable Amount: HIGHER of FVLCD and VIU\n(If either exceeds CA → asset not impaired)\n\nCGU: Smallest identifiable GROUP of assets generating cash inflows LARGELY INDEPENDENT of other assets/groups.\n\nValue in Use: PRESENT VALUE of future cash flows expected from an asset or CGU.\n\nCarrying Amount: Amount at which asset is recognised AFTER deducting accumulated depreciation and accumulated impairment losses.\n\nCorporate Assets: Assets OTHER than goodwill contributing to future cash flows of BOTH the CGU under review AND other CGUs. (e.g., head office, EDP equipment, research centre)\n\nCosts of Disposal: Incremental costs directly attributable to disposal, EXCLUDING finance costs & income tax." },

  { id:23, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – When to Test for Impairment\n\nName the 3 assets requiring MANDATORY ANNUAL impairment test.\nFor all other assets: when must impairment be assessed?",
    back:"3 Assets requiring MANDATORY ANNUAL test (regardless of indicators):\n1. Intangible assets with INDEFINITE useful life\n2. Intangible assets NOT YET AVAILABLE for use\n3. Goodwill acquired in a business combination\n\nKey rule for these 3:\n→ Test can be performed at any time during the year, but SAME TIME every year\n→ Different intangibles may be tested at different times\n→ If acquired in current period → must be tested before end of current annual period\n→ May roll forward previous calculation if: CGU unchanged + substantial headroom + remote likelihood of impairment\n\nFor ALL OTHER assets:\n→ Assess at END OF EACH REPORTING PERIOD for any INDICATION of impairment\n→ If indication exists → estimate recoverable amount\n→ No indication → no formal calculation needed\n\n📌 The 3 mandatory-annual assets need testing even if there are NO indicators of impairment." },

  { id:24, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Indicators of Impairment\n\nList the EXTERNAL and INTERNAL sources of impairment indicators.",
    back:"EXTERNAL sources (4):\n(a) Asset's market value has DECLINED SIGNIFICANTLY — more than expected from passage of time or normal use\n(b) Significant ADVERSE CHANGES in technological, market, economic, or legal environment\n(c) Market INTEREST RATES have INCREASED — likely to materially affect discount rate in VIU\n(d) Carrying amount of net assets > MARKET CAPITALISATION\n\nINTERNAL sources (3):\n(a) Evidence of OBSOLESCENCE or PHYSICAL DAMAGE\n(b) Significant adverse changes in EXTENT or MANNER of use (asset becoming idle, plans to discontinue/restructure, plans to dispose before expected date, reassessing useful life from indefinite to finite)\n(c) INTERNAL REPORTING data shows economic performance worse than expected (actual cash flows significantly worse than budgeted, operating losses, etc.)\n\nInvestment in subsidiary/associate/JV:\n(d) Dividend received > total comprehensive income of investee\n(e) Carrying amount in separate FS > carrying amounts in consolidated FS" },

  { id:25, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Recoverable Amount & FVLCD\n\nWhat is Fair Value Less Costs of Disposal (FVLCD)?\nWhat costs are DEDUCTED vs NOT deducted?",
    back:"FVLCD = Fair Value (per Ind AS 113) MINUS Costs of Disposal\n\nFair Value: Price received to sell asset in orderly transaction between market participants.\n\nCosts of disposal DEDUCTED:\n✅ Legal costs\n✅ Stamp duty and similar transaction taxes\n✅ Costs of removing the asset\n✅ Direct incremental costs to bring asset into condition for sale\n(Only if NOT already recognised as liabilities)\n\nNOT deducted:\n❌ Termination benefits (Ind AS 19)\n❌ Costs of reducing/reorganising business following disposal\n\nWhen only one needs to be calculated:\n→ If FVLCD > CA → not impaired → no need to calculate VIU\n→ If no reliable basis for FVLCD → use VIU alone\n\nFV vs VIU distinction:\n• FV → market participant assumptions (entity-neutral)\n• VIU → entity-specific synergies and legal rights" },

  { id:26, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Value in Use (VIU)\n\nWhat is VIU? State the key rules for cash flow projections.\nWhat must be EXCLUDED from VIU cash flows?\nWhat is the discount rate requirement?",
    back:"VIU: Present value of FUTURE CASH FLOWS expected from an asset or CGU.\n\nCash flow projection rules:\n(a) Based on reasonable & supportable assumptions; GREATER WEIGHT to external evidence\n(b) Based on most recent management-approved budgets/forecasts — max 5 YEARS (unless longer justified)\n(c) Beyond 5-year period → steady or DECLINING growth rate (not exceeding long-term industry/country average)\n\nCash flows INCLUDED:\n✅ Inflows from continuing use\n✅ Outflows necessarily incurred to generate those inflows\n✅ Net cash flows from disposal at end of useful life\n\nCash flows EXCLUDED:\n❌ Future restructurings NOT YET COMMITTED\n❌ Improving or ENHANCING asset's performance\n❌ Cash flows from FINANCING activities\n❌ INCOME TAX receipts or payments (pre-tax basis)\n\nDiscount rate:\n→ PRE-TAX rate reflecting current market assessments of time value of money + asset-specific risks\n→ Surrogates: entity's WACC or incremental borrowing rate (adjusted to pre-tax, asset-specific)" },

  { id:27, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Recognition of Impairment Loss\n\nHow is impairment loss recognised for COST MODEL vs REVALUED ASSET?\nWhat happens to depreciation AFTER recognition?",
    back:"When Recoverable Amount < Carrying Amount → recognise impairment loss.\n\nCost model asset:\n→ Impairment loss recognised IMMEDIATELY in Profit or Loss\n\nRevalued asset (Ind AS 16 or Ind AS 38):\n→ FIRST: offset against existing REVALUATION SURPLUS for that asset (in OCI)\n→ EXCESS over revaluation surplus → recognised in P&L\n\nPost-recognition depreciation:\n→ Depreciation charge ADJUSTED in future periods\n→ New depreciation = (Revised CA − Residual value) ÷ Remaining useful life\n\nOther points:\n→ Deferred tax recalculated comparing revised CA with tax base\n→ If impairment loss > CA → recognise a liability if required by another standard\n\nExample:\nRevised CA = ₹10,000; Residual = ₹500; Remaining life = 5 years\nNew annual dep = (₹10,000 − ₹500) ÷ 5 = ₹1,900" },

  { id:28, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Cash-Generating Units (CGUs)\n\nWhat is a CGU? When is recoverable amount determined at CGU level?\nWhat does the carrying amount of a CGU include / exclude?",
    back:"CGU: Smallest identifiable group of assets generating cash inflows LARGELY INDEPENDENT of cash inflows from other assets/groups.\n\nWhen to use CGU:\n→ Individual asset cannot generate cash inflows independently (e.g., machine only usable as part of production line)\n→ UNLESS: asset's FVLCD > CA, or VIU ≈ FVLCD\n\nCarrying amount of CGU INCLUDES:\n✅ Assets directly attributed or allocated on reasonable & consistent basis\n✅ Assets generating the future cash inflows used in CGU's VIU calculation\n\nCarrying amount of CGU EXCLUDES:\n❌ Recognised liabilities (UNLESS recoverable amount cannot be determined without considering them)\n❌ Goodwill and corporate assets → tested separately with special rules\n\nIdentifying CGUs:\n→ Consistent with how management monitors operations\n→ Can be as small as one asset or as large as a reportable segment\n\n📌 A bus route = one CGU (even though individual buses do not generate independent cash inflows)." },

  { id:29, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Goodwill Impairment Testing\n\nHow is goodwill ALLOCATED to CGUs?\nState the ORDER of testing when CGU assets and goodwill tested simultaneously.\nHow is impairment loss allocated within a CGU?",
    back:"Goodwill allocation:\n→ To CGUs/groups of CGUs EXPECTED TO BENEFIT from synergies of the combination\n→ Lowest level at which management monitors goodwill; not larger than an operating segment\n→ Pro-rata method: Goodwill to CGU = (Purchase consideration allocated to CGU ÷ Total purchase consideration) × Total goodwill\n\nOrder of testing (bottom-up):\n1. FIRST test individual assets within CGU → recognise any impairment losses\n2. THEN test the CGU including goodwill → recognise impairment at CGU level\n\nImpairment loss allocation order:\n(a) FIRST → reduce carrying amount of GOODWILL to zero\n(b) THEN → reduce other assets PRO RATA based on carrying amounts\n\nFloor per individual asset:\nCA cannot be reduced below HIGHEST of:\n→ FVLCD (if determinable)\n→ VIU (if determinable)\n→ ZERO\n\nExcess over floor → reallocated pro rata to other assets in CGU.\n\n📌 CRITICAL: Goodwill impairment CANNOT BE REVERSED." },

  { id:30, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Corporate Assets & NCI Goodwill\n\nHow are corporate assets tested for impairment?\n\nExplain the NCI goodwill 'GROSSING UP' concept.",
    back:"Corporate assets: OTHER than goodwill; contribute to cash flows of BOTH CGU under review AND other CGUs.\n\nScenario A — CA can be allocated to CGU on reasonable & consistent basis:\n→ Include portion in CGU's carrying amount → test enlarged CGU against RA\n\nScenario B — CA CANNOT be allocated:\n→ Step 1: Test individual CGU without corporate asset\n→ Step 2: Identify SMALLEST GROUP of CGUs to which CA can be allocated\n→ Step 3: Test that group (including CA) against group's RA\n\nNCI Goodwill Grossing Up (partial goodwill method):\n→ Under Ind AS 103, if NCI measured at proportionate share, only PARENT'S goodwill recognised\n→ CGU carrying amount = net assets (parent + NCI) + parent's goodwill only\n→ But recoverable amount reflects FULL economic entity\n→ Solution: GROSS UP goodwill = Recognised goodwill ÷ Parent's % × NCI %\n→ Compare grossed-up CA with RA\n→ If impaired: total IL calculated on grossed-up basis\n→ Only impairment on PARENT'S share recognised in CFS\n→ NCI portion of unrecognised goodwill impairment → NOT recognised" },

  { id:31, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Reversal of Impairment Loss\n\nWhen can an impairment loss be reversed?\nState rules for: (a) Individual asset, (b) CGU, (c) Goodwill.",
    back:"General condition: Change in ESTIMATES used to determine recoverable amount.\n⚠️ Passage of time alone → NOT sufficient.\n\n(a) Individual asset reversal:\n→ Increased CA shall NOT exceed CA had NO impairment been recognised (net of dep/amortisation)\n→ Cost model → recognised in P&L\n→ Revalued model → recognised in OCI (reversal of prior OCI charge) or P&L (if prior impairment was in P&L)\n→ After reversal: adjust depreciation going forward\n\n(b) CGU reversal:\n→ Allocate reversal PRO RATA to assets (EXCEPT goodwill) based on carrying amounts\n→ Each asset's CA not increased above LOWER of:\n   (i) its RA\n   (ii) CA had no impairment been recognised (net of dep)\n→ Excess → reallocated pro rata to remaining assets\n\n(c) Goodwill:\n→ IMPAIRMENT LOSS ON GOODWILL CANNOT BE REVERSED — EVER.\n\n📌 Reversal ceiling = CA that would have existed (net of dep) HAD NO IMPAIRMENT been recognised." },

  { id:32, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Goodwill on Partial Disposal & Rolling Forward\n\nHow is goodwill derecognised when PART of a CGU is disposed?\n\nWhen can previous period's recoverable amount be ROLLED FORWARD?",
    back:"Goodwill on partial disposal:\n→ Goodwill associated with disposed operation → included in carrying amount of disposed operation\n→ Measured on basis of RELATIVE VALUES of:\n   (i) Operation disposed of, and\n   (ii) Portion of CGU retained\n→ Unless entity can demonstrate another method better reflects associated goodwill\n\nExample: Entity sells operation for ₹100; RA of retained portion = ₹300.\nTotal value = ₹400. Goodwill on disposed = 100/400 = 25% of total goodwill.\n\nRolling Forward (previous calculation reused):\nPermitted only if ALL 3 criteria met:\n(a) UNCHANGED CGU: assets/liabilities have not changed significantly since last calculation\n(b) SUBSTANTIAL HEADROOM: last RA exceeded CA by substantial margin\n(c) REMOTE LIKELIHOOD: likelihood that current RA < CA is remote\n\n📌 If any of the 3 criteria is NOT met → fresh calculation required.\n📌 This provision reduces cost of annual goodwill impairment testing." },

  { id:33, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Quick Fire\n\n1. Recoverable amount = ___\n2. VIU discount rate must be a ___ rate\n3. VIU cash flow projections: max period = ___\n4. Impairment allocated to goodwill: ___ (first/last?)\n5. Goodwill impairment: reversible? ___\n6. Three assets tested annually: ___",
    back:"1. Recoverable amount = HIGHER of (FVLCD) and (Value in Use)\n\n2. VIU discount rate = PRE-TAX rate (time value + asset-specific risks)\n\n3. VIU cash flow projections: max 5 YEARS (unless longer justified by track record)\n\n4. Impairment allocated to goodwill: FIRST (before other assets in CGU)\n\n5. Goodwill impairment: NO — NEVER reversible\n\n6. Three assets tested annually:\n   • Intangible with INDEFINITE useful life\n   • Intangible NOT YET AVAILABLE for use\n   • Goodwill from business combination\n\nBonus:\n→ Partial goodwill (NCI at proportionate share) → GROSS UP for impairment test\n→ Only parent's share of goodwill impairment recognised in CFS\n→ Corporate assets tested in context of CGU or group of CGUs (never in isolation)" },

  { id:34, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Formula Card\n\n1. Impairment Loss formula\n2. Revised Depreciation after Impairment\n3. Reversal ceiling formula\n\nWith a worked example for reversal ceiling.",
    back:"1. Impairment Loss:\nIL = Carrying Amount − Recoverable Amount\n(Recognise only when CA > RA)\n\n2. Recoverable Amount:\nRA = MAX (Fair Value Less Costs of Disposal, Value in Use)\n\n3. Revised Depreciation after Impairment:\nNew Dep = (Revised CA − Residual Value) ÷ Remaining Useful Life\n\nExample: Revised CA = ₹10,000; Residual = ₹500; Remaining life = 5 yrs\nNew Dep = (10,000 − 500) ÷ 5 = ₹1,900 per annum\n\n4. Reversal Ceiling:\nMax CA after reversal =\nHistorical Cost − Accumulated dep AS IF no impairment had ever been recognised\n\nExample:\nCost = ₹3,20,000 | Life = 20 years | Impairment at Year 4\nCA had no impairment = ₹3,20,000 − (₹3,20,000/20 × 4) = ₹3,20,000 − ₹64,000 = ₹2,56,000\n→ Reversal cannot increase CA above ₹2,56,000" },

  { id:35, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Disclosure Requirements\n\nWhat must be disclosed when an impairment loss or reversal has been recognised?",
    back:"For each material impairment loss or reversal:\n1. Events and circumstances leading to recognition\n2. Amount of IL or reversal\n3. Class of asset or description of CGU and segment\n4. Whether RA = FVLCD or VIU\n5. If FVLCD → valuation technique and key assumptions\n6. If VIU → discount rate(s) used in current and prior estimate\n\nFor CGUs with significant goodwill or indefinite-life intangibles:\n7. Carrying amount of goodwill allocated to the CGU\n8. Carrying amount of indefinite-life intangibles allocated\n9. Basis of RA determination (VIU or FVLCD)\n10. Key assumptions in cash flow projections\n11. Management's approach to each key assumption\n12. Period over which CFs projected and justification if > 5 years\n13. Growth rate used beyond budget period + justification\n14. Discount rate(s) applied\n15. Sensitivity — if reasonably possible change would cause impairment\n\nAggregate disclosures required even if no individual impairment is material." },

  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // IND AS 105 – HELD FOR SALE & DISCONTINUED OPS
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  { id:36, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Objective & Scope\n\nWhat are the 2 core objectives?\nWhich assets are scoped OUT of MEASUREMENT provisions?",
    back:"Two core objectives:\n1. Accounting for non-current assets (or disposal groups) HELD FOR SALE\n   → Measurement: lower of CA and FVLCTS\n   → Presentation: separately in balance sheet as CURRENT asset\n\n2. Accounting for DISCONTINUED OPERATIONS\n   → Results presented as single amount in P&L, separately from continuing operations\n\nScoped out of MEASUREMENT provisions only:\n(Still classified as HFS / in disclosure scope)\n→ Deferred tax assets (Ind AS 12)\n→ Financial assets (Ind AS 109)\n→ Biological assets at FV less costs to sell (Ind AS 41)\n→ Contractual rights (Ind AS 104)\n→ Employee benefit assets (Ind AS 19)\n\n📌 Ind AS 105 applies to NON-CURRENT assets only when sold individually.\n📌 A CURRENT asset sold individually → NEVER classified as HFS under Ind AS 105.\n📌 Current assets forming part of a DISPOSAL GROUP → included in the group." },

  { id:37, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Key Definitions\n\nDefine:\n• Non-current asset\n• Disposal group\n• Discontinued operation\n• Highly probable\n• Firm purchase commitment",
    back:"Non-current asset: Asset NOT meeting definition of current asset (not realisable within 12 months / operating cycle, not primarily for trading).\n\nDisposal group: Group of assets to be disposed TOGETHER IN A SINGLE TRANSACTION + directly associated liabilities. May be a CGU, single CGU, or part of CGU.\n→ Includes goodwill if CGU to which goodwill allocated (Ind AS 36).\n\nDiscontinued operation: COMPONENT of entity that either has been disposed of OR classified as HFS AND represents:\n(a) Separate major line of business or geographical area, OR\n(b) Part of coordinated plan to dispose of such, OR\n(c) Subsidiary acquired EXCLUSIVELY WITH A VIEW TO RESALE\n\nHighly probable: Significantly more likely than probable. (Probable = more likely than not.)\n\nFirm purchase commitment: Legally enforceable agreement with UNRELATED party; specifies all significant terms (price, timing); includes sufficient disincentive for non-performance." },

  { id:38, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Classification as Held for Sale\n\nState the 2 KEY REQUIREMENTS.\nList the 5 criteria for HIGHLY PROBABLE.",
    back:"2 KEY REQUIREMENTS:\n1. AVAILABLE FOR IMMEDIATE SALE in its present condition\n   (On terms usual and customary for sales of such assets)\n2. SALE IS HIGHLY PROBABLE\n\n5 Criteria for HIGHLY PROBABLE:\n(1) Appropriate level of management COMMITTED TO PLAN to sell\n(2) ACTIVE PROGRAMME to locate a buyer has been initiated\n(3) Asset actively MARKETED at price REASONABLE relative to current FV\n(4) Sale expected to be completed within ONE YEAR from date of classification\n(5) SIGNIFICANT CHANGES OR WITHDRAWAL from the plan are unlikely\n\nAdditional: Shareholders' approval (if required in jurisdiction) must be considered.\n\n📌 'Available for immediate sale' does NOT mean immediate transfer — usual customary terms (e.g., time to vacate a building) are acceptable.\n\n📌 Asset being REFURBISHED to enhance value → NOT available for immediate sale.\n\n📌 If sold individually, Ind AS 105 applies ONLY to NON-CURRENT assets." },

  { id:39, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – One-Year Rule Exceptions\n\nThe normal rule: sale must complete within ONE YEAR of classification. State the 2 general conditions AND 3 specific circumstances where beyond one year is acceptable.",
    back:"General conditions (BOTH must be met):\n(i) Delay caused by EVENTS OR CIRCUMSTANCES BEYOND entity's control\n(ii) SUFFICIENT EVIDENCE entity remains committed to selling plan\n\n3 Specific circumstances:\n\n1. Buyer requires LONGER PERIOD for regulatory/other approvals\n→ Entity has firm purchase commitment AND active programme\n→ Example: Mining entity committed to sell; regulatory approval takes > 1 year; firm commitment highly probable within 1 year\n\n2. Unexpected CONDITIONS raised by buyer or regulatory body requiring ADDITIONAL TIME\n→ Entity actively RESPONDS to resolve conditions\n→ Expected to resolve within reasonable period\n→ Example: Firm commitment obtained but buyer inspection reveals environmental damage; entity making good the damage\n\n3. Assets/liabilities must be SEPARATED from other assets/liabilities before legal sale\n→ Entity has firm commitment AND active programme\n\n📌 These are NARROW exceptions. If conditions not met → asset reclassified out of HFS.\n📌 Market conditions deteriorating + no reasonable offers + price reduced → still qualifies if entity continues to actively market at reasonable price." },

  { id:40, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Assets to be Abandoned\n\nCan assets to be ABANDONED be classified as held for sale?\nWhat about assets TEMPORARILY taken out of use?",
    back:"Assets to be ABANDONED:\n→ CANNOT be classified as held for sale\n→ Reason: CA recovered through CONTINUING USE, not sale\n→ Exception: If disposal group to be abandoned meets criteria for DISCONTINUED OPERATION → disclosure requirements apply\n\nAssets to be abandoned include:\n• Assets to be used to end of economic life\n• Assets to be CLOSED rather than sold\n\nAssets TEMPORARILY taken out of use:\n→ CANNOT be classified as abandoned\n→ Example: Factory idle due to low demand but maintained in workable condition and expected to restart → neither abandoned nor HFS\n→ Depreciation CONTINUES (CA recovered through future use)\n\nSummary:\n| Situation | HFS? | Depreciation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Held for sale (criteria met) | ✅ Yes | STOPS |\n| To be abandoned | ❌ No | Continues |\n| Temporarily idle | ❌ No | Continues |" },

  { id:41, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Measurement of Assets Held for Sale\n\nAt what amount are non-current assets classified as HFS measured?\nWhat happens to DEPRECIATION?\nWhat if sale > 1 year away?",
    back:"Measurement: LOWER of:\n(1) CARRYING AMOUNT (measured per applicable Ind AS immediately before classification)\n(2) FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL (FVLCTS)\n\nIf FVLCTS < CA → write-down to FVLCTS → IMPAIRMENT LOSS in P&L\nIf FVLCTS > CA → no write-up\n\nFor newly acquired disposal group as part of business combination:\n→ Measured at FVLCTS\n\nDepreciation/Amortisation:\n→ CEASES when asset classified as held for sale\n→ Interest & other expenses of disposal group LIABILITIES → continue to accrue\n\nIf sale expected BEYOND one year:\n→ Costs to sell → measured at PRESENT VALUE\n→ Increase in PV of costs to sell → presented as FINANCING COST\n\n📌 Cessation of depreciation is a critical distinguishing feature.\n📌 The asset is first measured per applicable Ind AS IMMEDIATELY BEFORE classification, then compared to FVLCTS." },

  { id:42, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Subsequent Measurement & Reversal\n\nHow is the asset remeasured at subsequent reporting dates?\nCan a GAIN be recognised? Under what limit?",
    back:"Subsequent measurement:\n→ Reassessed at each reporting date\n→ Asset continues at LOWER of CA and FVLCTS\n→ Further write-down if FVLCTS decreases → additional impairment in P&L\n\nReversal / Gain recognition:\n→ If FVLCTS INCREASES after previous write-down:\n→ Gain may be recognised, BUT limited to CUMULATIVE IMPAIRMENT LOSSES previously recognised under:\n   • Ind AS 105 (HFS impairment), AND\n   • Ind AS 36 (prior impairment before HFS classification)\n→ Any gain above cumulative losses → NOT recognised\n\nFor disposal groups:\n→ Scoped-out assets (Ind AS 109, 12, 2, 19) → remeasured per own standards BEFORE comparing disposal group FVLCTS\n→ Impairment allocated to in-scope assets in order:\n   (i) First reduce GOODWILL of disposal group to zero\n   (ii) Then pro rata to other non-current assets in measurement scope\n→ Scoped-out assets NOT allocated any impairment\n\n📌 On actual sale → full gain/loss on disposal recognised normally in P&L." },

  { id:43, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Reclassification Out of HFS\n\nAn asset classified as HFS no longer meets the criteria. How is it remeasured on reclassification?",
    back:"Remeasurement on reclassification (criteria no longer met):\n\nAsset measured at LOWER of:\n(1) CA BEFORE HFS classification, ADJUSTED for:\n   → Depreciation/amortisation that WOULD HAVE BEEN recognised had asset NOT been classified as HFS (notional depreciation catch-up)\n   → Any revaluations that would have been recognised\n(2) RECOVERABLE AMOUNT at the date of decision not to sell\n\nRecognition:\n→ Adjustment included in P&L from CONTINUING OPERATIONS in the period criteria no longer met\n→ Same caption as gains/losses on HFS items (not meeting discontinued operations definition)\n\nIf previously part of DISCONTINUED OPERATION:\n→ Results previously classified as discontinued → reclassified as CONTINUING OPERATIONS\n→ Prior period comparative P&L → RESTATED\n\n📌 Entity cannot 'enjoy' the depreciation holiday — on reclassification, asset brought down as if depreciation had continued normally.\n📌 Lower of (adjusted CA) and (recoverable amount) prevents windfall gains on reclassification." },

  { id:44, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Presentation in the Balance Sheet\n\nHow are HFS assets presented? How are liabilities of a disposal group presented?",
    back:"Presentation of assets:\n→ Presented SEPARATELY from other assets in balance sheet\n→ Classified as CURRENT ASSETS\n→ Major classes of assets → disclosed separately in balance sheet or notes\n\nPresentation of liabilities:\n→ Presented SEPARATELY from other liabilities\n→ Must NOT be OFFSET against assets (cannot show as single net amount)\n→ Major classes → disclosed separately in balance sheet or notes\n\nException: Newly acquired subsidiary classified as HFS on acquisition → major class disclosure not required\n\nOther rules:\n→ Prior period comparative balance sheet NOT reclassified to show HFS classification\n→ Any cumulative income/expense in OCI relating to HFS asset → presented separately\n\n📌 Summary:\n• Assets → separate line, current assets section ✅\n• Liabilities → separate line, not offset against assets ✅\n• Prior period BS → NOT restated ❌\n• Prior period P&L (discontinued ops) → RESTATED ✅" },

  { id:45, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Loss of Control in a Subsidiary\n\nAn entity commits to a sale plan involving LOSS OF CONTROL of a subsidiary. What classification and presentation rules apply?",
    back:"When committed to sale plan involving LOSS OF CONTROL:\n→ ALL assets and liabilities of that subsidiary must be classified as HELD FOR SALE\n→ Applies REGARDLESS of whether entity retains a non-controlling interest after sale\n\nClassification criteria: Standard HFS criteria still apply:\n→ Available for immediate sale, sale is highly probable, completion within 1 year\n\nPresentation in consolidated balance sheet:\n→ All assets of subsidiary → single line 'Assets classified as held for sale' (current assets)\n→ All liabilities → single line 'Liabilities directly associated with assets classified as held for sale'\n→ Assets and liabilities presented SEPARATELY (NOT netted)\n\nPartial disposal (NO loss of control):\n→ Only individual assets/liabilities that individually meet criteria are classified as HFS\n→ Full subsidiary not classified\n\n📌 Key trigger = LOSS OF CONTROL, not just any sale of shares.\n📌 Even if some assets/liabilities of subsidiary are scoped out of measurement → still classified in disposal group and presented as HFS." },

  { id:46, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Discontinued Operations: Definition & P&L Presentation\n\nWhat qualifies as a discontinued operation?\nHow are its results presented in P&L?",
    back:"Discontinued operation: COMPONENT of entity that either has been disposed of OR classified as HFS AND represents:\n(a) Separate MAJOR LINE OF BUSINESS or geographical area, OR\n(b) Part of SINGLE COORDINATED PLAN to dispose of such, OR\n(c) Subsidiary acquired EXCLUSIVELY WITH A VIEW TO RESALE\n\nComponent = operations and cash flows clearly distinguishable operationally and for financial reporting from rest of entity.\n\nP&L Presentation:\n→ SINGLE AMOUNT on face of P&L comprising total of:\n   • Post-tax P&L from discontinued operation\n   • Post-tax gain/loss on disposal (or remeasurement to FVLCTS)\n\n→ ANALYSIS of this single amount → disclosed in NOTES or in P&L:\n   • Revenue, expenses, pre-tax P&L\n   • Related income tax expense\n   • Gain/loss on disposal/remeasurement + related income tax\n\n→ Comparative P&L: MUST BE RE-PRESENTED to show discontinued operations separately\n   (Even if not classified as discontinued in prior period)\n\n📌 Single-line presentation keeps continuing operations 'clean' for analysis." },

  { id:47, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – What Does NOT Qualify as a Discontinued Operation?\n\nGive examples of situations that do NOT qualify, even if significant.",
    back:"Does NOT qualify (fails to meet component/major line test):\n\n1. Winding down while COMPLETING EXISTING CONTRACTS:\n→ Group closes engineering contracting segment\n→ No new contracts, but existing contracts being completed\n→ During wind-down period → still earning revenue → CONTINUING OPERATION\n→ Only qualifies as discontinued ONCE the final contract is completed\n\n2. Shifting production location:\n→ Moving factory from one state to another\n→ Same line of business continues → NOT a separate major line or geographic area\n\n3. Eliminating ONE PRODUCT LINE within a segment:\n→ Discontinuing a product, but the segment continues\n→ NOT a 'separate major line of business'\n\n4. Partial disposal NOT involving loss of control:\n→ Selling a 10% stake (retaining 60% control)\n→ NOT a discontinued operation\n\n📌 Key two-part test:\n(1) Component being DISPOSED OF (sold or HFS)? AND\n(2) Does it represent a SEPARATE MAJOR LINE or geographical area?\nBoth required simultaneously." },

  { id:48, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Comparative Restatement\n\nWhat comparative restatement is required for DISCONTINUED OPERATIONS in P&L?\nIs there comparative restatement in the BALANCE SHEET?",
    back:"PROFIT AND LOSS — Comparative RESTATEMENT REQUIRED:\n→ When component classified as discontinued in CURRENT period → re-present prior period comparative P&L to show discontinued operations as SINGLE AMOUNT (separate from continuing operations)\n→ Applies even if NOT classified as discontinued in prior period\n→ Purpose: allows users to see 'clean' continuing operations for both periods (comparability)\n\nBALANCE SHEET — NO Comparative Restatement:\n→ Non-current assets/disposal groups classified as HFS → NOT reclassified in prior period balance sheets\n→ Appear as separate line items ONLY from the period of first classification\n→ Exception: applicable Ind AS requires restatement (rare)\n\nCash flow statement:\n→ No specific requirement to restate comparative cash flows\n→ Disclosure of cash flows from discontinued operations in notes is required\n\n📌 Summary:\n• P&L comparatives: RESTATED ✅\n• Balance sheet comparatives: NOT restated ❌\n• Cash flows: Disclosure in notes ✅" },

  { id:49, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Held for Distribution to Owners\n\nWhat is held for distribution? How does it differ from held for sale?",
    back:"Held for distribution to owners:\n→ Entity intends to distribute asset to its owners (shareholders) — NOT sell to third party\n\nClassification criteria (same as HFS, adapted):\n→ Available for IMMEDIATE DISTRIBUTION in present condition\n→ Distribution highly probable:\n   (1) Management committed to plan\n   (2) Shareholders' approval obtained (if required)\n   (3) Distribution expected within ONE YEAR\n\nMeasurement:\n→ LOWER of (CA) and (FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO DISTRIBUTE)\n   [NOT 'costs to sell' — different concept]\n\nCosts to distribute = incremental costs directly attributable to distribution, excluding finance costs and income tax.\n\nDepreciation: CEASES on classification as held for distribution.\n\nPresentation: Presented separately from other assets (similar to HFS).\n\nKey difference:\n| | Held for Sale | Held for Distribution |\n|---|---|---|\n| Recovery | Through SALE (cash) | Through DISTRIBUTION to owners |\n| Measurement | Lower of CA and FVLCTS | Lower of CA and FVLCTD |\n| Acquirer | Third party | Entity's own owners |" },

  { id:50, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Ind AS 105 vs AS 24: Key Differences\n\nState 4 key differences between Ind AS 105 and old AS 24 (Discontinuing Operations).",
    back:"1. Scope:\n   Ind AS 105 → covers BOTH held for sale assets AND discontinued operations as one standard\n   AS 24 → covered only discontinuing operations; no separate standard for HFS assets\n\n2. Definition:\n   Ind AS 105 → 'discontinued operation' = component already disposed of or classified as HFS (binary)\n   AS 24 → 'discontinuing operation' = ongoing process; disclosures from point of initial disclosure\n\n3. Measurement:\n   Ind AS 105 → explicit measurement at lower of CA and FVLCTS; cessation of depreciation\n   AS 24 → no specific measurement requirements for assets to be sold\n\n4. P&L Presentation:\n   Ind AS 105 → single line item on face of P&L (post-tax)\n   AS 24 → no specific single-line presentation requirement\n\n5. Comparative restatement:\n   Ind AS 105 → prior period comparative P&L MUST be restated\n   AS 24 → no mandatory comparative restatement\n\n6. Abandonment:\n   Ind AS 105 → assets to be abandoned CANNOT be classified as HFS (may meet discontinued criteria)\n   AS 24 → abandonment could qualify as a discontinuing operation" },

  { id:51, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Formula Card\n\nA property: cost ₹4,70,000, life 13 years (SL), acquired 1 April 20X1.\nOn 1 April 20X4 classified as HFS. FVLCTS at 31 March 20X4 = ₹1,00,000.\nOn 31 March 20X5 FVLCTS = ₹85,000.\nSold 30 Sept 20X5 for ₹90,000.\n\nCalculate: (1) CA before classification, (2) Impairment on classification, (3) Position at 31 March 20X5, (4) Gain on sale.",
    back:"Annual depreciation = ₹4,70,000 ÷ 13 = ₹36,154\n\n(1) CA immediately before classification (end of Year 3 = 31 March 20X4):\nCA = ₹4,70,000 − (3 × ₹36,154) = ₹4,70,000 − ₹1,08,462 = ₹3,61,538 ≈ ₹3,62,000\n\n(2) Impairment on classification (1 April 20X4):\nFVLCTS = ₹1,00,000; CA = ₹3,62,000\nImpairment = ₹3,62,000 − ₹1,00,000 = ₹2,62,000 → recognised in P&L\nAsset carried at ₹1,00,000\n\nNote: Depreciation STOPS from date of HFS classification.\n\n(3) 31 March 20X5:\nFVLCTS falls to ₹85,000\nAdditional impairment = ₹1,00,000 − ₹85,000 = ₹15,000 → P&L\nAsset carried at ₹85,000\n\n(4) Sale 30 Sept 20X5 at ₹90,000:\nGain = ₹90,000 − ₹85,000 = ₹5,000 → recognised in P&L\n(Within cumulative impairment loss = ₹2,77,000; gain ₹5,000 is within this limit)" },

  { id:52, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Quick Fire\n\n1. HFS assets measured at: ___\n2. Depreciation on HFS assets: ___ (continues/stops)\n3. HFS assets in balance sheet: presented as ___ assets\n4. P&L — discontinued operations shown as: ___\n5. Asset to be ABANDONED: ___ (can/cannot) be HFS\n6. Comparative balance sheet: ___ restated\n7. Comparative P&L: ___ restated",
    back:"1. HFS assets: LOWER OF carrying amount AND FVLCTS\n\n2. Depreciation: STOPS on classification as HFS\n\n3. HFS in balance sheet: CURRENT assets (separately from other assets)\n\n4. P&L — discontinued ops: SINGLE AMOUNT (post-tax total of P&L + gain/loss on disposal)\n\n5. Asset to be abandoned: CANNOT be classified as HFS\n\n6. Comparative balance sheet: NOT restated\n\n7. Comparative P&L: RESTATED to show discontinued operations separately\n\nBonus:\n→ Assets & liabilities of disposal group → cannot be offset (shown GROSS)\n→ 'Component' = operations and CFs clearly distinguishable from rest of entity\n→ Highly probable = significantly more likely than probable\n→ Loss of control in subsidiary → ALL assets & liabilities of subsidiary classified as HFS\n→ Interest on liabilities of disposal group → continues to accrue after HFS classification" },

  // PRACTICAL – IND AS 2
  { id:53, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Practical: By-Product NRV & Joint Cost Allocation\n[Illustration 8 – Mars Ltd]\n\nCosts: Raw material ₹1,50,000 | Wages ₹90,000 | Fixed O/H ₹65,000 | Variable O/H ₹50,000\nOutput: MP1 – 5,000 units | MP2 – 4,000 units | BP – 2,000 units | Scrap realised ₹5,000\nClosing stock: MP1 – 250 units | MP2 – 100 units\nMarket price: MP1 @ ₹60/unit | MP2 @ ₹50/unit | BP @ ₹20/unit\nSeparate processing (BP): ₹8,000 | Packing (BP): ₹2,000\n\nCalculate closing stock values of MP1 and MP2.",
    back:"Step 1 – NRV of By-product BP:\nSelling price: 2,000 × ₹20 = ₹40,000\nLess: Processing ₹8,000 + Packing ₹2,000 = (₹10,000)\nNRV of BP = ₹30,000\n\nStep 2 – Joint cost for allocation:\nTotal costs (1,50,000+90,000+65,000+50,000) = 3,55,000\nLess NRV of BP (30,000) and scrap (5,000) = (35,000)\nJoint cost = 3,20,000\n\nStep 3 – Allocation on relative sales value (ratio 3:2):\n             MP1         MP2\nUnits        5,000       4,000\nPrice        ₹60         ₹50\nSales value  3,00,000    2,00,000\nAllocation   1,92,000    1,28,000\nCost/unit    ₹38.40      ₹32.00\n\nStep 4 – Closing stock:\nMP1: 250 × ₹38.40 = ₹9,600\nMP2: 100 × ₹32.00 = ₹3,200" },

  { id:54, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Practical: FIFO vs Weighted Average\n[Illustration 11 – Mercury Ltd]\n\nMercury Ltd periodic inventory system 20X1-20X2:\nApril     Opening inventory  200 units @ ₹10 = ₹2,000\nMay       Purchase           50 units @ ₹11 = ₹550\nSeptember Purchase          400 units @ ₹12 = ₹4,800\nFebruary  Purchase          350 units @ ₹14 = ₹4,900\nTotal                       1,000 units      ₹12,250\n\nPhysical inventory at 31.3.20X2: 400 units.\nCalculate closing inventory and cost of sales under (a) FIFO and (b) Weighted Average.",
    back:"(a) FIFO Method:\nClosing inventory (400 units – most recent purchases first):\n350 units @ ₹14 = ₹4,900\n50 units @ ₹12  = ₹600\nClosing inventory = ₹5,500\nCost of sales = ₹12,250 − ₹5,500 = ₹6,750\n\n(b) Weighted Average:\nWA cost = ₹12,250 ÷ 1,000 = ₹12.25 per unit\nClosing inventory = 400 × ₹12.25 = ₹4,900\nCost of sales = ₹12,250 − ₹4,900 = ₹7,350\n\nComparison:\n                  FIFO      Wtd Avg\nClosing inventory ₹5,500    ₹4,900\nCost of sales     ₹6,750    ₹7,350\n\nIn a RISING price environment: FIFO gives higher closing inventory and lower COGS.\nLIFO is NOT permitted under Ind AS 2." },

  { id:55, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 2", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 2 – Practical: NRV Item-by-Item vs Group Basis\n[Illustration 17 – Sun Pharma Ltd]\n\nItem   Cost    NRV\nA      2,000   1,900\nB      5,000   5,100\nC      4,400   4,550\nD      3,200   2,990\nTotal  14,600  14,540\n\nCalculate inventory value on (a) item-by-item basis and (b) group basis.\nWhich is CORRECT as per Ind AS 2? What is the write-down?",
    back:"(a) ITEM-BY-ITEM BASIS (CORRECT per Ind AS 2):\n\nItem  Cost   NRV    Lower    Basis\nA     2,000  1,900  1,900    NRV < cost → write down ₹100\nB     5,000  5,100  5,000    Cost < NRV → no write down\nC     4,400  4,550  4,400    Cost < NRV → no write down\nD     3,200  2,990  2,990    NRV < cost → write down ₹210\nTotal                14,290\n\nTotal write-down = ₹100 + ₹210 = ₹310\n\n(b) GROUP BASIS (NOT permitted — shown only to explain concept):\nTotal cost (14,600) vs Total NRV (14,540)\nGroup value = ₹14,540\n\nInd AS 2 requires item-by-item → correct answer is ₹14,290.\nGroup basis (₹14,540) overstates inventory by allowing surpluses on B & C to offset write-downs on A & D." },

  // PRACTICAL – IND AS 36
  { id:56, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Practical: Impairment Loss Calculation\n[Illustration 4 – Jupiter Ltd]\n\nJupiter Ltd has a furnace on the balance sheet at ₹250 lakh (31 March 20X1).\nAt that date: Value in Use = ₹200 lakh | Fair value = ₹200 lakh | Cost of disposal = ₹13 lakh.\n\nCalculate the impairment loss.",
    back:"Step 1 – FVLCD:\nFVLCD = Fair value − Cost of disposal = ₹200L − ₹13L = ₹187 lakh\n\nStep 2 – Recoverable Amount:\nRA = Higher of FVLCD and VIU = Higher of ₹187L and ₹200L = ₹200 lakh\n\nStep 3 – Impairment Loss:\nIL = Carrying Amount − Recoverable Amount = ₹250L − ₹200L = ₹50 lakh\n\nRecognition: ₹50 lakh recognised immediately in Profit or Loss (cost model asset).\n\nKey points:\nFVLCD (₹187L) < VIU (₹200L) → VIU is used as RA, which reduces impairment.\nFVLCD ≠ Fair Value. Always deduct costs of disposal.\nAfter recognition: revised CA = ₹200L; depreciation adjusted going forward." },

  { id:57, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – Practical: CGU Impairment + Reversal\n[Illustration 10 – Venus Ltd / Saturn Ltd]\n\nVenus Ltd acquired 100% Saturn Ltd on 1 April 20X1 for ₹4,00,000.\nFV of identifiable assets = ₹3,20,000 | Goodwill = ₹80,000 | Life 20 years SL, no residual.\n\n31 March 20X3 (Year 2): Govt cancelled licences. VIU = ₹2,12,000.\n31 March 20X5 (Year 4): Licences reinstated. VIU = ₹3,04,000 | FVLCD = ₹2,90,000.\n\nCalculate: (a) Impairment at 31.3.20X3 and allocation, (b) Reversal at 31.3.20X5.",
    back:"(a) Impairment at 31 March 20X3 (Year 2):\n\nCGU Carrying Amounts:\nGoodwill = ₹80,000 (not depreciated)\nOther assets = ₹3,20,000 − (₹16,000 × 2) = ₹2,88,000\nTotal CGU CA = ₹3,68,000\n\nRA = VIU = ₹2,12,000\nImpairment Loss = ₹3,68,000 − ₹2,12,000 = ₹1,56,000\n\nAllocation:\n1st → Goodwill fully eliminated: (₹80,000)\n2nd → Other assets: (₹76,000)\nRevised CA of other assets: ₹2,88,000 − ₹76,000 = ₹2,12,000\n\n(b) Reversal at 31 March 20X5 (Year 4):\n\nCA of other assets at 31.3.20X5:\nRevised dep = ₹2,12,000 ÷ 18 years × 2 ≈ ₹24,000 (rounded)\nCA = ₹2,12,000 − ₹24,000 = ₹1,88,000\n\nReversal CEILING (CA had no impairment at Year 4):\n₹3,20,000 − (₹16,000 × 4) = ₹3,20,000 − ₹64,000 = ₹2,56,000\n\nRA at reversal = max(₹3,04,000, ₹2,90,000) = ₹3,04,000\nReversal = min(₹3,04,000, ₹2,56,000) − ₹1,88,000 = ₹68,000\n\nNew CA = ₹2,56,000 | New annual dep = ₹2,56,000 ÷ 16 = ₹16,000\nGoodwill impairment ₹80,000 → CANNOT be reversed." },

  { id:58, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 36", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 36 – AS 28 vs Ind AS 36\n\nState 4 key differences between Ind AS 36 and old AS 28.",
    back:"1. Fair Value Measurement Standard:\nInd AS 36 → uses Ind AS 113 Fair Value Measurement to determine FV in FVLCD\nAS 28 → no separate FV measurement standard; FV determined under AS 28 itself\n\n2. NCI Goodwill Grossing Up:\nInd AS 36 → specific guidance on grossing up partially recognised goodwill (partial goodwill method) before impairment test\nAS 28 → no such guidance\n\n3. Scope Exclusions:\nInd AS 36 → excludes assets per Ind AS 109, 12, 19, 41, 115, 117, 105 (new Ind AS framework)\nAS 28 → exclusions aligned to old AS framework equivalents\n\n4. Discount Rate Guidance:\nInd AS 36 → detailed guidance on surrogates (WACC, incremental borrowing rate) when asset-specific rate unavailable\nAS 28 → similar in principle but less detailed\n\n5. Reversal of goodwill impairment:\nInd AS 36 → PROHIBITS reversal of goodwill impairment — NEVER reversible\nAS 28 → ALLOWS reversal IF caused by a specific external event of exceptional nature not expected to recur AND subsequent external events reverse the effect of that event\n\n6. Annual impairment test:\nInd AS 36 → MANDATORY annual test for goodwill + indefinite-life intangibles + intangibles not yet available for use (regardless of indicators)\nAS 28 → does NOT require mandatory annual testing for goodwill; tests only when there is an INDICATION of impairment" },

  // PRACTICAL – IND AS 105
  { id:59, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Practical: Reclassification Out of HFS\n[Illustration 2 – S Ltd]\n\nS Ltd purchased property ₹6,00,000 on 1 April 20X1. Useful life 15 years SL.\n\n31 March 20X3 (Year 2): Classified as HFS.\nImpairment testing before classification: RA = ₹4,70,000 (impairment ₹50,000)\nFVLCTS = ₹4,60,000. Asset recorded at ₹4,60,000.\n\n31 March 20X4 (Year 3): Plan abandoned — HFS criteria no longer met.\nRecoverable amount at 31.3.20X4 = ₹5,00,000.\n\nCalculate: (a) P&L charges for year 31.3.20X3, (b) Value of property at 31.3.20X4.",
    back:"(a) 31 March 20X3 — Year of HFS Classification:\n\nCA before classification per Ind AS 16:\nCost                                  ₹6,00,000\nLess: Dep 2 years (6,00,000/15×2)     (₹80,000)\nLess: Impairment loss (5,20,000−4,70,000) (₹50,000)\nCA after impairment testing           ₹4,70,000\n\nOn HFS classification: Lower of CA (₹4,70,000) and FVLCTS (₹4,60,000) = ₹4,60,000\nAdditional HFS write-down = ₹10,000\n\nTotal charged to P&L in Year 20X3:\nDepreciation ₹40,000 + Impairment ₹60,000 (₹50,000 + ₹10,000) = ₹1,00,000\nProperty recorded at ₹4,60,000\n\n(b) 31 March 20X4 — Reclassification back:\n\nNotional depreciation catch-up (1 year):\nCA immediately before HFS = ₹4,70,000 (pre-HFS write-down CA)\nRemaining life = 13 years; Annual dep = ₹4,70,000 ÷ 13 = ₹36,154\nAdjusted CA = ₹4,70,000 − ₹36,154 = ₹4,33,846\n\nLower of adjusted CA (₹4,33,846) and RA (₹5,00,000) = ₹4,33,846\n\nAdjustment to P&L (continuing operations):\n₹4,60,000 − ₹4,33,846 = ₹26,154 charged to P&L" },

  { id:60, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 105", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 105 – Disclosures for HFS Assets & Discontinued Operations\n\nWhat must be disclosed for (a) non-current assets held for sale and (b) discontinued operations?",
    back:"(a) HFS non-current assets (or disposal groups):\n1. Description of the asset / disposal group\n2. Facts and circumstances of the sale; expected manner and timing\n3. Gain/loss on initial or subsequent write-down (if not on face of P&L → caption used)\n4. Reportable segment (Ind AS 108)\n5. If there is a CHANGE OF PLAN:\n   Description of facts/circumstances; effect on results\n\nNote: Prior period comparative BALANCE SHEET → NOT restated.\n\n(b) Discontinued operations:\n1. Description of the discontinued operation\n2. Segment in which reported\n3. Date and manner of disposal\n4. Gain/loss on disposal (before/after tax)\n5. Cash flows: Operating | Investing | Financing\n   (In notes or on face of cash flow statement)\n6. Revenue, expenses, pre-tax P&L for the period\n7. Related income tax expense\n8. Consideration received/receivable; net assets disposed of\n\nNote: Prior period comparative P&L → MUST be restated for discontinued operations." },

  // FR · Ind AS 16, 38 & 40
  // ── CONCEPT ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:61, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What is the Objective of Ind AS 16?\nWhat are the 4 items it does NOT apply to?",
    back:"Objective: Prescribe accounting treatment for PPE so that users can discern information about an entity's investment in PPE and changes in such investment.\n\nPrincipal Issues: Recognition of assets, determination of carrying amounts, depreciation charges and impairment losses.\n\n❌ Does NOT apply to:\n(a) PPE classified as Held for Sale (Ind AS 105)\n(b) Biological assets related to agricultural activity OTHER than bearer plants (Ind AS 41)\n(c) Exploration & evaluation assets (Ind AS 106)\n(d) Mineral rights & reserves (oil, gas, non-regenerative resources)\n\n✅ DOES apply to PPE used to DEVELOP or MAINTAIN assets in (b)–(d)\n\n📌 Entity accounting for investment property under Ind AS 40 → shall use COST MODEL of Ind AS 16 for owned investment property.",
    exam:false },

  { id:62, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"Define PPE. What are its 2 conditions?\nAlso define: Bearer Plant | Carrying Amount | Cost | Depreciable Amount | Residual Value | Useful Life",
    back:"PPE = Tangible items that:\n(a) Held for use in PRODUCTION / SUPPLY of goods/services, RENTAL to others, or ADMINISTRATIVE purposes; AND\n(b) Expected to be used during MORE than one period\n\nBearer Plant = Living plant used in agricultural produce production, expected to bear produce for more than one period, with REMOTE likelihood of sale as agricultural produce (except incidental scrap sales)\n\nCarrying Amount = Cost LESS Accumulated Depreciation LESS Accumulated Impairment Losses\n\nCost = Cash/cash equivalents paid OR Fair Value of consideration given to acquire/construct an asset\n\nDepreciable Amount = Cost (or substituted amount) LESS Residual Value\n\nResidual Value = Estimated amount obtainable from disposal NOW, if asset were already at end of its useful life (net of disposal costs)\n\nUseful Life = Period of availability for use OR number of production units expected\n\n📌 Impairment Loss = Carrying Amount exceeds Recoverable Amount\n📌 Recoverable Amount = HIGHER of (FV less costs of disposal) and (Value in Use)",
    exam:false },

  { id:63, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the 2 Recognition Criteria for PPE?\nHow are Spare Parts & Stand-by Equipment treated?\nWhat about safety/environmental PPE?",
    back:"Recognition Criteria (BOTH must be met):\n(a) It is PROBABLE that future economic benefits will flow to the entity; AND\n(b) The COST of the item can be MEASURED RELIABLY\n\nSpare Parts, Stand-by Equipment & Servicing Equipment:\n✅ Meets PPE definition → Recognized as PPE\n❌ Does NOT meet PPE definition → Classified as INVENTORY\n\nSafety / Environmental PPE:\n→ Qualifies even if NOT directly increasing future economic benefits of a specific existing asset\n→ Enables future economic benefits from OTHER assets\n→ Example: Chemical handling equipment installed to comply with environmental laws → recognized as asset because without it the entity cannot manufacture and sell chemicals\n→ Resulting carrying amount reviewed for impairment under Ind AS 36\n\nAggregation:\n→ Individually insignificant items (moulds, tools, dies) may be AGGREGATED\n→ Recognition criteria applied to the aggregate value\n\n📌 Both criteria must be met simultaneously — if either fails → cost goes to P&L",
    exam:false },

  { id:64, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Distinguish between the 3 types of Subsequent Costs under Ind AS 16:\n\n1. Repairs & Maintenance\n2. Replacement of Parts\n3. Major Inspection / Overhaul",
    back:"🔧 Repairs & Maintenance (Day-to-day servicing):\n→ NOT added to carrying amount\n→ Recognized in PROFIT OR LOSS as incurred\n→ Includes labour, consumables, cost of small parts\n\n🔩 Replacement of Parts:\n→ ADDED to carrying amount when BOTH recognition criteria are met\n→ OLD part's carrying amount DERECOGNIZED\n→ Example: Furnace relining, aircraft seats/galleys, interior walls of building\n\n🔍 Major Inspection / Overhaul:\n→ Cost recognized in CARRYING AMOUNT as a replacement if criteria satisfied\n→ PREVIOUS inspection cost DERECOGNIZED (even if not originally separately identified)\n→ If previous cost unknown → use estimated cost of a FUTURE similar inspection as proxy\n→ Example: Aircraft mandatory overhaul, ship dry-dock inspection every 5 years (must be capitalized)\n\n📌 KEY RULE: Only CAPITALIZE subsequent costs if BOTH recognition criteria are met\n📌 Ask: Does the cost RESTORE or ENHANCE future economic benefits beyond original assessment?\n📌 Day-to-day repairs merely MAINTAIN benefits → P&L",
    exam:true },

  { id:65, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the Cost Model and Revaluation Model?\nHow is Revaluation Surplus / Deficit treated?\nWhen is Revaluation Surplus transferred to Retained Earnings?",
    back:"📊 Cost Model:\nCarrying Amount = Cost − Accumulated Depreciation − Accumulated Impairment Losses\n\n🔄 Revaluation Model:\nCarrying Amount = FV at date of revaluation − Subsequent accumulated depreciation − Subsequent accumulated impairment losses\nRevaluations must be made with SUFFICIENT REGULARITY.\n\nTreatment of Surplus / Deficit:\n\nFIRST-TIME REVALUATION:\n↑ CA increases → OCI (Revaluation Surplus, in equity)\n↓ CA decreases → P&L (Revaluation Loss)\n\nSUBSEQUENT REVALUATION:\n↑ CA increases → First reverses previous P&L loss (recognize in P&L); remaining to OCI\n↓ CA decreases → First uses existing revaluation surplus in OCI; remaining to P&L\n\nTransfer of Revaluation Surplus to Retained Earnings:\n→ On DERECOGNITION → transfer whole surplus\n→ While in USE → transfer difference between (revalued dep. and historical cost dep.) each year\n→ Transfers NOT made through P&L\n\n📌 Revaluation must apply to ENTIRE CLASS of assets (no selective revaluation)\n📌 Rolling basis allowed if completed within short period and kept up to date\n📌 Frequency: Annual if volatile FV; every 3–5 years if changes are insignificant",
    exam:true },

  // ── FORMULA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:66, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 3 Components of Cost of PPE.\nList all Directly Attributable Costs.\nList all NON-Capitalizable Costs.",
    back:"3 Components of Cost:\n(a) Purchase price (incl. import duties + non-refundable taxes) LESS trade discounts & rebates\n(b) Directly Attributable Costs\n(c) Initial estimate of DISMANTLING & RESTORATION costs (Ind AS 37 provision)\n\n✅ Directly Attributable Costs:\n• Employee benefits directly from construction/acquisition of PPE\n• Site preparation costs\n• Initial delivery & handling costs\n• Installation & assembly costs\n• Professional fees\n• Testing costs NET of proceeds from items produced during testing\n\n❌ NOT Capitalizable (P&L):\n• Day-to-day repairs & maintenance\n• Cost of opening a new facility\n• Staff training costs / new product / service introduction costs\n• Administrative & general overhead costs\n• Initial operating losses\n• Costs of relocation or reorganization\n• Any cost incurred AFTER asset is in location & condition for intended use\n\n📌 Abnormal waste in self-construction → NEVER capitalized\n📌 Internal profits in self-construction → eliminated\n📌 Excess net proceeds from testing over testing cost → deducted from cost (NOT credited to P&L) — this is the Ind AS 16 carve-out vs IAS 16",
    exam:true },

  { id:67, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Two Methods for Accumulated Depreciation at Revaluation Date.\nWork through both with this example:\nCost ₹1,00,000 | Acc. Dep. ₹55,000 | Fair Value ₹65,000",
    back:"Carrying Amount before revaluation = 1,00,000 − 55,000 = ₹45,000\nFair Value = ₹65,000 → Surplus = ₹20,000\n\nMethod I — Depreciation Elimination Approach:\nStep 1: Eliminate accumulated depreciation\n  Acc. Dep. Dr. 55,000\n    To Asset Cost     55,000\n\nStep 2: Increase net asset to fair value\n  Asset Cost Dr. 20,000\n    To Revaluation Surplus 20,000\n\nFinal CA = 1,00,000 − 55,000 + 20,000 = ₹65,000 ✅\n\n──────────────────────────────\nMethod II — Restatement Approach:\nSurplus % = 20,000 / 45,000 = 44.44%\n\nEntry:\n  Asset (1,00,000 × 44.44%) Dr. 44,444\n    To Acc. Dep. (55,000 × 44.44%)  24,444\n    To Revaluation Surplus           20,000\n\nFinal CA = 1,00,000 − 55,000 + 44,444 − 24,444 = ₹65,000 ✅\n\n📌 Both methods give the SAME carrying amount of ₹65,000\n📌 Method I → accumulated depreciation becomes NIL after revaluation\n📌 Method II → both gross cost AND accumulated depreciation are restated proportionately",
    exam:true },

  { id:68, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Depreciation under Ind AS 16:\n(a) Allowed methods\n(b) When is depreciation ZERO?\n(c) When does depreciation CEASE?\n(d) How are changes in method / useful life treated?",
    back:"Allowed Methods:\n(a) Straight-Line Method (SLM) → Constant charge\n(b) Diminishing Balance Method → Decreasing charge\n(c) Units of Production → Based on expected use or output\n❌ Revenue-based depreciation → NOT appropriate\n\nDepreciation = ZERO when:\n→ Residual Value ≥ Carrying Amount (resumes only when RV falls below CA again)\n\nDepreciation CEASES at EARLIER of:\n(a) Date classified as Held for Sale (Ind AS 105)\n(b) Date derecognized\n\n📌 Does NOT cease when asset becomes IDLE or retired from active use (unless fully depreciated)\n📌 Under usage methods (units of production), charge CAN be zero when there is no production\n📌 Depreciation IS recognized even if Fair Value > Carrying Amount, as long as Residual Value < Carrying Amount\n📌 Repair & maintenance do NOT negate the need to depreciate\n\nChanges in Method / Useful Life / Residual Value:\n→ Treated as CHANGE IN ACCOUNTING ESTIMATE (Ind AS 8)\n→ Applied PROSPECTIVELY — no restatement of prior periods\n→ Reviewed at EACH YEAR-END",
    exam:true },

  // ── PRACTICAL ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:69, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: ABC Ltd. installs a new plant. Identify capitalizable costs:\n1. Plant cost (invoice + taxes) ₹25,00,000\n2. Delivery & handling ₹2,00,000\n3. Site preparation ₹6,00,000\n4. Consultancy fees ₹7,00,000\n5. Interest on deferred credit to supplier ₹2,00,000\n6. NPV of dismantling costs (7 yrs) ₹3,00,000\n7. Operating losses before commercial production ₹4,00,000",
    back:"✅ CAPITALIZABLE:\n1. Plant cost ₹25,00,000 ✅\n2. Delivery & handling ₹2,00,000 ✅\n3. Site preparation ₹6,00,000 ✅\n4. Consultancy fees ₹7,00,000 ✅\n6. NPV of dismantling costs ₹3,00,000 ✅\n\nTotal Capitalizable = ₹43,00,000\n\n❌ NOT Capitalizable:\n5. Interest on deferred credit ₹2,00,000 ❌\n→ Finance cost; plant is NOT a qualifying asset under Ind AS 23\n→ Recognized in P&L over the credit period\n\n7. Operating losses ₹4,00,000 ❌\n→ Post-recognition cost; asset was already ready for use\n→ Recognized in P&L\n\n📌 Dismantling costs (NPV) → ALWAYS part of cost as per Ind AS 37 provision\n📌 Interest to supplier on deferred terms ≠ borrowing costs under Ind AS 23 (unless the plant qualifies as a qualifying asset — generally it doesn't for short credit terms)\n📌 Operating losses before commercial production → P&L, never capitalized",
    exam:true },

  { id:70, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Revision of Useful Life\nAsset cost ₹10,000 | Useful life 10 years | Residual value ₹2,000.\nAfter 2 years, useful life revised to 4 REMAINING years.\nCalculate depreciation for Years 1, 2, and 3.",
    back:"Years 1 & 2 — Original Estimate:\nDepreciable Amount = 10,000 − 2,000 = ₹8,000\nAnnual Depreciation = 8,000 / 10 = ₹800 p.a.\n\nEnd of Year 2 Carrying Amount = 10,000 − (800 × 2) = ₹8,400\n\nYear 3 Onwards — Revised Estimate:\nRevised Depreciable Amount = 8,400 − 2,000 = ₹6,400\nRevised Annual Depreciation = 6,400 / 4 remaining years = ₹1,600 p.a.\n\n📊 Summary:\nYear 1: ₹800\nYear 2: ₹800\nYear 3 onwards: ₹1,600\n\n📌 Change in useful life = Change in Accounting Estimate (Ind AS 8) → PROSPECTIVE only\n📌 NO restatement of prior years\n📌 Formula for revised depreciation:\n  (Carrying Amount at revision date − Revised Residual Value) / Revised Remaining Life\n📌 Similarly, if residual value ≥ carrying amount → depreciation becomes zero until RV falls below CA",
    exam:true },

  { id:71, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: PPE on Deferred Payment\nProperty sale price = ₹1,00,00,000. Paid in 3 equal installments of ₹33,33,333 over 2 years. Implicit interest rate = 5.36% p.a.\nWhat is the cost of PPE? How is the difference treated?",
    back:"Key Rule: Cost = CASH PRICE EQUIVALENT at recognition date (i.e., present value of all payments)\n\nPV Calculation:\n1st installment (Day 1): 33,33,333 × 1.000 = ₹33,33,333\n2nd installment (Year 1): 33,33,333 × 0.949 = ₹31,63,333\n3rd installment (Year 2): 33,33,334 × 0.901 = ₹30,03,334\nCash Price Equivalent = ₹95,00,000\n\nJournal Entry on Day 1:\nPPE A/c                Dr. 95,00,000\n  To Bank A/c                   33,33,333\n  To Accounts Payable           61,66,667\n\nDifference = ₹1,00,00,000 − ₹95,00,000 = ₹5,00,000\n→ Recognized as INTEREST EXPENSE over the credit period (P&L)\n\nYear 1 Interest = 61,66,667 × 5.36% = ₹3,30,533 → P&L\nYear 2 Interest = 31,63,867 × 5.36% = ₹1,69,467 → P&L\n\n📌 Interest on deferred payment to supplier → FINANCE COST (P&L)\n📌 NOT capitalizable (asset is not a qualifying asset under Ind AS 23)\n📌 Settlement discount received → OTHER INCOME in P&L (NOT deducted from PPE cost)",
    exam:true },

  { id:72, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Exchange of Assets with Commercial Substance\nPluto Ltd.: Land & Building (CA ₹10M, FV ₹15M) exchanged for Private Jet (FV ₹20M) + ₹3M cash paid. Transaction has commercial substance.\nCompute cost of jet and profit on exchange. Pass journal entry.",
    back:"Rule: Exchange with commercial substance → Acquired asset measured at FV of asset GIVEN UP + any cash paid\n\nCost of Private Jet = FV of Land & Building given up + Cash paid\n= ₹15M + ₹3M = ₹18M\n\nProfit on Disposal = FV of asset given up − Carrying Amount\n= ₹15M − ₹10M = ₹5M\n\nJournal Entry:\nPPE (Private Jet)             Dr. 18,000\n  To PPE (Land & Building)           10,000\n  To Cash                             3,000\n  To Profit on Exchange of Assets     5,000\n\n📌 If NO commercial substance OR FV not reliably measurable:\n→ Measure at CARRYING AMOUNT of asset given up → NO profit/loss recognized\n\n📌 Commercial substance exists if:\n(a) Cash flow configuration changes (risk/timing/amount), OR\n(b) Entity-specific value changes significantly\n(c) AND difference is SIGNIFICANT relative to FV of assets exchanged\n\n📌 Gains on exchange of PPE → NOT classified as Revenue",
    exam:true },

  { id:73, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Change in Depreciation Method\nAsset cost ₹50,00,000. Method: 10% Reducing Balance for 3 years. At end of Year 3, entity switches to SLM with remaining useful life of 8 years.\nCalculate depreciation for Years 1–3 and Years 4–11.",
    back:"Years 1–3 (Reducing Balance @ 10%):\nYear 1: 50,00,000 × 10% = ₹5,00,000 | Closing: ₹45,00,000\nYear 2: 45,00,000 × 10% = ₹4,50,000 | Closing: ₹40,50,000\nYear 3: 40,50,000 × 10% = ₹4,05,000 | Closing: ₹36,45,000\n\nYear 4 onwards (SLM — Revised):\nCarrying Amount at end of Year 3 = ₹36,45,000\nRemaining Useful Life = 8 years (assumed residual value = 0)\nRevised Annual Depreciation = 36,45,000 / 8 = ₹4,55,625 p.a.\n\n(Years 4 to 11: ₹4,55,625 per annum)\n\n📌 Change in depreciation method = Change in Accounting Estimate (Ind AS 8) → PROSPECTIVE\n📌 No restatement of previous years\n📌 Formula: Revised Dep = Carrying Amount at change date / Remaining Useful Life (when RV = 0)\n📌 Entity selects method that MOST CLOSELY reflects the expected pattern of consumption of future economic benefits",
    exam:true },

  { id:74, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Decommissioning Liability — Cost Model\nH Ltd. buys PPE ₹100M. Decommissioning obligation PV = ₹2.32M [₹5M/(1.08)^10].\nAt end of Year 4, revised estimate = ₹8M. New PV = ₹5.04M [₹8M/(1.08)^6].\nExisting liability at Year 4 end = ₹3.15M.\nHow is the change accounted for? What is the new depreciation?",
    back:"Increase in Liability = 5.04 − 3.15 = ₹1.89M\n\nJournal Entry (Cost Model):\nPPE A/c                               Dr. ₹1.89M\n  To Provision for Decommissioning         ₹1.89M\n\nCarrying Amount of PPE at Year 4 end (before adjustment) = ₹61.39M\nRevised CA = 61.39 + 1.89 = ₹63.28M\nDepreciated over remaining 6 years: ₹63.28M / 6 = ₹10.55M p.a.\n\nCost Model Rules for changes:\n↑ Increase in liability → Added to COST of asset (then test for impairment — Ind AS 36)\n↓ Decrease in liability → Deducted from COST (CANNOT exceed carrying amount)\n   Decrease > CA → excess recognized as INCOME in P&L immediately\n\n📌 Periodic UNWINDING of discount → P&L as Finance Cost (NOT capitalizable under Ind AS 23)\n📌 After asset reaches end of useful life → ALL changes in liability → P&L immediately\n📌 Three things that change decommissioning liability:\n(a) Change in estimated cash outflows\n(b) Change in current market-based discount rate\n(c) Passage of time (unwinding of discount)",
    exam:true },

  // ── THEORY Q&A ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:75, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the Disclosure Requirements under Ind AS 16?\n(a) General disclosures for each PPE class\n(b) Required reconciliation items\n(c) Additional disclosures for Revalued assets",
    back:"General Disclosures (for each class of PPE):\n• Measurement bases for gross carrying amount\n• Depreciation methods used\n• Useful lives or depreciation rates used\n• Gross carrying amount + accumulated depreciation (+ impairment) at beginning & end of period\n\nReconciliation of Carrying Amount:\nAdditions | Held for Sale / other disposals | Business combinations | Revaluation changes | Impairment (OCI & P&L) | Impairment reversals | Depreciation | Exchange differences\n\nAdditional Required Disclosures:\n• Restrictions on title / PPE pledged as security\n• Contractual commitments to acquire PPE\n• Compensation from third parties for impaired/lost PPE\n• Depreciation charged during period (P&L or in cost of other assets)\n• Accumulated depreciation at end of period\n\nRevalued Assets — Additional:\n• Effective date of revaluation\n• Whether independent valuer was involved\n• Carrying amount had cost model been used\n• Revaluation surplus (change for period + restrictions on distribution)\n\n📌 Encouraged but NOT required: Temporarily idle PPE | Fully depreciated PPE still in use | PPE retired but not held for sale | FV of PPE when materially different from CA",
    exam:false },

  { id:76, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"How does Appendix A to Ind AS 16 deal with Changes in Decommissioning Liabilities?\nExplain treatment under BOTH Cost Model and Revaluation Model.",
    back:"COST MODEL — Changes in decommissioning liability:\n↑ Increase → ADDED to cost of PPE (then test for impairment — Ind AS 36)\n↓ Decrease → DEDUCTED from cost of PPE\n   • Cannot exceed carrying amount of asset\n   • If decrease > CA → excess recognized as INCOME in P&L immediately\n\nREVALUATION MODEL — Changes:\n↑ Increase → Adjusted against Revaluation Surplus (OCI); excess to P&L\n↓ Decrease → Recognized in Revaluation Reserve (OCI)\n   • If previous deficit charged to P&L → reverse that amount in P&L first\n   • If decrease > CA → excess = 'deemed revaluation' → P&L\n   • Change in revaluation surplus from decommissioning → separate line item in OCI (Ind AS 1)\n\nBoth Models — Common Rules:\n• After asset's useful life ends → ALL changes in liability → P&L immediately\n• Periodic unwinding of discount → P&L as Finance Cost\n• Capitalisation under Ind AS 23 → NOT permitted\n\n📌 Three events that change decommissioning liability:\n(a) Change in estimated cash outflows\n(b) Change in current market-based discount rate (incl. time value of money)\n(c) Passage of time — unwinding of discount",
    exam:true },

  { id:77, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the 4 Factors affecting the Useful Life of a PPE asset?\nWhat is the significance of an entity's Asset Management Policy on useful life?\nWhat is special about Land vs Buildings for depreciation?",
    back:"4 Factors Affecting Useful Life:\n(a) Expected USAGE — assessed by expected capacity or physical output\n(b) Expected PHYSICAL WEAR & TEAR — number of shifts, repair & maintenance programme, care while idle\n(c) TECHNICAL/COMMERCIAL OBSOLESCENCE — production improvements, market demand shifts, expected price reductions of output\n(d) LEGAL or similar LIMITS — lease expiry dates, regulatory restrictions\n\nAsset Management Policy:\n→ Entity may dispose of assets after a specified time or after consuming a specified proportion of future economic benefits\n→ Therefore, useful life may be SHORTER than economic life\n→ Estimation = matter of JUDGEMENT based on experience with similar assets\n\nLand vs Buildings:\n→ Land & Buildings = SEPARABLE assets; accounted for SEPARATELY even when acquired together\n→ Land → generally has UNLIMITED useful life → NOT depreciated\n→ Buildings → have LIMITED useful life → ARE depreciated\n→ Increase in land value does NOT affect building's depreciable amount\n→ Exception: If land has costs of dismantlement/restoration included → that portion IS depreciated\n\n📌 Residual value + Useful life reviewed at EACH YEAR-END\n📌 Changes = Change in Accounting Estimate → PROSPECTIVE (Ind AS 8)",
    exam:false },

  { id:78, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"Ind AS 16 vs AS 10 — What are the 2 key differences?\nWhat is the Carve-Out in Ind AS 16 vs IAS 16?\nWhen does derecognition occur and how is gain/loss calculated?",
    back:"Ind AS 16 vs AS 10:\n\n1. Held for Sale:\n• Ind AS 16 → Does NOT deal with assets held for sale → covered under Ind AS 105\n• AS 10 → Deals with fixed assets retired from active use and held for sale\n\n2. Stripping Costs:\n• Ind AS 16 → Provides guidance on 'Stripping Costs in Production Phase of a Surface Mine'\n• AS 10 → Does NOT contain this guidance\n\nCarve-Out — Ind AS 16 vs IAS 16:\n• Ind AS 16 (MCA amendment, 23 March 2022): Excess of net proceeds from items produced DURING TESTING → DEDUCTED from cost of PPE (NOT credited to P&L)\n• IAS 16 (IASB): Proceeds from testing → CANNOT be deducted from PPE cost (credited to P&L)\n• Impact: Depreciation | Impairment | Deferred Tax\n\nDerecognition:\nOccurs when: (a) On disposal; OR (b) When no future economic benefits expected from its use or disposal\n\nGain/Loss on Derecognition:\n= Net Disposal Proceeds − Carrying Amount of the item\n→ Recognized in P&L\n→ Gains NOT classified as Revenue\n\n📌 Date of disposal = date recipient obtains CONTROL (Ind AS 115)\n📌 Sale and leaseback disposal → governed by Ind AS 116",
    exam:false },

  // ── QUICK FIRE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:79, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ TRUE or FALSE:\n\n'Depreciation must stop when an asset becomes idle or is retired from active use.'",
    back:"❌ FALSE\n\nDepreciation does NOT cease when an asset becomes idle or is retired from active use UNLESS the asset is FULLY DEPRECIATED.\n\nDepreciation only CEASES at the EARLIER of:\n(a) Date classified as Held for Sale (Ind AS 105)\n(b) Date derecognized (sold/disposed)\n\nException: Under USAGE-BASED methods (e.g., units of production), the charge CAN be zero when there is no production — but this is because the method is output-linked, not because depreciation 'stops.'\n\nAlso TRUE:\n→ Depreciation IS recognized even if Fair Value > Carrying Amount, as long as Residual Value < Carrying Amount\n→ Repair and maintenance of an asset do NOT negate the need to depreciate it\n\n📌 Example: Machine shut down for 3 months → SLM/WDV depreciation continues every period",
    exam:false },

  { id:80, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ IDENTIFY: Capitalizable vs P&L\n\nA. Staff training at new factory\nB. Site preparation costs\nC. General overhead costs\nD. Installation & assembly costs\nE. Operating losses before commercial production\nF. Initial delivery & handling costs\nG. NPV of decommissioning obligation\nH. Cost of opening ceremony\nI. Testing costs (net of proceeds from samples produced)",
    back:"✅ CAPITALIZABLE (Part of PPE cost):\nB. Site preparation costs ✅\nD. Installation & assembly costs ✅\nF. Initial delivery & handling costs ✅\nG. NPV of decommissioning obligation ✅\nI. Testing costs net of proceeds ✅\n\n❌ NOT Capitalizable → P&L:\nA. Staff training → P&L ❌\nC. General overhead costs → P&L ❌\nE. Operating losses before commercial production → P&L ❌\nH. Cost of opening ceremony → P&L ❌\n\n📌 GOLDEN TEST: Was this cost NECESSARY to bring the asset to its LOCATION and CONDITION for its INTENDED USE?\n• YES → Capitalize\n• NO → P&L\n\n📌 Capitalisation CEASES when asset is in location & condition for intended use — costs incurred after that point go to P&L\n📌 Income from incidental operations (e.g., using building site as car park during construction) → P&L directly (NOT offset against PPE cost)",
    exam:false },

  { id:81, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ MATCH: Revaluation Surplus / Deficit Treatment\n\nA. First revaluation — FV increases\nB. First revaluation — FV decreases\nC. Subsequent revaluation — FV increases (previous P&L loss existed)\nD. Subsequent revaluation — FV decreases (previous OCI surplus existed)",
    back:"A. First revaluation — FV increases:\n→ OCI (Revaluation Surplus, accumulated in equity) ✅\n\nB. First revaluation — FV decreases:\n→ P&L (Revaluation Loss) ❌\n\nC. Subsequent — FV increases (previous P&L loss existed):\n→ FIRST: Reverse previous P&L loss → recognize in P&L (credit)\n→ THEN: Any remaining increase → OCI ✅\n\nD. Subsequent — FV decreases (previous OCI surplus existed):\n→ FIRST: Use existing revaluation surplus → OCI (debit)\n→ THEN: Any remaining decrease → P&L ❌\n\n📌 SIMPLE MEMORY RULE:\n• GAINS → OCI first\n• LOSSES → P&L first\n• Subsequent events REVERSE the original treatment first\n\n📌 Transfer of surplus to Retained Earnings:\n→ On derecognition → full surplus\n→ While in use → excess depreciation (revalued dep. minus historical cost dep.) each year\n→ Transfers NOT through P&L",
    exam:false },

  { id:82, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 16", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ FULL FORMS & 1-LINE MEANING:\nInd AS 16 | PPE | SLM | WDV | OCI | CA | FV | RV | Ind AS 37 | Ind AS 23",
    back:"Ind AS 16 → Indian Accounting Standard 16\n(Property, Plant & Equipment — governs recognition, measurement & disclosure of PPE)\n\nPPE → Property, Plant & Equipment\n(Tangible assets held for use in production/rental/admin for more than one period)\n\nSLM → Straight Line Method\n(Constant depreciation charge over useful life)\n\nWDV → Written Down Value / Diminishing Balance Method\n(Decreasing depreciation charge over useful life)\n\nOCI → Other Comprehensive Income\n(Non-P&L items — e.g., revaluation surplus, actuarial gains/losses)\n\nCA → Carrying Amount\n(Cost less accumulated depreciation less accumulated impairment losses)\n\nFV → Fair Value\n(Price received/paid in orderly transaction between market participants — Ind AS 113)\n\nRV → Residual Value\n(Estimated disposal proceeds at end of useful life, net of disposal costs)\n\nInd AS 37 → Provisions, Contingent Liabilities & Contingent Assets\n(Governs measurement of decommissioning / restoration provisions)\n\nInd AS 23 → Borrowing Costs\n(Governs capitalization of interest on qualifying assets; unwinding of decommissioning discount is NOT capitalizable under Ind AS 23)",
    exam:false },

  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // IND AS 38 — INTANGIBLE ASSETS
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  // ── CONCEPT ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:83, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What is the Objective of Ind AS 38?\nWhat 4 items are EXCLUDED from its scope?\nWhat 3 special scope notes apply to:\n(a) Physical substance  (b) Leases  (c) Extractive / Insurance industries?",
    back:"Objective: Prescribe accounting treatment for intangible assets NOT dealt with specifically in another Standard. Requires recognition ONLY if specified criteria are met. Specifies recognition, measurement & disclosures.\n\n❌ Scope Exclusions:\n(a) Intangible assets covered by another Standard (Ind AS 2, 12, 19, 32, 103, 105, 115, 116, 117)\n(b) Financial assets (Ind AS 32)\n(c) Exploration & evaluation assets (Ind AS 106)\n(d) Expenditure on development & extraction of minerals, oil, natural gas\n\n📌 Physical substance (5.2.2): Mixed asset (tangible + intangible) → use JUDGEMENT on which element is MORE SIGNIFICANT\n→ Software integral to hardware (OS, machine-control software) → PPE (Ind AS 16)\n→ Software not integral → Intangible Asset\n\n📌 Leases (5.2.3): Licensing rights for films, plays, manuscripts, patents, copyrights → EXCLUDED from Ind AS 116, within scope of Ind AS 38\n\n📌 Extractive/Insurance (5.2.4): Computer software, start-up costs used in extractive industries → INCLUDED in Ind AS 38 even though exploration costs are excluded",
    exam:false },

  { id:84, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"Define Intangible Asset. What are its 3 key elements?\nDefine: Amortisation | Carrying Amount | Development | Research | Residual Value | Useful Life",
    back:"Intangible Asset = An IDENTIFIABLE, NON-MONETARY ASSET WITHOUT PHYSICAL SUBSTANCE\n\n3 Key Elements:\n(i) Identifiable\n(ii) Non-monetary asset (not money/receivable in fixed amounts)\n(iii) Without physical substance\n\nAmortisation: Systematic allocation of DEPRECIABLE AMOUNT over USEFUL LIFE\n\nCarrying Amount: Amount at which asset is recognized LESS accumulated amortisation LESS accumulated impairment losses\n\nDevelopment: Application of research findings/knowledge to a plan/design for NEW or SUBSTANTIALLY IMPROVED products/processes BEFORE start of commercial production or use\n\nResearch: Original & planned investigation to gain NEW scientific or technical knowledge and understanding\n\nResidual Value: Estimated disposal amount NOW (if asset were already at end of useful life, net of disposal costs) — assumed ZERO unless (a) third-party commitment to purchase, or (b) active market exists\n\nUseful Life:\n(a) Period over which asset is available for use; OR\n(b) Number of production/similar units expected to be obtained\n\n📌 Indefinite ≠ Infinite — indefinite means no foreseeable limit on the period of net cash inflows",
    exam:false },

  { id:85, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is IDENTIFIABILITY in Ind AS 38?\nWhat are the 2 conditions for an asset to be IDENTIFIABLE?\nWhy can't market share or customer loyalty be recognized as intangible assets?\n\n🔍 [Illustration 1 — Sun Ltd.]",
    back:"Identifiability distinguishes an intangible asset from goodwill (which represents unidentifiable future economic benefits).\n\nAn asset is IDENTIFIABLE if EITHER:\n(a) SEPARABLE — capable of being separated/divided from entity and sold, transferred, licensed, rented or exchanged (individually or with related contract/asset/liability), regardless of whether entity INTENDS to; OR\n(b) Arises from CONTRACTUAL or OTHER LEGAL RIGHTS — regardless of whether those rights are transferable or separable\n\nWhy Market Share / Customer Loyalty CANNOT be recognized:\n→ Not separable (cannot be sold separately from the business)\n→ Does NOT arise from contractual or legal rights\n→ Therefore: NOT identifiable → cannot meet intangible asset definition\n\n📌 Sun Ltd. Example: Company gained 30% market share → CANNOT recognize as intangible asset. Market share fails BOTH identifiability conditions.\n\n📌 Customer lists: If entity INTERNALLY generates a list → cannot recognize (cost not distinguishable from business development costs). BUT if acquired in a business combination or purchased separately → CAN recognize (exchange transaction proves separability & control).",
    exam:true },

  { id:86, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is CONTROL in the context of intangible assets?\nGive 3 examples of what DOES and DOES NOT meet the control criterion.\n\n🔍 [Illustration 2 — XYZ Staff Training]",
    back:"CONTROL = Entity has:\n(i) Power to obtain future economic benefits from the resource; AND\n(ii) Ability to RESTRICT access of others to those benefits\n\n→ Usually stems from LEGAL RIGHTS (enforceable in court)\n→ Legal enforceability is NOT necessary if control exists another way\n\n✅ CONTROL EXISTS (Intangible Asset recognized):\n• Technical knowledge protected by copyright or restraint-of-trade agreement\n• Customer lists acquired through exchange transactions (separability proven)\n• Patent, licence, trademark (legal rights exist)\n\n❌ CONTROL DOES NOT EXIST (NOT an intangible asset):\n• Staff skills from training → Staff can RESIGN; entity CANNOT restrict others benefiting from their skills → No control → EXPENSE\n• Market share, customer loyalty → No legal rights; entity cannot restrict competitors\n• Specific management talent → Unless protected by legal rights\n\n📌 XYZ Ltd. Staff Training: Company provides GST/Ind AS training. Company WILL get economic benefits, BUT staff can resign at any time. Entity lacks ability to RESTRICT ACCESS to those benefits → Staff training cost → P&L EXPENSE, NOT intangible asset.\n\n📌 Future economic benefits = Revenue from sale, cost savings, or other benefits",
    exam:true },

  { id:87, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Explain the Research Phase vs Development Phase for internally generated intangibles.\nWhat are the 6 CRITERIA that ALL must be met for Development costs to be capitalized?\nWhat items can NEVER be recognized as internally generated intangible assets?",
    back:"RESEARCH PHASE → Always EXPENSE when incurred\nReason: Cannot demonstrate at research stage that an identifiable asset will generate probable future economic benefits.\nExamples: New knowledge activities, search for & evaluation of research findings, search for alternatives, formulation & final selection of alternatives.\n\nDEVELOPMENT PHASE → Capitalize IF all 6 criteria met:\n(T-I-A-H-A-A mnemonic)\n✅ Technical feasibility of completing the asset for use or sale\n✅ Intention to complete and use or sell the asset\n✅ Ability to use or sell the asset\n✅ How the asset will generate probable future economic benefits (demonstrable market or internal usefulness)\n✅ Adequate technical, financial & other resources to complete development\n✅ Ability to measure reliably expenditure attributable to the asset during development\n\n📌 If research and development phases CANNOT be distinguished → treat all as RESEARCH → full expense\n📌 Previously expensed costs CANNOT be reinstated as an asset later\n\n❌ NEVER recognizable as internally generated intangibles:\n• Internally generated goodwill\n• Brands, mastheads, publishing titles\n• Customer lists\n• Items similar in substance to the above",
    exam:true },

  // ── FORMULA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:88, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 What are the COMPONENTS of cost for a SEPARATELY ACQUIRED intangible asset?\nHow is DEFERRED CONSIDERATION handled?\nList costs that are NOT part of the cost.",
    back:"Cost = (a) + (b):\n(a) Purchase price (incl. import duties + non-refundable purchase taxes) LESS trade discounts & rebates\n(b) Any DIRECTLY ATTRIBUTABLE cost of preparing the asset for its intended use:\n   • Employee benefits costs arising directly (Ind AS 19)\n   • Professional fees arising directly\n   • Testing costs to check whether asset is working properly\n\nDeferred Consideration (payment beyond normal credit terms):\n→ Cost = CASH PRICE EQUIVALENT (present value of all payments)\n→ Difference between total payments and cash price equivalent = INTEREST EXPENSE recognized in P&L over credit period\n→ Unless capitalized under Ind AS 23 (Borrowing Costs)\n\n❌ NOT part of cost:\n• Costs of introducing a new product/service (incl. advertising/promotional)\n• Costs of conducting business in new location/class of customer (incl. staff training)\n• Administrative & other general overhead costs\n• Initial operating losses\n\nCessation of Capitalisation:\n→ When asset is in condition necessary for operation as intended by management\n→ Costs incurred while asset capable of operating but not yet brought into use → NOT capitalized\n\n📌 Probability recognition criterion ALWAYS satisfied for separately acquired intangibles (price already reflects probable future benefits)",
    exam:true },

  { id:89, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Measurement after Recognition — Cost Model vs Revaluation Model for Intangible Assets.\nHow is Revaluation Surplus / Deficit treated?\nWhen can the Revaluation Model be applied?\nHow is Revaluation Surplus transferred to Retained Earnings?",
    back:"COST MODEL:\nCarrying Amount = Cost − Accumulated Amortisation − Accumulated Impairment Losses\n\nREVALUATION MODEL:\nCarrying Amount = FV at date of revaluation − Subsequent accumulated amortisation − Subsequent accumulated impairment losses\n→ Fair value measured by reference to an ACTIVE MARKET\n→ Revaluation applied to ENTIRE CLASS of similar intangible assets\n→ Frequency: Sufficient regularity so CA does not differ materially from FV; annually if FV is volatile\n\nRestrictions on Revaluation Model:\n❌ Cannot revalue assets not previously recognized\n❌ Cannot initially recognize at amounts other than cost\n✅ Applied AFTER initial recognition at cost\n✅ Can apply to asset initially recognized at nominal amount (government grant)\n\nRevaluation Surplus/Deficit Treatment:\n↑ CA increases → OCI (Revaluation Surplus)\n↓ CA decreases → P&L (Revaluation Loss)\nSubsequent: reversal follows original treatment (same as Ind AS 16)\n\nTransfer to Retained Earnings:\n→ On retirement/disposal → entire surplus\n→ While in use → difference between (revalued amortisation − historical cost amortisation)\n→ Transfer NOT made through P&L\n\n📌 If active market no longer exists → carry at last revaluation less subsequent amortisation/impairment\n📌 Loss of active market may indicate impairment → test under Ind AS 36",
    exam:false },

  { id:90, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Amortisation of Intangible Assets — Complete Framework:\n(a) Finite vs Indefinite useful life — what happens to each?\n(b) When does amortisation BEGIN and CEASE?\n(c) Residual Value assumptions\n(d) Amortisation methods — which is presumed inappropriate?",
    back:"FINITE USEFUL LIFE → Amortised on a systematic basis over useful life\nINDEFINITE USEFUL LIFE → NOT amortised; tested for impairment ANNUALLY (Ind AS 36)\n→ 'Indefinite' ≠ 'Infinite' — means no foreseeable limit to net cash inflow period\n\nAmortisation BEGINS: When asset is AVAILABLE FOR USE\nAmortisation CEASES: EARLIER of:\n(a) Date classified as Held for Sale (Ind AS 105)\n(b) Date derecognized\n→ Does NOT cease when asset is no longer used (unless fully amortised or held for sale)\n\nDepreciable Amount = Cost (or revalued amount) LESS Residual Value\n\nResidual Value ASSUMED ZERO unless:\n(a) Third-party commitment to purchase at end of useful life, OR\n(b) Active market exists AND (i) RV determinable by reference to that market AND (ii) market likely to exist at end of useful life\n\nAmortisation Methods:\n✅ Straight-line (default if consumption pattern not determinable)\n✅ Diminishing balance\n✅ Units of production\n❌ Revenue-based amortisation → REBUTTABLY PRESUMED INAPPROPRIATE\n(Exception: if intangible is expressed as measure of revenue, or revenue & consumption are highly correlated)\n\n📌 Amortisation period & method reviewed at EACH year-end → changes = change in accounting estimate (Ind AS 8) → PROSPECTIVE",
    exam:true },

  // ── PRACTICAL ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:91, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Separate Acquisition — Cost Calculation\n[Illustration 4 — Venus India Pvt. Ltd.]\n\nSoftware acquired for internal use. Paid ₹6,00,000 immediately & ₹4,00,000 in one year.\nOther costs:\n• Purchase Tax: ₹1,00,000\n• Entry Tax: 10% (recoverable from tax dept.)\n• Legal Fees: ₹87,000\n• Consultancy fees for implementation: ₹1,20,000\nCost of capital: 10%\n\nCalculate total cost to be capitalized.",
    back:"Cash paid immediately:                     ₹ 6,00,000\nDeferred consideration (PV): 4,00,000 / 1.1 = ₹ 3,63,636\nPurchase Tax (non-refundable):             ₹ 1,00,000\nEntry Tax (10% — recoverable):                    NIL ← refundable, not capitalizable\nLegal Fees:                                ₹    87,000\nConsultancy fees for implementation:       ₹ 1,20,000\n─────────────────────────────────────────\nTotal Cost to be Capitalised:              ₹12,70,636\n\n📌 KEY RULES APPLIED:\n→ Deferred payment beyond normal terms → cash price equivalent (PV at 10%)\n→ Difference (₹4,00,000 − ₹3,63,636 = ₹36,364) → Interest expense in P&L\n→ Refundable taxes (Entry Tax) → NEVER part of cost\n→ Legal fees + consultancy for implementation → directly attributable → ✅ CAPITALIZE\n→ Recoverable taxes cannot be included in asset cost",
    exam:true },

  { id:92, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Business Combination — Goodwill & Intangibles\n[Illustration 5 — Earth India / Sun India]\n\nEarth India Ltd. paid ₹50,00,000 for 100% of Sun India Ltd.\nSun Ltd.'s net assets fair value: ₹30,00,000\nSun Ltd. also holds:\n• Trademark 'GRAND' — valued at ₹1,80,000 (DCF)\n• Sole distribution rights — ₹1,50,000 p.a. for 6 years\n  (10% discount rate; 6-yr annuity factor = 4.36)\n\nCalculate Goodwill on acquisition.",
    back:"Purchase consideration (A):                       ₹50,00,000\n\nNet assets acquired:\nNet assets at fair value:       ₹30,00,000\nTrademark 'GRAND':               ₹ 1,80,000\nDistribution rights:\n  1,50,000 × 4.36 =             ₹ 6,54,000\n─────────────────────────────────\nTotal identifiable net assets (B):               ₹38,34,000\n\nGoodwill = A − B = 50,00,000 − 38,34,000 =      ₹11,66,000\n\n📌 KEY RULES APPLIED:\n→ Intangible assets in business combinations → recognized at FAIR VALUE at acquisition date\n→ Recognizable REGARDLESS of whether acquiree recognized them before the combination\n→ Trademark (DCF valuation) → ✅ separable → capitalize separately\n→ Distribution rights (contract-based) → ✅ legal rights → capitalize separately\n→ Probability criterion ALWAYS satisfied for assets in business combinations\n→ Goodwill = residual after identifying all individually measurable intangibles",
    exam:true },

  { id:93, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Exchange of Assets — 3 Situations\n[Illustration 6 — Sun Ltd. / Earth Ltd.]\n\nSun Ltd. exchanges Telecom License (CA ₹5,00,000) for Software from Earth Ltd. (CA ₹10,000 — NOT fair value).\n\nSituation 1: FV of Software = ₹5,20,000; FV of Telecom License = ₹5,00,000\nSituation 2: FV of Software NOT measurable; Similar Telecom License transacted at ₹4,90,000\nSituation 3: Neither FV measurable\n\nPass journal entries in books of Sun Ltd. and Earth Ltd. (₹ in '000)",
    back:"SITUATION 1 — Both FVs available → Use FV of asset GIVEN UP (if more clearly evident, use FV received):\nSun Ltd.:  Software Dr. 500 | To Telecom License 500 | Profit = Nil\nEarth Ltd.: Telecom License Dr. 520 | To Software 10 | To Profit on Exchange 510\n\nSITUATION 2 — FV of Software not measurable; use FV of similar Telecom License (₹490):\nSun Ltd.:  Software Dr. 490 | Loss on Exchange Dr. 10 | To Telecom License 500\nEarth Ltd.: Telecom License Dr. 490 | To Software 10 | To Profit on Exchange 480\n\nSITUATION 3 — Neither FV measurable → use CA of asset GIVEN UP:\nSun Ltd.:  Software Dr. 500 | To Telecom License 500\nEarth Ltd.: Telecom License Dr. 10 | To Software 10\n\n📌 KEY RULE: Cost of intangible in exchange = FV of asset given up UNLESS:\n(a) Exchange lacks COMMERCIAL SUBSTANCE, OR\n(b) NEITHER FV reliably measurable\n→ Then use CA of asset given up → NO profit/loss recognized\n📌 If FV received is MORE CLEARLY EVIDENT → use FV received as cost",
    exam:true },

  { id:94, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Development Phase — Carrying Amount Across Years\n[Illustration 8]\n\nExpenditure on new production process in 20X1-20X2:\n• 1 Apr–31 Dec: ₹2,700\n• 1 Jan–31 Mar: ₹900 (met recognition criteria from 1 Jan 20X2)\nRecoverable amount at 31 Mar 20X2: ₹1,000\nFurther development in 20X2-20X3: ₹6,000\nBrought into use 31 Mar 20X3; useful life 6 years\nRecoverable amount at 31 Mar 20X4: ₹5,000\n\nFind: Charge to P&L (20X1-20X2), CA at 31 Mar 20X2, 20X3 & 20X4",
    back:"1) CHARGE TO P&L IN 20X1-20X2:\nTotal expenditure: ₹3,600\nLess: Development phase (from 1 Jan 20X2): (₹900)\nCharge to P&L = ₹2,700 (research/pre-criteria phase)\n\n2) CA AT 31 MAR 20X2:\nCapitalize only development phase = ₹900\n(Recoverable amount ₹1,000 > CA ₹900 → No impairment)\nCA = ₹900\n\n3) CA AT 31 MAR 20X3:\nCA at 31 Mar 20X2:            ₹  900\nAdd: Further development:     ₹6,000\nCA at 31 Mar 20X3:            ₹6,900\n(Asset not yet in use → no amortisation yet)\n\n4) CHARGES IN 20X3-20X4:\nOpening CA:                   ₹6,900\nLess: Amortisation (6,900/6): (₹1,150)\nCA before impairment:         ₹5,750\nLess: Recoverable amount:     (₹5,000)\nImpairment Loss (P&L):           ₹750\n\nCA AT 31 MAR 20X4 = ₹5,000 (recoverable amount)\n\n📌 Capitalize only from date recognition criteria are FIRST MET\n📌 Previously expensed amounts CANNOT be reinstated",
    exam:true },

  { id:95, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Revaluation Model — Journal Entries\n[Illustration 9 — Saturn Ltd. & Jupiter Ltd.]\n\nSaturn Ltd.: Acquired intangible ₹1,00,000 on 31 Mar 20X1.\n→ Revalued ₹1,20,000 on 31 Mar 20X2\n→ Revalued ₹85,000 on 31 Mar 20X3\n\nJupiter Ltd.: Acquired intangible ₹1,00,000 on 31 Mar 20X1.\n→ Revalued ₹85,000 on 31 Mar 20X2\n→ Revalued ₹1,05,000 on 31 Mar 20X3\n\n(Ignore amortisation for simplicity)\nAdvise treatment in financial statements.",
    back:"SATURN LTD.:\n31 Mar 20X2 — FV increases by ₹20,000:\n→ ₹20,000 credited to REVALUATION RESERVE (OCI) ✅\n\n31 Mar 20X3 — FV decreases by ₹35,000 (from ₹1,20,000 to ₹85,000):\n→ First: Use revaluation reserve → ₹20,000 debited to OCI (Revaluation Reserve)\n→ Then: Remaining ₹15,000 → P&L (Revaluation Loss / Expense) ❌\n\nJUPITER LTD.:\n31 Mar 20X2 — FV decreases by ₹15,000:\n→ ₹15,000 recognized as EXPENSE in P&L ❌\n\n31 Mar 20X3 — FV increases by ₹20,000 (from ₹85,000 to ₹1,05,000):\n→ First: Reverse previous P&L loss → ₹15,000 credited to P&L (Income) ✅\n→ Then: Remaining ₹5,000 → OCI (Revaluation Reserve) ✅\n\n📌 RULE SUMMARY:\nFirst revaluation → Gain to OCI | Loss to P&L\nSubsequent → Gain FIRST reverses previous P&L loss; rest to OCI\nSubsequent → Loss FIRST absorbs existing OCI surplus; rest to P&L\n📌 Amounts above will DIFFER if amortisation is considered",
    exam:true },

  { id:96, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Internally Generated Intangibles — Expense or Capitalize?\n[Illustration 7 — Venus Ltd.]\n\nVenus Ltd. year ended 31 Mar 20X2:\n1. Marketing & advertising campaign: ₹2,40,000 (expected to create ₹5,00,000 additional profits over 3 years)\n2. New product development: ₹1,50,000 total (₹1,00,000 before 30 Sep 20X1; ₹50,000 after; technically viable from 30 Sep 20X1; recoverable amount ₹70,000)\n3. Staff training programme: ₹3,00,000 (expected incremental profits ₹5,00,000 over 12 months)\n\nWhat amounts appear as assets in Venus Ltd.'s balance sheet at 31 Mar 20X2?",
    back:"1. MARKETING & ADVERTISING CAMPAIGN (₹2,40,000):\n→ Ind AS 38 SPECIFICALLY PROHIBITS advertising expenditure as intangible asset\n→ Expected future profits do NOT change this rule\n→ Treatment: FULL ₹2,40,000 expensed in P&L\nBalance sheet asset: NIL\n\n2. NEW PRODUCT DEVELOPMENT (₹1,50,000):\n→ Before 30 Sep 20X1 (pre-technical feasibility): ₹1,00,000 → P&L EXPENSE\n→ After 30 Sep 20X1 (development phase criteria met): ₹50,000 → CAPITALIZE\n→ Test for impairment: CA ₹50,000 < Recoverable Amount ₹70,000 → No impairment\nBalance sheet asset: ₹50,000 ✅\n\n3. STAFF TRAINING PROGRAMME (₹3,00,000):\n→ Staff are NOT under control of Venus Ltd. — they can resign at any time\n→ No control → training cost CANNOT meet intangible asset definition\n→ Treatment: ₹3,00,000 → P&L EXPENSE\nBalance sheet asset: NIL\n\n📌 Total intangible assets on balance sheet: ₹50,000 only\n📌 Expenditure previously expensed CANNOT be reinstated as asset at a later date",
    exam:true },

  // ── THEORY Q&A ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:97, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What items are PROHIBITED from recognition as intangible assets under Ind AS 38?\nExplain why Internally Generated Goodwill cannot be recognized.\nWhat types of expenditure must ALWAYS be recognized as expenses?",
    back:"PROHIBITED FROM RECOGNITION (Internally Generated):\n❌ Internally generated goodwill\n❌ Brands\n❌ Mastheads\n❌ Publishing titles\n❌ Customer lists\n❌ Items similar in substance to the above\nReason: Cost cannot be distinguished from cost of developing the business as a whole\n\nINTERNALLY GENERATED GOODWILL — Why Not Recognized:\n→ NOT identifiable (not separable, not from contractual/legal rights)\n→ NOT controlled by entity in a reliable, measurable way\n→ Cost CANNOT be measured reliably\n→ Differences between FV and book value of net assets ≠ cost of controlled intangibles\n\nEXPENDITURE ALWAYS RECOGNIZED AS EXPENSE:\n(a) Research expenditure (unless acquired in a business combination)\n(b) Start-up / pre-opening / pre-operating costs\n(c) Training activities\n(d) Advertising & promotional activities (incl. mail order catalogues)\n(e) Relocation/reorganization expenditure\n\n📌 If item doesn't qualify as intangible asset but is acquired in a business combination → part of GOODWILL at acquisition date\n📌 Subsequent expenditure on brands, mastheads, publishing titles, customer lists → ALWAYS P&L (cannot distinguish from business development costs)\n📌 Once expensed → CANNOT reinstate as asset at a later date",
    exam:true },

  { id:98, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the Disclosure Requirements under Ind AS 38?\nList:\n(a) General disclosures for each class\n(b) Special disclosures for indefinite-life assets\n(c) Special disclosures for revalued intangibles\n(d) Research & Development expenditure disclosure",
    back:"GENERAL DISCLOSURES (for each class, distinguishing internally generated vs others):\n• Useful lives (finite/indefinite) or amortisation rates\n• Amortisation methods for finite-life assets\n• Gross CA + accumulated amortisation (+ impairment) at beginning & end of period\n• P&L line item(s) where amortisation is included\n• Reconciliation of CA (additions — internal/separate/business combinations; disposals; revaluations; impairments recognized/reversed; amortisation; exchange differences; other changes)\n\nINDEFINITE USEFUL LIFE ASSETS:\n• Carrying amount of that asset\n• Reasons supporting the indefinite life assessment (factors that played a significant role)\n\nINDIVIDUALLY MATERIAL INTANGIBLES:\n• Description, CA and remaining amortisation period\n\nREVALUED INTANGIBLES:\n• Effective date of revaluation\n• Carrying amount of revalued assets\n• CA that would have been recognized under cost model\n• Revaluation surplus (opening, closing, changes, distribution restrictions)\n\nGOVERNMENT GRANT INTANGIBLES:\n• Fair value initially recognized; carrying amount; measurement model post-recognition\n\nR&D EXPENDITURE:\n• Aggregate amount recognized as expense during the period (mandatory)\n\n📌 Encouraged (not required): Description of fully amortised assets still in use; significant intangibles not recognized (failed criteria or pre-standard)",
    exam:false },

  { id:99, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What factors determine the USEFUL LIFE of an intangible asset?\nWhen is an intangible asset's useful life INDEFINITE?\nWhat special rules apply to intangible assets arising from CONTRACTUAL or OTHER LEGAL RIGHTS?\nHow is a change from indefinite to finite useful life treated?",
    back:"FACTORS DETERMINING USEFUL LIFE:\n• Expected usage by entity\n• Product life cycles and public information on similar assets\n• Technical, technological, commercial or other obsolescence\n• Industry stability and market demand changes\n• Expected actions by competitors\n• Period of control; legal/contractual limits (lease expiry, regulatory restrictions)\n• Dependence on useful lives of other assets\n\n📌 Computer software → susceptible to technological obsolescence → often SHORT useful life\n📌 Useful life reflects MAINTENANCE EXPENDITURE required to maintain standard of performance\n\nINDEFINITE USEFUL LIFE:\n→ When there is NO FORESEEABLE LIMIT to the period over which asset is expected to generate net cash inflows\n→ 'Indefinite' ≠ 'Infinite'\n→ NOT amortised; tested for impairment annually (Ind AS 36)\n\nCONTRACTUAL / LEGAL RIGHTS:\n→ Useful life shall NOT EXCEED period of contractual/legal rights\n→ If rights are renewable → include renewal periods ONLY if evidence supports renewal WITHOUT significant cost\n→ Evidence: Historical renewals, conditions likely to be met, renewal cost insignificant vs future benefits\n→ Reacquired right in business combination → remaining contractual period only (no renewal periods)\n\nINDEFINITE → FINITE CHANGE:\n→ Treated as CHANGE IN ACCOUNTING ESTIMATE (Ind AS 8) → PROSPECTIVE\n→ Change is also an INDICATOR OF IMPAIRMENT → test immediately (Ind AS 36)",
    exam:true },

  { id:100, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Ind AS 38 vs AS 26 — What are the most important differences?\nList at least 6 key areas of difference.",
    back:"1. USEFUL LIFE:\nInd AS 38: Can be INDEFINITE (not amortised; tested for impairment annually)\nAS 26: Always FINITE; rebuttable presumption max 10 years\n\n2. REVALUATION MODEL:\nInd AS 38: PERMITTED (must have active market; applied to entire class)\nAS 26: NOT permitted (only cost model)\n\n3. REVENUE-BASED AMORTISATION:\nInd AS 38: Rebuttably presumed INAPPROPRIATE (rare exceptions allowed)\nAS 26: Silent\n\n4. DEFERRED CONSIDERATION:\nInd AS 38: Difference between cash price equivalent and total payments = INTEREST EXPENSE\nAS 26: No such provision\n\n5. IDENTIFIABILITY:\nInd AS 38: Separable OR from contractual/legal rights (rights need not be transferable)\nAS 26: Separability not necessary condition for identifiability\n\n6. BUSINESS COMBINATIONS:\nInd AS 38: Detailed guidance; probability criterion ALWAYS satisfied for acquired intangibles\nAS 26: Only covers amalgamations in nature of purchase; not business combinations as a whole\n\n7. GOVERNMENT GRANTS:\nInd AS 38: Recognize both asset and grant at FAIR VALUE (per Ind AS 20); nominal amount allowed as alternative\nAS 26: Nominal value or acquisition cost\n\n8. RESIDUAL VALUE:\nInd AS 38: Can increase; if RV ≥ CA, amortisation = zero; reviewed each year-end\nAS 26: Residual value NOT subsequently increased for changes in prices or value",
    exam:true },

  // ── QUICK FIRE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:101, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ TRUE or FALSE (Ind AS 38):\n\nA. Research expenditure can be capitalized if it is expected to generate future economic benefits.\nB. Internally generated goodwill must be recognized as an intangible asset.\nC. An intangible asset with an indefinite useful life must be tested for impairment annually.\nD. Amortisation of a finite-life intangible ceases when the asset is no longer in use.\nE. Advertising expenditure can be capitalized if market research shows it will drive future profits.",
    back:"A. FALSE ❌\n→ Research expenditure is ALWAYS expensed. The standard explicitly prohibits capitalizing research costs. Future benefit expectation is irrelevant at the research stage.\n\nB. FALSE ❌\n→ Internally generated goodwill is PROHIBITED from recognition. It is not identifiable, not separable, and cannot be measured reliably.\n\nC. TRUE ✅\n→ Intangible asset with INDEFINITE useful life → Annual impairment test (Ind AS 36) PLUS whenever there is an indication of impairment.\n\nD. FALSE ❌\n→ Amortisation does NOT cease when an intangible asset is no longer used, unless it is FULLY AMORTISED or classified as Held for Sale (Ind AS 105).\n\nE. FALSE ❌\n→ Ind AS 38 SPECIFICALLY PROHIBITS advertising expenditure from being capitalized as an intangible asset, regardless of expected future profits or market research.\n\n📌 Remember: Advertising = Always P&L | Research = Always P&L | Staff Training = Always P&L",
    exam:false },

  { id:102, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ IDENTIFY: Capitalize (Intangible Asset) vs Expense (P&L) for Ind AS 38:\n\nA. Cost of pilot plant not commercially feasible — development stage\nB. Staff training to use new software\nC. Legal fees to register a patent\nD. Marketing campaign for new product launch\nE. Pre-production prototype testing costs (development phase — all 6 criteria met)\nF. Expenditure on research to discover new compound\nG. Implementation/consultancy fees for internally developed software (development phase)\nH. Amortisation of existing patents used to develop a new intangible\nI. Opening losses before commercial production of internally developed software",
    back:"✅ CAPITALIZE (Intangible Asset — development costs):\nA. Pilot plant (not commercially feasible) in development phase ✅ — example of development activity\nC. Legal fees to register a patent ✅ — directly attributable cost\nE. Prototype testing costs (development phase, all 6 criteria met) ✅\nG. Implementation/consultancy fees — development phase, directly attributable ✅\nH. Amortisation of patents used to generate the new intangible ✅ — directly attributable\n\n❌ EXPENSE (P&L):\nB. Staff training ❌ — always P&L; no control\nD. Marketing campaign ❌ — advertising expenditure always P&L\nF. Research to discover new compound ❌ — research phase; always P&L\nI. Opening losses before commercial production ❌ — cost exclusion\n\n📌 GOLDEN RULE: Development costs capitalize ONLY when ALL 6 criteria (T-I-A-H-A-A) are met\n📌 Research phase → ALWAYS P&L, no exceptions\n📌 Once expensed → CANNOT be reinstated as asset",
    exam:false },

  { id:103, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ MATCH: Amortisation Treatment for Intangible Assets\n\nGiven these scenarios, state whether: (i) Amortise | (ii) Do NOT amortise but test for impairment annually | (iii) Change useful life assessment\n\nA. Broadcasting licence renewable indefinitely at little cost; entity intends to renew\nB. Trademark with 5-yr legal life, renewable every 10 yrs at little cost; trademarked product expected to generate cash inflows indefinitely\nC. Broadcasting licence — authority announces no more renewals; 3 years remaining\nD. Trademark with indefinite life — management decides to discontinue product in 4 years\nE. Customer list acquired — useful life estimated at 18 months",
    back:"A. Broadcasting licence — renewable indefinitely at little cost:\n→ (ii) INDEFINITE USEFUL LIFE → Do NOT amortise; test annually for impairment ✅\n\nB. Trademark — renewable every 10 yrs, expected to generate cash flows indefinitely:\n→ (ii) INDEFINITE USEFUL LIFE → Do NOT amortise; test annually ✅\n→ Intention to renew + evidence = include renewal periods\n\nC. Broadcasting licence — renewals cancelled; 3 years remaining:\n→ (iii) CHANGE from indefinite to FINITE (3 years)\n→ Treat as change in accounting estimate (Ind AS 8) → PROSPECTIVE\n→ ALSO triggers immediate impairment test (Ind AS 36)\n→ Now: AMORTISE over remaining 3 years ✅\n\nD. Trademark — decision to discontinue in 4 years:\n→ (iii) CHANGE from indefinite to FINITE (4 years)\n→ Test for impairment immediately\n→ Then amortise over remaining 4-year useful life ✅\n\nE. Customer list — 18 months estimated:\n→ (i) FINITE USEFUL LIFE → AMORTISE over 18 months ✅\n→ Also reviewed for impairment indicators at each reporting date\n\n📌 Change from indefinite to finite = indicator of impairment → ALWAYS test under Ind AS 36",
    exam:true },

  { id:104, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 38", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ FULL FORMS & 1-LINE MEANING (Ind AS 38 edition):\n\nInd AS 38 | R&D | Amortisation | FV | OCI | CA | Ind AS 20 | Ind AS 36 | Ind AS 103 | T-I-A-H-A-A",
    back:"Ind AS 38 → Indian Accounting Standard 38\n(Intangible Assets — prescribes recognition, measurement & disclosure for intangible assets)\n\nR&D → Research & Development\n(Research = always expense; Development = capitalize if all 6 criteria met)\n\nAmortisation → Systematic allocation of depreciable amount of a FINITE-life intangible over its useful life\n(Indefinite-life intangibles: NOT amortised; tested for impairment annually)\n\nFV → Fair Value\n(Price received/paid in orderly transaction between market participants — Ind AS 113; required for revaluation model active market reference)\n\nOCI → Other Comprehensive Income\n(Where revaluation surpluses are initially recognized; not routed through P&L)\n\nCA → Carrying Amount\n(Cost less accumulated amortisation less accumulated impairment losses)\n\nInd AS 20 → Accounting for Government Grants\n(Intangible assets received free via government grant → recognize at FV; nominal amount alternative)\n\nInd AS 36 → Impairment of Assets\n(Governs annual impairment test for indefinite-life intangibles; also triggered by change from indefinite to finite life)\n\nInd AS 103 → Business Combinations\n(Intangibles acquired in business combination → recognized at FV; probability criterion always satisfied)\n\nT-I-A-H-A-A → The 6 criteria for capitalizing development costs:\nTechnical feasibility | Intention to complete | Ability to use/sell | How FEB will be generated | Adequate resources | Ability to measure reliably",
    exam:false },

  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // IND AS 40 — INVESTMENT PROPERTY
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  // ── CONCEPT ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:105, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What is the Objective of Ind AS 40?\nWhat is the KEY DIFFERENCE from IFRS (IAS 40) on measurement?\nWhat 2 items are EXCLUDED from its scope?",
    back:"Objective: Prescribe the accounting treatment for property (land and/or buildings) held to earn rentals or for capital appreciation (or both), and the related disclosure requirements.\n\n🇮🇳 INDIA-SPECIFIC KEY DIFFERENCE FROM IFRS:\n→ Ind AS 40 prescribes ONLY the COST MODEL for accounting for investment property\n→ IAS 40 (IFRS) permits entities to choose between cost model OR fair value model as accounting policy\n→ Under Ind AS 40: fair value is MANDATORY FOR DISCLOSURE only — it is NOT an option for balance sheet measurement\n\nScope: Applied in recognition, measurement and disclosure of investment property.\n\n❌ EXCLUDED from scope:\n(a) Biological assets related to agricultural activity (see Ind AS 41 Agriculture and Ind AS 16 PPE)\n(b) Mineral rights and mineral reserves such as oil, natural gas and similar non-regenerative resources\n\n📌 Computer software, start-up costs used in connection with IP → WITHIN scope of Ind AS 40\n📌 Leased-out intangible assets (licensing rights for films, patents, copyrights) → Ind AS 38, not Ind AS 40",
    exam:true },

  { id:106, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"Define Investment Property and Owner-Occupied Property under Ind AS 40.\nWhat Ind AS applies to each?\nWhat generates INDEPENDENT cash flows — and why does that matter?",
    back:"INVESTMENT PROPERTY:\nProperty (land or a building — or part of a building — or both) held (by owner OR by lessee as a right-of-use asset) to earn rentals or for capital appreciation or BOTH, rather than for:\n(a) Use in production/supply of goods/services or for administrative purposes; OR\n(b) Sale in the ordinary course of business\n\n→ (a) above → Ind AS 16 (PPE) → Owner-Occupied Property\n→ (b) above → Ind AS 2 (Inventories)\n\nOWNER-OCCUPIED PROPERTY:\nProperty held (by owner or by lessee as a right-of-use asset) for use in production/supply of goods or services or for ADMINISTRATIVE PURPOSES\n→ Governed by Ind AS 16 (PPE) and Ind AS 116 (Leases for right-of-use assets)\n\nKey Definitions:\nFair Value: Price received to sell an asset in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date (Ind AS 113)\nCost: Cash or cash equivalents paid (or FV of consideration given) to acquire an asset at acquisition/construction\nCarrying Amount: Amount at which an asset is recognized in the balance sheet\n\n📌 WHY INDEPENDENT CASH FLOWS MATTER:\n→ IP generates cash flows LARGELY INDEPENDENT of other assets held by the entity\n→ This distinguishes IP from OOP (whose cash flows are attributable to production/supply process assets collectively)\n→ IP can therefore represent a CASH GENERATING UNIT for impairment testing (Ind AS 36)",
    exam:true },

  { id:107, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Classify each as Investment Property (IP), Owner-Occupied Property (OOP), or Inventory (INV):\n\nA. Land held for long-term capital appreciation\nB. Land held for currently undetermined future use\nC. Building owned by entity and leased under operating lease\nD. Vacant building held to be leased under operating leases\nE. Property under construction for future IP use\nF. Property for development and resale\nG. Property held for future use as owner-occupied property\nH. Property occupied by employees (paying below-market rent)\nI. Property leased to another entity under a finance lease\nJ. Investment property held for sale\nK. Existing IP being redeveloped for continued future use as IP",
    back:"A. Land — long-term capital appreciation → ✅ IP (Ind AS 40)\n\nB. Land — undetermined future use → ✅ IP (Ind AS 40)\n(If entity hasn't decided: owner-occupied OR short-term sale → treat as capital appreciation = IP)\n\nC. Building leased under operating lease → ✅ IP (Ind AS 40)\n\nD. Vacant building held to be leased under operating leases → ✅ IP (Ind AS 40)\n\nE. Property under construction for future IP use → ✅ IP (Ind AS 40)\n\nF. Property for development and resale → ❌ INV (Ind AS 2)\n\nG. Property held for future owner-occupation → ❌ OOP (Ind AS 16)\n\nH. Employee-occupied property (any rent level) → ❌ OOP (Ind AS 16)\n\nI. Property leased to another entity under FINANCE lease → ❌ OOP — Ind AS 116 applies\n(The lessor has derecognized the asset; it is a lease receivable, not IP)\n\nJ. Investment property held for sale → ❌ NOT IP → Ind AS 105 (Non-current Assets Held for Sale)\n\nK. Existing IP being redeveloped for continued IP use → ✅ IP — remains IP; NOT reclassified as OOP during redevelopment (Ind AS 40)\n\n📌 RIGHT-OF-USE ASSET leased out under operating lease → ✅ IP\n📌 RIGHT-OF-USE ASSET leased out under finance lease → ❌ Ind AS 116",
    exam:true },

  { id:108, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"How is property classified when held for MORE THAN ONE PURPOSE?\nWhat is the ANCILLARY SERVICES rule?\nHow is IP leased to a group entity treated differently in individual vs consolidated financial statements?\n\n🔍 Examples: Sun Ltd. (15 floors) | Moon Ltd. (35%) | Hotel with health centre | Office building (security & maintenance) | Owner-managed hotel",
    back:"DUAL PURPOSE — ABLE TO SPLIT (sold/leased under finance lease separately):\n→ Classify each portion SEPARATELY: IP portion → Ind AS 40 | OOP portion → Ind AS 16\n📌 Sun Ltd.: 15-floor building; 5 floors used as office (OOP); 10 floors leased out (IP) → CAN split titles between floors → 10 floors = IP ✅\n\nDUAL PURPOSE — UNABLE TO SPLIT:\n→ Classify entire property as IP ONLY IF the owner-occupied portion is INSIGNIFICANT\n→ If owner-occupied portion is SIGNIFICANT → entire property = OOP (Ind AS 16)\n📌 Moon Ltd.: 35% office (significant) + 65% leased; cannot split → ENTIRE building = OOP (Ind AS 16) ❌\n\nANCILLARY SERVICES RULE:\n→ Services INSIGNIFICANT to arrangement as a whole → classify property as IP\n→ Services SIGNIFICANT to arrangement as a whole → property = OOP (owner-occupied)\n📌 Office building providing security & maintenance to lessees → services insignificant → ✅ IP\n📌 Owner-managed hotel → services provided to guests are significant → ❌ OOP\n\nGROUP COMPANY TREATMENT:\n→ Property leased by entity to its parent or another subsidiary:\n• CONSOLIDATED FS: NOT IP (owner-occupied from group's perspective)\n• INDIVIDUAL FS of the lessor: IS IP (meets definition from lessor entity's perspective)\n→ Same asset → treated differently in different sets of financial statements\n\n📌 MANAGEMENT INTENTION ALONE ≠ evidence of change in use for classification purposes",
    exam:true },

  // ── FORMULA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:109, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 Recognition of Investment Property — General Principle\nWhat are the 2 criteria?\nHow are DAY-TO-DAY SERVICING COSTS treated?\nHow are REPLACEMENT COSTS treated?\n\n🔍 [Illustration 1 — Wall Replacement]",
    back:"RECOGNITION CRITERIA (both must be met):\n(a) It is PROBABLE that future economic benefits associated with the IP will flow to the entity; AND\n(b) The COST of the IP can be measured RELIABLY\n→ This applies both to initial acquisition cost AND subsequent costs (add-ons, replacements, servicing)\n\nDAY-TO-DAY SERVICING COSTS:\n→ e.g., labour, consumables, cost of minor parts — described as 'repairs & maintenance'\n→ Do NOT add to carrying amount\n→ Recognize in PROFIT OR LOSS as incurred\n\nREPLACEMENT COSTS:\n→ If recognition criteria are met → ADD replacement cost to carrying amount of IP\n→ DERECOGNIZE the carrying amount of the part that was replaced\n\n📌 Illustration 1 — X Ltd Wall Replacement:\nBuilding CA:                    ₹50,00,000\nNew interior walls (capitalize): + ₹ 5,00,000\nOld walls CA (derecognize):     − ₹ 1,00,000\n─────────────────────────────────\nNew CA of building:              ₹54,00,000\n\n→ If CA of replaced part cannot be practically determined → use cost of replacement as a proxy for what the original part's cost was at time of acquisition/construction",
    exam:true },

  { id:110, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Measurement at RECOGNITION — Investment Property\nWhat is included and excluded from COST?\nHow is DEFERRED PAYMENT handled?\nHow is EXCHANGE OF ASSETS handled?\n\n🔍 [Illustration 2 — Netravati | Illustration 3 — X Ltd | Illustration 4 — Deferred | Example 5 — Exchange]",
    back:"INITIAL MEASUREMENT: At COST (including transaction costs)\n\n✅ COST INCLUSIONS:\n• Purchase price (incl. import duties + non-refundable purchase taxes)\n• Less: trade discounts & rebates\n• Directly attributable expenditure: professional/legal fees, property transfer taxes, other transaction costs\n\n❌ COST EXCLUSIONS:\n• Start-up costs (unless needed to bring property to operable condition)\n• Operating losses incurred before achieving planned level of occupancy\n• Abnormal amounts of wasted material, labour or other resources\n\nDEFERRED PAYMENT:\n→ Cost = CASH PRICE EQUIVALENT (PV of all future payments)\n→ Difference between total payments and cash price equivalent = INTEREST EXPENSE in P&L over credit period\n\nEXCHANGE OF ASSETS — cost of IP acquired:\nStep 1: Does exchange have COMMERCIAL SUBSTANCE or is FV reliably measurable?\n→ YES: Cost = FV of asset GIVEN UP (default)\n   → UNLESS FV of asset RECEIVED is more clearly evident → use FV of asset received\n→ NO (no commercial substance or FV not measurable): Cost = CARRYING AMOUNT of asset given up\n\n📌 When FV of both assets given and received are stated and equally evident → use FV of asset GIVEN UP\n📌 Probability criterion ALWAYS satisfied for IP acquired in a business combination",
    exam:true },

  { id:111, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Measurement AFTER Recognition — Cost Model (Ind AS 40)\nWhat are the 3 measurement paths depending on the asset's status?\nWhat are the FAIR VALUE obligations even under the cost model?\nWhen is FV deemed NOT reliably measurable — and what must be disclosed?",
    back:"ACCOUNTING POLICY: COST MODEL — mandatory for ALL IP under Ind AS 40\n\n3 POST-RECOGNITION MEASUREMENT PATHS:\n(a) If meets criteria to be classified as HELD FOR SALE (or in disposal group held for sale):\n   → Measure per Ind AS 105\n(b) If held by lessee as RIGHT-OF-USE ASSET and not held for sale:\n   → Measure per Ind AS 116\n(c) ALL OTHER CASES:\n   → Measure per Ind AS 16 cost model: Cost − Accumulated Depreciation − Accumulated Impairment Losses\n\nFAIR VALUE OBLIGATIONS (even though balance sheet uses cost model):\n→ All entities MUST measure FV of IP for DISCLOSURE purposes\n→ Independent valuer: ENCOURAGED but NOT required\n→ FV should reflect: rental income from current leases + other market participant assumptions\n\nWHEN FV IS NOT RELIABLY MEASURABLE (exceptional cases only):\nArises when BOTH conditions exist:\n(a) Market for comparable properties is INACTIVE (few transactions, non-current price quotes, distressed sales); AND\n(b) Alternative reliable FV measurements (e.g., DCF projections) are NOT available\n\nDisclosure when FV not reliably measurable:\n(i) Description of the IP\n(ii) Explanation of why FV cannot be measured reliably\n(iii) If possible, range of estimates within which FV is likely to lie\n\n📌 REBUTTABLE PRESUMPTION: Entity CAN reliably measure FV of IP on a continuing basis\n📌 If FV was previously measured → must continue measuring FV until disposal (even if market becomes less active)",
    exam:true },

  // ── PRACTICAL ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:112, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Cost Build-Up — Joining Fee & Apportionment\n[Illustration 2 — Netravati Ltd.]\n\nNetravati Ltd. purchases office space as Investment Property for ₹5 crores. To purchase, it must obtain mandatory membership of the Complex Association: one-time joining fee ₹6,25,000.\n\nNetravati wants to write off ₹6,25,000 as Membership & Subscription Charges and value IP at ₹5 crores.\n\nAdvise. Also comment if the property was for admin use instead.",
    back:"PART 1 — INVESTMENT PROPERTY:\nAs per Ind AS 40, cost of a purchased IP = purchase price + any DIRECTLY ATTRIBUTABLE expenditure (legal fees, transfer taxes, other transaction costs).\n\nThe one-time joining fee was MANDATORY to acquire the property → it is a directly attributable transaction cost.\n\n✅ Correct cost of IP = ₹5,00,00,000 + ₹6,25,000 = ₹5,06,25,000\n\nWriting off ₹6,25,000 as Membership & Subscription is NOT appropriate.\n\n─────────────────────────────────\nPART 2 — IF USED AS ADMINISTRATIVE OFFICE:\n→ Property is then OWNER-OCCUPIED PROPERTY → NOT investment property\n→ Ind AS 16 (PPE) applies instead\n→ Under Ind AS 16, all direct costs related to acquisition are also added to purchase price\n→ Cost under Ind AS 16 would ALSO be ₹5,06,25,000 (same amount, different classification)\n\n📌 KEY POINT: The joining fee is capitalized REGARDLESS of whether it's classified as IP or OOP — the cost treatment principle is identical",
    exam:true },

  { id:113, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Cost Computation — Multiple Costs Including Refundable Taxes\n[Illustration 3 — X Limited]\n\nX Ltd. purchased a building for ₹30,00,000 on 1 May 20X1 to earn rentals.\nLoan funded (interest @ 5%); building does NOT qualify substantial period criteria under Ind AS 23.\nOther costs:\n• Property transfer taxes: ₹1,00,000\n• Direct legal costs: ₹20,000\n• Planning permission: ₹2,00,000\n• Construction costs: ₹7,00,000 (incl. ₹40,000 REFUNDABLE purchase taxes)\n\nCompute cost of the building as per Ind AS 40.",
    back:"Cost computation per Ind AS 40:\n\n Particulars                            ₹\n Purchase price                   30,00,000\n Property transfer taxes            1,00,000\n Direct legal costs                    20,000\n Fee for planning permission        2,00,000\n Construction costs      7,00,000\n Less: Refundable taxes    (40,000)   6,60,000\n ─────────────────────────────────────────\n COST OF BUILDING (Ind AS 40)        39,80,000\n\n📌 KEY RULES APPLIED:\n→ Refundable taxes (₹40,000): EXCLUDED — these are recoverable, so they do not form part of cost\n→ Non-refundable transfer taxes (₹1,00,000): INCLUDED — directly attributable, non-recoverable\n→ Borrowing costs (loan interest @ 5%): NOT capitalized — building does not meet the 'substantial period of time' criteria for a qualifying asset under Ind AS 23\n→ Planning permission + legal costs: ✅ directly attributable → INCLUDED\n\n📌 Interest cost on the loan goes to P&L as finance cost, NOT to cost of building",
    exam:true },

  { id:114, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Deferred Payment — Cost vs Total Payments\n[Illustration 4 — X Limited]\n\nX Limited purchased land worth ₹1,00,00,000.\nOption 1: Pay full ₹1,00,00,000 now.\nOption 2: Pay ₹1,20,00,000 over two years (deferred).\n\nDetermine the cost of the land under both payment options.\nWhat happens to the ₹20,00,000 difference under Option 2?",
    back:"OPTION 1 — Immediate payment:\nCost of land = ₹1,00,00,000 (straightforward)\n\nOPTION 2 — Deferred payment (₹1,20,00,000 over 2 years):\nCost of land = CASH PRICE EQUIVALENT = ₹1,00,00,000\n\nTreatment of ₹20,00,000 difference:\n→ ₹20,00,000 = difference between total deferred payments and cash price equivalent\n→ Recognized as INTEREST EXPENSE in P&L over the 2-year credit period\n→ NOT added to cost of the land\n\n📌 RULE: When payment is deferred beyond normal credit terms, cost = cash price equivalent (present value of future payments).\n\n📌 REGARDLESS of which payment option is chosen → the COST OF THE ASSET IS THE SAME: ₹1,00,00,000.\n\n📌 The ₹20,00,000 represents the time value of money / financing cost — same principle as Ind AS 38 for intangible assets with deferred consideration.",
    exam:false },

  { id:115, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Exchange of Assets — Journal Entries\n[Example 5 — Sun Ltd.]\n\nSun Ltd. acquires a building (for rental) by exchanging:\n• Warehouse (FV = ₹5,00,000) given up\n• Cash paid = ₹2,00,000\n• FV of building received = ₹8,00,000\n\nPass journal entries under:\n(A) Default — FV of asset given up is the cost basis\n(B) FV of building received is MORE CLEARLY EVIDENT",
    back:"Both journal entries in Sun Ltd.'s books:\n\n(A) DEFAULT — FV of asset GIVEN UP used as cost:\nCost of building = FV of warehouse + cash = ₹5,00,000 + ₹2,00,000 = ₹7,00,000\n\n Investment Property (Building)  Dr. 7,00,000\n   To Cash                                    2,00,000\n   To PPE (Warehouse)                         5,00,000\n\nNo gain or loss — asset given up is removed at its FV.\n\n─────────────────────────────────\n(B) FV RECEIVED (₹8,00,000) MORE CLEARLY EVIDENT — use FV of asset received:\nCost of building = ₹8,00,000\n\n Investment Property (Building)  Dr. 8,00,000\n   To Cash                                    2,00,000\n   To PPE (Warehouse)                         5,00,000\n   To Gain on Sale of PPE                     1,00,000\n\n📌 KEY RULE: When BOTH FVs are stated and equally evident → use FV of asset GIVEN UP (default)\n📌 If FV of asset received is MORE CLEARLY EVIDENT → use FV of asset received\n📌 Gain = FV received (₹8L) − FV given up (₹7L incl. cash) = ₹1L → recognized in P&L\n📌 If exchange lacks commercial substance or neither FV measurable → use CARRYING AMOUNT of asset given up (no gain/loss)",
    exam:true },

  { id:116, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: PPE → Investment Property Transfer (Cost Model)\n[Illustration 5 — Moon Ltd.]\n\nMoon Ltd. purchased a building on 1 Apr 20X1:\n• Cost: ₹10 million | Useful life: 10 years | Cost model (Ind AS 16)\nOn 1 Apr 20X5: Company no longer needs the factory; rents it out to a third party.\nOn reclassification date: Fair value = ₹8 million.\n\nMoon Ltd. uses COST MODEL for investment property.\n\nDetermine the value of the building on reclassification.",
    back:"Step 1: Carrying amount after 4 years of depreciation:\nCA = ₹10M − (10/10 × 4) = ₹10M − ₹4M = ₹6 million\n\nStep 2: Assess impairment at transfer date:\nFair value (₹8M) > CA (₹6M) → No impairment\n\nStep 3: Revaluation surplus?\n→ Moon Ltd. applied COST MODEL under Ind AS 16 (not revaluation model)\n→ Therefore NO revaluation surplus to transfer to OCI\n→ Entry: No adjustment needed — carry at existing CA\n\nStep 4: Building initially recognized as Investment Property (Ind AS 40 — cost model):\n→ ₹6 million\n\n📌 RULE: Transfers between investment property, owner-occupied property and inventories do NOT change the carrying amount of the property transferred (para 59 of Ind AS 40).\n\n📌 If entity had been using the REVALUATION MODEL under Ind AS 16 and FV > CA at transfer:\n→ First record revaluation increase to FV → Revaluation Surplus to OCI\n→ Then transfer to IP at that revalued amount\n📌 Fair value (₹8M) is ONLY FOR DISCLOSURE under Ind AS 40 — not the balance sheet amount",
    exam:true },

  { id:117, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Disposal of Investment Property — Two Methods\n[Example 6 — Sun Ltd.]\n\nSun Ltd. holds a building given on an operating lease.\nBook value: ₹2,00,000.\n\nCase A: Pluto Ltd. offers to BUY the building at ₹4,00,000.\n\nCase B: Pluto Ltd. offers to take the building on FINANCE LEASE for 10 years.\nLease rental: ₹80,000 p.a. | PV of minimum lease payments: ₹3,20,000\n\nPass journal entries for both cases in Sun Ltd.'s books.",
    back:"CASE A — SALE (Disposal by outright sale):\n\n Bank A/c                         Dr. 4,00,000\n   To Investment Property                   2,00,000\n   To Gain on Disposal                      2,00,000\n\nGain = Net sale proceeds (₹4,00,000) − Carrying amount (₹2,00,000) = ₹2,00,000 → P&L\n\n─────────────────────────────────\nCASE B — FINANCE LEASE (Disposal by entering into finance lease):\n\n Lease Receivable                 Dr. 3,20,000\n   To Investment Property                   2,00,000\n   To Gain on Disposal                      1,20,000\n\nGain = PV of MLP (₹3,20,000) − Carrying amount (₹2,00,000) = ₹1,20,000 → P&L\n→ Ind AS 116 applies to disposal effected by entering into a finance lease\n\n📌 Date of disposal = date recipient obtains CONTROL of the IP (per Ind AS 115)\n📌 Deferred consideration on disposal: initially recognized at FAIR VALUE; if payment is deferred → cash price equivalent; difference = INTEREST REVENUE (not gain on disposal)\n📌 Compensation from third parties for IP impaired/lost → P&L when receivable\n📌 Impairments, disposals, compensation and replacement costs = SEPARATE ECONOMIC EVENTS → accounted separately",
    exam:true },

  { id:118, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: IP → Inventory Transfer + Carrying Value Calculation\n[TYK Q4 — X Ltd.]\n\nX Ltd. (construction industry):\n• 1 Apr 20X1: Purchased land for ₹2,00,00,000; immediately leased to Y Ltd. (operating lease, ₹20,00,000 p.a.)\n• 31 Mar 20X5: Y Ltd. gave 6-month notice to cancel lease\n• 30 Sep 20X5: Y Ltd. vacated; FV = ₹2,90,00,000\n• 1 Oct 20X5: X Ltd. begins converting land into 10 flats for SALE; spends ₹60,00,000 by 31 Mar 20X6\n• Remaining costs to complete: ₹40,00,000; expected sale price per flat: ₹50,00,000\n\nShow how the 3 events are reported in FS for year ended 31 Mar 20X6.",
    back:"EVENT 1 — INVESTMENT PROPERTY (1 Apr 20X1 to 30 Sep 20X5):\n→ Land = IP; measured at COST MODEL = ₹2,00,00,000 at each year-end (land is not depreciated)\n→ Rental income for year ended 31 Mar 20X6 (operating lease, 6 months):\n₹20,00,000 × 6/12 = ₹10,00,000 → recognized in P&L\n\n─────────────────────────────────\nEVENT 2 — TRANSFER: IP → INVENTORY (30 Sep 20X5):\n→ Commencement of development for SALE = change in use → reclassify from IP to Inventories (Ind AS 2)\n→ Per para 59 Ind AS 40: transfer does NOT change carrying amount\n→ Inventory cost at transfer = ₹2,00,00,000 (same CA — ignoring FV of ₹2,90,00,000)\n\n─────────────────────────────────\nEVENT 3 — INVENTORY (31 Mar 20X6):\nCost of inventory:\nCA at transfer:            ₹2,00,00,000\nAdd: Development costs:    ₹  60,00,000\nTotal cost:                ₹2,60,00,000\n\nNRV test:\nTotal expected sale:        ₹5,00,00,000 (10 × ₹50L)\nLess: Remaining costs:     (₹  40,00,000)\nNRV:                        ₹4,60,00,000\n\nCost (₹2.6Cr) < NRV (₹4.6Cr) → No write-down → Inventory at ₹2,60,00,000 ✅\n→ Shown as CURRENT ASSET in balance sheet",
    exam:true },

  { id:119, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: 6-House Property — Cost Apportionment Between IP and OOP\n[TYK Q3 — X Limited]\n\nX Ltd. acquires a property of 6 identical houses, each with separate legal title:\n• 1 Apr 20X1: Purchase cost ₹1,80,00,000\n• Non-refundable transfer taxes (not in purchase cost): ₹20,00,000\n• Legal cost for acquisition (2 Apr 20X1): ₹5,00,000\n• Advertisement campaign to attract tenants (6 Apr 20X1): ₹3,00,000\n• Opening ceremony (8 Apr 20X1): ₹1,50,000\n• Repair & maintenance + admin throughout year: ₹1,00,000\n\nX Ltd. uses 1 house for office/staff; 5 houses rented to independent third parties.\n\nHow should X Ltd. account for all the above?",
    back:"STEP 1 — Total cost of property:\nPurchase price:              ₹1,80,00,000\nNon-refundable transfer tax:   ₹ 20,00,000\nLegal costs (directly attributable): ₹5,00,000\nTotal cost:                  ₹2,05,00,000\n\n📌 Each house has SEPARATE LEGAL TITLE → can be sold separately → able to split\n\nSTEP 2 — Apportion cost:\nIP (5/6 — rented):   ₹2,05,00,000 × 5/6 = ₹1,70,83,333 → Ind AS 40\nOOP (1/6 — office): ₹2,05,00,000 × 1/6 = ₹  34,16,667 → Ind AS 16\n\nSTEP 3 — Other expenditures:\n✅ Advertisement (₹3,00,000) → EXPENSE in P&L\n(Not directly attributable to bringing property to use; treated as start-up/promotional cost)\n✅ Opening ceremony (₹1,50,000) → EXPENSE in P&L\n✅ Repairs & maintenance + admin (₹1,00,000) → EXPENSE in P&L\n(Day-to-day servicing costs → always P&L)\n\n📌 KEY: Separate legal titles allow the property to be sold separately → SPLIT treatment possible\n📌 If separate titles did NOT exist → use the Dual Purpose rule: classify entire property based on whether OOP portion is significant or insignificant",
    exam:true },

  // ── THEORY Q&A ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:120, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"When and how are TRANSFERS to/from Investment Property made?\nWhat are the 4 types of transfers with their evidence?\nWhat happens to the CARRYING AMOUNT on transfer?\nWhat happens if an entity decides to DISPOSE of IP without development?",
    back:"FUNDAMENTAL RULE: Transfer to/from IP only when there is a CHANGE IN USE.\n→ Change in use = property meets OR ceases to meet definition of IP AND there is EVIDENCE of that change\n→ Management's intention to change use ALONE is NOT sufficient evidence\n\n4 TYPES OF TRANSFERS:\n(a) IP → PPE (Ind AS 16):\nEvidence: Commencement of owner-occupation, or development with view to owner-occupation\n\n(b) IP → Inventories (Ind AS 2):\nEvidence: Commencement of development with a view to SALE\n\n(c) PPE (Ind AS 16) → IP:\nEvidence: End of owner-occupation (entity stops using property for own operations)\n\n(d) Inventories (Ind AS 2) → IP:\nEvidence: Inception of an operating lease to another party\n\nCARRYING AMOUNT ON TRANSFER:\n→ Transfers do NOT change the carrying amount of the property\n→ Transfers do NOT change the cost for measurement or disclosure purposes\n→ Under cost model: carry over the existing CA — no revaluation gain/loss recognized\n\nDISPOSAL WITHOUT DEVELOPMENT:\n→ Entity continues to treat property as IP until it is DERECOGNIZED\n→ Does NOT reclassify as inventory merely because it intends to dispose\n\n📌 IP being REDEVELOPED for CONTINUED future use as IP:\n→ Remains classified as IP throughout redevelopment (NOT reclassified as OOP)",
    exam:true },

  { id:121, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"How is the DISPOSAL of Investment Property treated?\nWhat are the 3 ways to derecognize IP?\nHow is GAIN OR LOSS calculated and where is it recognized?\nHow is DEFERRED CONSIDERATION treated on disposal?\nHow is COMPENSATION from third parties treated?",
    back:"DERECOGNIZE (eliminate from balance sheet) investment property:\n(a) ON DISPOSAL: by sale, OR by entering into a finance lease\n(b) When IP is PERMANENTLY WITHDRAWN FROM USE and no future economic benefits expected from disposal\n\nDATE OF DISPOSAL:\n→ Date recipient obtains CONTROL of the IP per Ind AS 115 (when performance obligation satisfied)\n→ Disposal by finance lease / sale-leaseback → Ind AS 116 applies\n\nGAIN OR LOSS ON DISPOSAL:\nGain/Loss = Net Disposal Proceeds − Carrying Amount of Asset\n→ Recognized in PROFIT OR LOSS in the period of retirement/disposal\n→ Exception: Sale and leaseback → Ind AS 116 may require otherwise\n\nCONSIDERATION ON DISPOSAL:\n→ Initially recognized at FAIR VALUE\n→ If payment is DEFERRED:\n   • Recognize initially at CASH PRICE EQUIVALENT\n   • Difference between nominal consideration and cash price equivalent = INTEREST REVENUE (not additional gain)\n\nCOMPENSATION FROM THIRD PARTIES:\n→ For IP that was impaired, lost or given up:\n→ Recognize in P&L WHEN COMPENSATION BECOMES RECEIVABLE\n\n📌 4 SEPARATE ECONOMIC EVENTS — treated independently:\n1. Impairments → Ind AS 36\n2. Retirements/disposals → Ind AS 40\n3. Third-party compensation → P&L when receivable\n4. Cost of replacement assets → Ind AS 40",
    exam:true },

  { id:122, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the DISCLOSURE REQUIREMENTS under Ind AS 40?\nList:\n(a) General disclosures\n(b) Additional disclosures for cost model\n(c) Carrying amount reconciliation items\n(d) Disclosure when FV cannot be measured reliably",
    back:"GENERAL DISCLOSURES:\n1. Accounting policy for measurement of IP\n2. When classification is difficult: criteria used to distinguish IP from OOP and from property held for sale\n3. Extent to which FV of IP is based on independent valuer's valuation (if no such valuation → disclose that fact)\n4. Amounts recognized in P&L:\n   (a) Rental income from IP\n   (b) Direct operating expenses (incl. repairs & maintenance) from IP that GENERATED rental income\n   (c) Direct operating expenses from IP that did NOT generate rental income\n5. Existence and amounts of RESTRICTIONS on realisability of IP or remittance of income/disposal proceeds\n6. Contractual obligations to purchase, construct or develop IP or for repairs/maintenance/enhancements\n\nADDITIONAL DISCLOSURES (Cost Model):\n7. Depreciation methods used\n8. Useful lives or depreciation rates\n9. Gross CA + accumulated depreciation (+ impairment losses) at beginning and end of period\n10. FV of IP (even under cost model — mandatory disclosure)\n\nCARRYING AMOUNT RECONCILIATION:\nAdditions (from acquisitions; from subsequent expenditure as asset; from business combinations); disposals; assets held for sale (Ind AS 105); depreciation; impairment losses recognized/reversed; net exchange differences; transfers to/from inventories and OOP; other changes\n\nWHEN FV NOT RELIABLY MEASURABLE:\n(a) Description of the IP\n(b) Explanation of why FV cannot be measured reliably\n(c) If possible, range of estimates within which FV is likely to lie",
    exam:false },

  { id:123, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the KEY DIFFERENCES between Ind AS 40 and IAS 40 (IFRS)?\nAnd where does Indian GAAP (AS) differ from Ind AS 40?\nList at least 5 differences across both comparisons.",
    back:"IND AS 40 vs IAS 40 (IFRS) — KEY DIFFERENCES:\n\n1. MEASUREMENT MODEL:\nIAS 40 (IFRS): Choice between COST MODEL or FAIR VALUE MODEL as accounting policy\nInd AS 40: COST MODEL ONLY — no choice; FV used for disclosure only\n\n2. P&L IMPACT OF FV CHANGES:\nIAS 40 (FV model): FV changes recognized in P&L each period → can create volatility\nInd AS 40: No FV changes in P&L; depreciation + impairment only\n\n3. DISCLOSURE OF FV:\nBoth: Mandatory disclosure of FV even under cost model\nInd AS 40: Independent valuer encouraged but not required (same as IAS 40)\n\n4. RIGHT-OF-USE ASSETS:\nBoth: A lessee can classify ROU asset as IP if it meets the definition\nBoth: IP held as ROU asset → initially measured per Ind AS 116 / IFRS 16\n\n5. TRANSFERS UNDER FAIR VALUE MODEL:\nIAS 40: When property transfers from IP (FV model) to PPE/Inventory → FV at date of transfer = deemed cost\nInd AS 40: Transfers at carrying amount (cost model) → no such adjustment needed\n\n─────────────────────────────────\nIND AS 40 vs INDIAN GAAP (AS 13/AS 10) — KEY DIFFERENCES:\n• No dedicated Indian GAAP standard for investment property — covered by AS 13 (Investments) or AS 10 (PPE)\n• Ind AS 40 provides a distinct classification of investment property as a separate category\n• Ind AS 40 mandates FV disclosure; Indian GAAP has no such requirement for property\n• Ind AS 40 allows ROU assets to be classified as IP; Indian GAAP has no concept of ROU assets",
    exam:false },

  // ── QUICK FIRE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:124, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ TRUE or FALSE (Ind AS 40):\n\nA. Under Ind AS 40, entities may choose the fair value model as their accounting policy.\nB. Day-to-day repair and maintenance costs of IP are added to the carrying amount.\nC. A property leased to a subsidiary is classified as IP in the subsidiary's individual financial statements.\nD. Management's declared intention to change the use of a property is sufficient to trigger a reclassification.\nE. When an entity disposes of IP via a finance lease, a gain may still arise.\nF. An entity can reclassify IP as inventory when it decides to sell it without any development work.\nG. FV of IP must be disclosed even when the cost model is used.",
    back:"A. FALSE ❌\n→ Ind AS 40 mandates ONLY the cost model. The choice between cost model and fair value model (as in IAS 40) is NOT available under Indian Accounting Standards.\n\nB. FALSE ❌\n→ Day-to-day servicing costs (labour, consumables, minor parts / repairs & maintenance) are recognized in PROFIT OR LOSS as incurred — NOT added to carrying amount.\n\nC. FALSE ❌\n→ It is the LESSOR (the entity that owns the property and leases it TO the subsidiary) that classifies the property as IP in its individual FS. The subsidiary (lessee) would recognize a right-of-use asset.\n\nD. FALSE ❌\n→ Management's intention alone does NOT provide evidence of a change in use. Evidence is required (e.g., actual commencement of owner-occupation, actual commencement of development for sale, actual start of operating lease to third party).\n\nE. TRUE ✅\n→ When IP is disposed of via a finance lease, gain = PV of MLP − Carrying amount. A gain arises if PV of MLP > CA (as in Example 6 where gain = ₹3,20,000 − ₹2,00,000 = ₹1,20,000).\n\nF. FALSE ❌\n→ If entity decides to dispose of IP WITHOUT development, it continues to treat the property as IP until derecognized. It does NOT reclassify as inventory.\n\nG. TRUE ✅\n→ All entities applying the cost model MUST STILL measure and disclose the fair value of IP in their financial statements (in notes). This is a mandatory disclosure requirement.",
    exam:false },

  { id:125, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 40", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ IDENTIFY: Investment Property / Not Investment Property:\nFor each, state the classification AND the applicable Ind AS.\n\nA. Office building owned by company, used by its own employees\nB. Warehouse leased out under an operating lease\nC. Apartment complex under construction, intended for sale\nD. Land purchased — use not yet decided\nE. Hotel owned and operated by the owner (owner serves guests)\nF. Office building providing security/maintenance to lessees\nG. Shopping mall leased out under operating leases; owner only collects rent\nH. IP being redeveloped for SALE as residential flats\nI. Investment property held for sale (disposal criteria met per Ind AS 105)\nJ. ROU asset (leased-in building) subleased to third party under operating lease",
    back:"A. Office building — used by own employees → ❌ NOT IP → OOP → Ind AS 16\n\nB. Warehouse — operating lease to third party → ✅ IP → Ind AS 40\n\nC. Apartment complex under construction — intended for SALE → ❌ NOT IP → Inventory → Ind AS 2\n\nD. Land — use not yet decided → ✅ IP (Ind AS 40)\n(Treated as held for capital appreciation until decision made)\n\nE. Hotel — owner managed (serves guests) → ❌ NOT IP → OOP → Ind AS 16\n(Services are significant to the arrangement as a whole)\n\nF. Office building — security/maintenance to lessees → ✅ IP → Ind AS 40\n(Services are INSIGNIFICANT to arrangement as a whole)\n\nG. Shopping mall — operating leases, owner only collects rent → ✅ IP → Ind AS 40\n(No significant services beyond rent collection)\n\nH. IP being redeveloped for SALE → ❌ NOT IP → Inventory → Ind AS 2\n(Change in use from IP to inventory — evidence: commencement of development for sale)\n\nI. IP held for sale (Ind AS 105 criteria met) → ❌ NOT IP → Ind AS 105\n\nJ. ROU asset (leased building) subleased under operating lease → ✅ IP → Ind AS 40\n(Lessee can classify ROU asset as IP if it meets the definition)\n\n📌 COMMON TRAP: Redeveloping existing IP for CONTINUED IP use → remains IP throughout (not reclassified)",
    exam:true },

  // FR · Ind AS 41
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  // IND AS 41 – AGRICULTURE
  // ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  // ── CONCEPT ──────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:300, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Objective & Introduction\n\nWhat is the core objective of Ind AS 41?\nWhat significant accounting shift does it introduce?\nWhat 3 items does it apply to?",
    back:"Ind AS 41 is the FIRST standard specifically covering accounting and reporting for the primary sector (agriculture and allied industries).\n\nCore objective:\n→ Prescribe accounting for agricultural activity — the management of biological transformation of biological assets into agricultural produce.\n→ Generally requires biological assets to be measured at FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL.\n\nSignificant shift:\n→ Introduces FAIR VALUE MODEL (departure from traditional cost model widely used in primary industry)\n\nApplies to the following (when they relate to agricultural activity):\n(a) Biological assets\n(b) Agricultural produce at the point of harvest\n(c) Government grants\n\nKey issues addressed:\n(a) When to recognise a biological asset or agricultural produce on the balance sheet\n(b) At what value to measure a recognised biological asset or agricultural produce\n(c) How to account for differences in value between two reporting dates\n(d) What disclosures are required" },

  { id:301, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Scope Exclusions\n\nList the items to which Ind AS 41 does NOT apply.\nFor bearer plants, what is the key exception?\nWhen does Ind AS 41 apply to agricultural produce?",
    back:"Ind AS 41 does NOT apply to:\n\n(a) Land related to agricultural activity → Ind AS 16 / Ind AS 40\n(b) Bearer plants related to agricultural activity → Ind AS 16\n   ✅ EXCEPTION: Standard APPLIES to the PRODUCE growing ON bearer plants\n(c) Government grants related to bearer plants → Ind AS 20\n(d) Intangible assets associated with agricultural activity (e.g., licences, rights) → Ind AS 38\n(e) Right-of-use assets arising from lease of land related to agricultural activity → Ind AS 116\n\nAgricultural produce:\n→ Ind AS 41 applies ONLY at the POINT OF HARVEST\n→ BEFORE harvest: produce is part of the biological asset (NOT accounted separately)\n→ AFTER harvest: Ind AS 2 or another applicable standard applies\n\nExamples:\n| Biological Asset | Agricultural Produce | Post-Harvest Product |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sheep | Wool | Yarn, carpet |\n| Dairy cattle | Milk | Cheese |\n| Tea bushes (bearer) | Picked leaves | Tea |\n| Grape vines (bearer) | Picked grapes | Wine |" },

  { id:302, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Agricultural Activity\n\nDefine agricultural activity.\nState the 3 common features ALL agricultural activities share.\nGive 2 examples of activities that are NOT agricultural activity.",
    back:"Agricultural activity: Management by an entity of the BIOLOGICAL TRANSFORMATION and HARVEST of biological assets for SALE or for conversion into AGRICULTURAL PRODUCE or into ADDITIONAL BIOLOGICAL ASSETS.\n\nCovers: raising livestock, forestry, annual/perennial cropping, cultivating orchards and plantations, floriculture, aquaculture (fish farming).\n\n3 Common features:\n\nI. CAPABILITY TO CHANGE\n   Living animals and plants are capable of biological transformation\n\nII. MANAGEMENT OF CHANGE\n   Management facilitates biological transformation by enhancing or at least stabilising conditions (nutrient levels, moisture, temperature, fertility, light)\n   → This distinguishes agricultural activity from OTHER activities\n\nIII. MEASUREMENT OF CHANGE\n   Change in quality (genetic merit, density, ripeness, fat cover, protein content, fibre strength) or quantity (progeny, weight, cubic metres, fibre length, number of buds) is measured and monitored as a routine management function\n\nNOT agricultural activity:\n✗ Harvesting from UNMANAGED SOURCES (ocean fishing, deforestation)\n✗ Processing AFTER HARVEST (brewing beer, cheese production, wine making)\n✗ Managing recreational animals (zoo)\n✗ Guard/security animals (dogs for security)" },

  { id:303, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Biological Asset & Biological Transformation\n\nDefine: Biological Asset | Biological Transformation\nState and explain the 4 processes of biological transformation.",
    back:"Biological Asset: A LIVING ANIMAL OR PLANT.\n\nBiological transformation: Comprises the processes of growth, degeneration, production, and procreation that cause QUALITATIVE or QUANTITATIVE changes in a biological asset.\n\n4 Processes:\n\n1. GROWTH\n   An increase in quantity OR improvement in quality of an animal or plant\n   Example: Weight gain in cattle; increase in height of trees\n\n2. DEGENERATION\n   A decrease in quantity OR deterioration in quality of an animal or plant\n   Example: Ageing of livestock beyond productive prime\n\n3. PRODUCTION\n   Of agricultural produce such as latex, tea leaf, wool, and milk\n   Example: Dairy cow producing milk\n\n4. PROCREATION\n   Creation of additional living animals or plants\n   Example: Birth of a calf from a dairy cow → gain recognised immediately in P&L\n\n📌 Unharvested agricultural produce is PART OF THE BIOLOGICAL ASSET until the moment of harvest.\nExample: Milk is part of the dairy cow right up to the moment at which the cow is milked.\n\n📌 Processing after harvest (brewing beer, cheese making) does NOT constitute biological transformation and falls OUTSIDE Ind AS 41." },

  { id:304, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Agricultural Produce & Harvest\n\nDefine: Agricultural Produce | Harvest\n\nHow is agricultural produce treated:\n(a) Before harvest?\n(b) At the point of harvest?\n(c) After harvest?",
    back:"Agricultural produce: The HARVESTED PRODUCT of the entity's biological assets.\n\nHarvest: The DETACHMENT of produce from a biological asset OR the CESSATION of a biological asset's life processes.\n\nTreatment at 3 stages:\n\n(a) BEFORE HARVEST:\n→ Unharvested produce is part of the BIOLOGICAL ASSET\n→ NOT accounted for separately from the biological asset\n→ Example: Milk is part of the dairy cow until the moment of milking\n\n(b) AT THE POINT OF HARVEST:\n→ Ind AS 41 APPLIES\n→ Measured at FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL\n→ This FV less CTS becomes the COST for Ind AS 2 purposes (deemed cost)\n→ Standard states: FV of agricultural produce at harvest can ALWAYS be measured reliably — no exception\n\n(c) AFTER HARVEST:\n→ Ind AS 41 CEASES to apply\n→ Ind AS 2 (Inventories) or another applicable standard applies\n\nExamples:\n| Biological Asset | Agri. Produce | Post-Harvest |\n|---|---|---|\n| Dairy cattle | Milk | Cheese |\n| Sheep | Wool | Yarn, carpet |\n| Grape vines | Picked grapes | Wine |\n| Cotton plants | Harvested cotton | Thread, clothing |" },

  { id:305, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Bearer Plant\n\nDefine bearer plant. State all 3 criteria (ALL must be met).\nWhich standard governs bearer plants? Which governs produce on them?\nWhat is NEVER a bearer plant?",
    back:"Bearer plant: A LIVING PLANT that:\n(i) Is used in the PRODUCTION OR SUPPLY of agricultural produce\n(ii) Is expected to bear produce for MORE THAN ONE PERIOD\n(iii) Has a REMOTE LIKELIHOOD of being sold as agricultural produce, except for incidental scrap sales\n\n→ ALL THREE criteria must be met simultaneously.\n\nApplicable standards:\n→ BEARER PLANTS themselves → IND AS 16 (PPE)\n→ PRODUCE growing ON bearer plants → IND AS 41\n\nExamples of bearer plants (Ind AS 16):\nTea bushes → tea leaves (Ind AS 41)\nGrape vines → picked grapes (Ind AS 41)\nOil palms → oil palm fruit (Ind AS 41)\nRubber trees → harvested latex (Ind AS 41)\n\nNOT bearer plants:\n❌ Annual crops (maize, wheat, soya) — held solely to be harvested as produce\n❌ Trees grown for lumber — the tree itself is the product\n❌ Dual-use plants — where more than remote likelihood of being sold as agricultural produce itself (e.g. rubber trees sold for both latex AND lumber)\n❌ ANIMALS (sheep, cows etc.) — NEVER bearer plants; always biological assets under Ind AS 41\n\nNote: Root systems of perennial plants (sugar cane, bamboo, asparagus) → typically bearer plants despite appearing consumable." },

  { id:306, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Recognition of Biological Assets\n\nState the 3 conditions for recognising a biological asset or agricultural produce.\nHow is CONTROL over biological assets evidenced?\nWhat happens once a non-current biological asset meets Ind AS 105 criteria?",
    back:"Recognise a biological asset or agricultural produce WHEN AND ONLY WHEN all 3 conditions are met:\n\n1. CONTROL\n   The entity controls the asset as a result of past events\n   Evidence of control: legal ownership, branding or otherwise marking of cattle on acquisition, birth, or weaning\n\n2. PROBABLE FUTURE ECONOMIC BENEFITS\n   Future economic benefits associated with the asset will probably flow to the entity\n   → Normally assessed by measuring significant physical attributes\n\n3. FAIR VALUE OR COST MEASURABLE RELIABLY\n   The fair value or cost of the asset can be measured reliably\n\n📌 There is a PRESUMPTION that fair value CAN be measured reliably for any biological asset. This presumption can be rebutted only on initial recognition.\n\n📌 Ind AS 105 (Held for Sale):\nOnce a non-current biological asset meets the criteria to be classified as held for sale (or is included in a disposal group classified as HFS), it is PRESUMED that fair value can be measured reliably — no exception allowed." },

  { id:307, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Measurement of Biological Assets\n\nAt what amount are biological assets measured?\nState the EXCEPTION (2 conditions) and the critical rules around it.\nWhen may cost approximate fair value?",
    back:"General rule:\n→ Measured at FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL at:\n   • Initial recognition, AND\n   • End of EACH REPORTING PERIOD\n\nPresumption: Fair value CAN always be measured reliably.\n\nEXCEPTION — use COST MODEL only when BOTH apply:\n(i) Quoted market prices are NOT available for the biological asset, AND\n(ii) Alternative fair value measurements are determined to be CLEARLY UNRELIABLE\n→ Measure at: COST LESS ACCUMULATED DEPRECIATION LESS ACCUMULATED IMPAIRMENT LOSSES\n   (per Ind AS 2, Ind AS 16 and Ind AS 36 as applicable)\n\nCritical rules on the exception:\n→ Presumption can be REBUTTED ONLY ON INITIAL RECOGNITION\n→ Once an entity has measured a biological asset at FV less CTS → must CONTINUE at FV less CTS until disposal (cannot revert to cost later)\n→ Once FV becomes reliably measurable → must switch to FV less CTS model\n\nContract prices:\n→ NOT relevant to FV measurement; FV reflects current market conditions\n→ FV of biological asset NOT adjusted because of existence of a contract\n\nCost may APPROXIMATE FV when:\n(a) Little biological transformation since initial cost incurrence (e.g., fruit tree seedlings planted just before period end; newly acquired livestock)\n(b) Impact of biological transformation on price not expected to be material (e.g., initial growth in a 30-year pine plantation)" },

  { id:308, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Measurement of Agricultural Produce\n\nHow is agricultural produce measured at the point of harvest?\nIs there any exception (like there is for biological assets)?\nHow is land + biological asset combined value split?",
    back:"Agricultural produce measurement:\n→ Measured at FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL at the POINT OF HARVEST\n→ This measurement becomes the COST for Ind AS 2 purposes thereafter (deemed cost)\n\nNo exception applies:\n→ The standard states that fair value of agricultural produce at the point of harvest can ALWAYS be measured reliably\n→ Unlike biological assets, NO cost-model fallback available for agricultural produce\n\nGrouping for FV measurement:\n→ FV measurement may be facilitated by grouping biological assets or agricultural produce by significant attributes (e.g. age, quality)\n→ Entity selects attributes corresponding to those used in the market as the basis for pricing\n\nFair value can change due to:\n→ Both PHYSICAL CHANGES (e.g. ageing, growth) and PRICE CHANGES in the market\n\nLand + Biological Assets combined:\n→ Biological assets often physically attached to land (e.g. trees in a plantation forest)\n→ No separate market may exist for the biological asset alone, but an active market may exist for the COMBINED PACKAGE (biological assets + raw land + land improvements)\n→ Method: Deduct (FV of raw land + FV of land improvements) from combined FV → arrive at FV of biological assets alone" },

  { id:309, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Gains and Losses\n\nHow are gains and losses from biological assets treated?\nHow are gains and losses from agricultural produce treated?\nGive 2 examples of when a LOSS and a GAIN arise on initial recognition.",
    back:"BIOLOGICAL ASSETS — Gains and Losses:\n→ Gain or loss on INITIAL RECOGNITION at FV less CTS → P&L in the period it arises\n→ Gain or loss from CHANGE IN FV less CTS at each reporting date → P&L in the period it arises\n\nAGRICULTURAL PRODUCE — Gains and Losses:\n→ Gain or loss on INITIAL RECOGNITION at FV less CTS → P&L in the period it arises\n→ A gain or loss may arise on initial recognition of agricultural produce as a result of HARVESTING\n\nSummary:\n| Source | Occasion | Recognition |\n|---|---|---|\n| Biological asset | Initial recognition | P&L immediately |\n| Biological asset | Change in FV at period end | P&L in period |\n| Agricultural produce | Initial recognition (harvest) | P&L immediately |\n\nLOSS on initial recognition:\n→ Costs to sell are deducted from fair value → FV less CTS < cash paid → loss arises\nExample: Sheep purchased at auction — transport + auctioneer fee deducted → immediate loss\n\nGAIN on initial recognition:\n→ When a new biological asset comes into existence (procreation)\nExample: Calf born during period → FV less CTS of ₹5,000 recognised immediately as INCOME in P&L" },

  { id:310, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Government Grants\n\nExplain the two tracks for government grant treatment.\nDistinguish: (a) Unconditional vs Conditional grants for FV-model assets.\n(b) What applies when biological asset is measured at cost?",
    back:"Government grants — 2 tracks based on measurement model:\n\nTRACK 1: Biological Asset measured at FV LESS COSTS TO SELL:\n\n(a) UNCONDITIONAL GRANT:\n→ Recognised in PROFIT OR LOSS when, and only when, the grant becomes RECEIVABLE\n→ NOT spread over useful life (contrast with Ind AS 20)\n\n(b) CONDITIONAL GRANT (including grants requiring entity NOT to engage in specified agricultural activity):\n→ Recognised in PROFIT OR LOSS when, and only when, the CONDITIONS ATTACHING TO THE GRANT ARE MET\n\nExample (conditional): Grant requires farming for 5 years; return entire grant if shorter\n→ Grant recognised only AFTER 5 years pass\nIf proportional retention allowed → recognise proportionately as time passes (e.g. ₹2 crore/year)\n\nTRACK 2: Biological Asset measured at COST (exception applies):\n→ IND AS 20 applies (standard government grant accounting)\n→ Two acceptable methods:\n   (i) Deferred income → recognised in P&L systematically over useful life of asset, OR\n   (ii) Deduct from carrying amount → recognised as reduced depreciation expense\n\nGrant for BEARER PLANTS:\n→ Bearer plants are outside Ind AS 41 → Ind AS 20 applies\n\n📌 KEY DISTINCTION: Unconditional grants under Ind AS 41 go to P&L IMMEDIATELY when receivable — NOT deferred over useful life as under Ind AS 20." },

  // ── THEORY Q&A ────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:311, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Scope: Vines, Grapes & Wine\n[Illustration 1 – ABC Ltd]\n\nABC Ltd grows vines, harvests the grapes and produces wine.\n\nIdentify which activity falls under which standard, with reasons.",
    back:"1. GRAPE VINES (growing):\n→ Grape vines are BEARER PLANTS — used to produce crops of grapes over multiple periods\n→ Bearer plants → IND AS 16 (PPE) — outside Ind AS 41 scope\n→ However, PRODUCE growing on them (unripe grapes on vine) → IND AS 41\n\n2. HARVESTED GRAPES:\n→ At the point of harvest, biological transformation CEASES\n→ Grapes become AGRICULTURAL PRODUCE covered by IND AS 41\n→ Measured at FV less CTS at harvest → this FV less CTS becomes COST for Ind AS 2\n\n3. WINE PRODUCTION:\n→ Wine involves a lengthy maturation period\n→ This process is similar to CONVERSION OF RAW MATERIALS TO FINISHED PRODUCT — not biological transformation\n→ Even though it may be a logical extension of agricultural activity, it does NOT meet the definition of agricultural activity\n→ IND AS 2 (Inventories) applies\n\nSummary:\n| Activity | Standard | Reason |\n|---|---|---|\n| Grape vines | Ind AS 16 | Bearer plant |\n| Harvested grapes | Ind AS 41 | Agricultural produce at harvest |\n| Wine production | Ind AS 2 | Post-harvest processing |\n\n📌 Post-harvest processing is NEVER agricultural activity under Ind AS 41." },

  { id:312, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Activity Classification\n[Test Your Knowledge Q5]\n\nAnalyse whether each falls within scope of Ind AS 41:\n(a) Zoo management  (b) Ocean fishing\n(c) Fish farming  (d) Growing plants for drugs\n(e) Guard dogs for security  (f) Development of cells/bacteria/viruses",
    back:"(a) ZOO MANAGEMENT → NOT Ind AS 41\nPrimary purpose is showing animals to public for recreation — no management of biological transformation for sale or produce. Not agricultural activity.\n\n(b) OCEAN FISHING → NOT Ind AS 41\nHarvesting biological assets from UNMANAGED SOURCES. Fish grow naturally — no management of biological transformation. Not agricultural activity.\n\n(c) FISH FARMING → YES — IND AS 41\nManaging growth of fish + harvesting for sale = management of biological transformation of biological assets for sale. Agricultural activity.\n\n(d) GROWING PLANTS FOR DRUGS → YES — IND AS 41\nPlants grown for use in drug production = agricultural activity → within scope.\n\n(e) GUARD DOGS (security) → NOT Ind AS 41\nNot kept for sale, not for conversion into agricultural produce, not for generation of additional biological assets. No agricultural activity.\n\n(f) CELLS/BACTERIA/VIRUSES → Depends on PURPOSE:\n→ For RESEARCH purposes only → NOT Ind AS 41 (not developed for sale or conversion into agricultural produce)\n→ For SALE or use in dairy products → YES — IND AS 41\n\n📌 Two-part test:\n(1) Is there management of biological transformation?\n(2) Is it for sale, agricultural produce, or additional biological assets?\nBoth must be satisfied." },

  { id:313, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Bearer Plant vs Produce: Key Distinctions\n\nWhy are bearer plants treated under Ind AS 16 rather than Ind AS 41?\nWhat is the treatment of produce ON bearer plants?\nAre animals ever classified as bearer plants?",
    back:"Bearer plants excluded from Ind AS 41 because:\n→ They function like MANUFACTURING EQUIPMENT — used over multiple periods to produce agricultural output\n→ They do NOT themselves constitute agricultural produce to be sold\n→ Their carrying amount is recovered through CONTINUING USE (producing crops), not through sale of the plant itself\n→ Therefore: depreciated over useful life under Ind AS 16\n\nProduce ON bearer plants:\n→ IS a biological asset within scope of IND AS 41\n→ Examples:\n   • Tea leaves on tea bushes → Ind AS 41\n   • Grapes on grape vines → Ind AS 41\n   • Latex on rubber trees → Ind AS 41\n   • Oil palm fruit → Ind AS 41\n\nAnimals — NEVER bearer plants:\n→ Definition of bearer plant explicitly covers only PLANTS\n→ Sheep, cows — biological assets under Ind AS 41, even if they produce agricultural produce over multiple periods\n→ Example: Dairy cow produces milk for many years but is still a biological asset, NOT a bearer plant\n\nDual-use plants → NOT bearer plants:\n→ If a plant is cultivated for agricultural produce AND there is MORE THAN REMOTE likelihood of being sold as agricultural produce itself → not a bearer plant\n→ Example: Rubber trees sold for both latex AND lumber — may not qualify as bearer plant" },

  { id:314, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Government Grants: Agro Foods Ltd\n[Illustration 4]\n\nAgro Foods Ltd received a government grant to set up a poultry unit, used to buy:\n(a) Broiler birds (measured at FV less CTS) — NO conditions attached\n(b) Incubator machine (Ind AS 16 asset) — condition: used for minimum 3 years\n\nAdvise the accounting treatment under Ind AS 41 and Ind AS 20.",
    back:"(a) BROILER BIRDS — biological asset at FV less CTS:\n→ No conditions attached → UNCONDITIONAL grant\n→ Per Ind AS 41: Recognise in PROFIT OR LOSS when grant becomes RECEIVABLE\n→ Grant received with no future conditions → recognise in P&L in the PERIOD IN WHICH IT IS RECEIVED\n\n(b) INCUBATOR MACHINE — Ind AS 16 asset (NOT a biological asset):\n→ Plant and machinery used to develop/maintain biological assets → covered by Ind AS 16\n→ Does NOT qualify as biological asset under Ind AS 41\n→ Ind AS 41 government grant provisions DO NOT apply\n→ IND AS 20 APPLIES\n\nUnder Ind AS 20, two acceptable methods:\nMethod 1: Recognise grant as DEFERRED INCOME → recognised in P&L on systematic basis over useful life (3 years)\nMethod 2: DEDUCT from carrying amount of asset → recognised in P&L over 3 years as reduced depreciation expense\n\nConclusion for incubator:\n→ Since condition = use for minimum 3 years (= useful life), grant spread over 3 years under either method\n→ Either method gives same timing of recognition over the 3-year life\n\n📌 Key distinction:\n• Biological asset grants (FV model) → Ind AS 41 (immediate P&L when receivable/conditions met)\n• Non-biological asset grants + cost-model biological asset grants → Ind AS 20 (deferred or reduced carrying amount)" },

  // ── FORMULA ───────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:315, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Formula Card: Price Change vs Physical Change\n[Illustration 2]\n\nA farmer owns 250 dairy cattle (3-year old) at 1 April 20X1, total FV = ₹13,750.\nFV of 3-year cattle at 31 March 20X2 = ₹60/cattle\nFV of 4-year cattle at 31 March 20X2 = ₹75/cattle\n\n(1) State the formula for Price Change and Physical Change\n(2) Calculate both; state total FV at 31 March 20X2\n(3) Pass the journal entry",
    back:"Opening FV per cattle = ₹13,750 ÷ 250 = ₹55/cattle\n\nFormulas:\nPRICE CHANGE = Units × (FV at SAME AGE at new price − FV at same age at old price)\n= 250 × (₹60 − ₹55) = 250 × ₹5 = ₹1,250\n[Price changed; cattle still 3 years old → same age, new market rate]\n\nPHYSICAL CHANGE = Units × (FV at NEW AGE − FV at same age at new prices)\n= 250 × (₹75 − ₹60) = 250 × ₹15 = ₹3,750\n[Cattle aged from 3 years to 4 years → physical growth using new prices]\n\nCalculation:\nFV at 1 April 20X1:                                    ₹13,750\nIncrease due to Price change [250 × (60 − 55)]:         ₹1,250\nIncrease due to Physical change [250 × (75 − 60)]:      ₹3,750\nFV at 31 March 20X2:                                   ₹18,750\n\nJournal Entry (31 March 20X2):\nBiological Asset (Cattle A/c)       Dr.  ₹5,000\n   To Gain – Change in value (P/L)          ₹5,000\n(Being change in value of cattle recognised at end of reporting period)\n\n📌 Price change = SAME age, rate changed\n📌 Physical change = animal AGED (matured), using new market rates at the new age\n📌 Total gain of ₹5,000 → recognised entirely in P&L" },

  { id:316, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Formula Card: Initial Recognition & Remeasurement\n[Illustration 3]\n\nXYZ Ltd purchased 100 sheep on 1 December 20X3 for ₹5,00,000.\nTransaction cost (paid by seller): 2% of market price = ₹10,000.\nSheep's FV increased to ₹6,00,000 on 31 March 20X4.\nTransaction cost to sell at 31 March 20X4: 2% (paid by seller).\n\nCalculate FV less CTS on purchase date and on 31 March 20X4. Pass journal entries.",
    back:"INITIAL RECOGNITION (1 December 20X3):\nFV = ₹5,00,000\nLess: Costs to sell = 2% × ₹5,00,000 = ₹10,000\nFV less CTS = ₹4,90,000\nLoss on initial recognition = ₹10,000 → P&L\n\nJournal Entry (1 December 20X3):\nBiological Asset (Sheep)     Dr.   4,90,000\nLoss on initial recognition  Dr.     10,000\n   To Bank                           5,00,000\n(Being biological asset purchased at FV less CTS)\n\nREMEASUREMENT (31 March 20X4):\nFV = ₹6,00,000\nLess: Costs to sell = 2% × ₹6,00,000 = ₹12,000\nFV less CTS = ₹5,88,000\nGain = ₹5,88,000 − ₹4,90,000 = ₹98,000 → P&L\n\nJournal Entry (31 March 20X4):\nBiological Asset (Sheep)             Dr.  98,000\n   To Gain – Change in fair value            98,000\n(Being change in fair value recognised at end of reporting period)\n\n📌 Costs to sell are ALWAYS deducted from FV regardless of WHO bears them\n📌 Costs to sell include: brokers' and dealers' commissions, auctioneer fees, transfer taxes, transport costs to sale point\n📌 Costs to sell EXCLUDE: finance costs and income taxes" },

  // ── QUICK FIRE ───────────────────────────────────────
  { id:317, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Quick Fire\n\n1. Biological assets measured at: ___\n2. Agricultural produce at point of harvest measured at: ___\n3. Bearer plants accounted under: ___\n4. FV exception for biological assets can be applied at: ___\n5. Ocean fishing is / is not agricultural activity because: ___\n6. Gain on birth of a calf → recognised: ___\n7. Post-harvest produce → governed by: ___",
    back:"1. FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL (at initial recognition and at each reporting period end)\n\n2. FAIR VALUE LESS COSTS TO SELL at point of harvest — this becomes the COST for Ind AS 2\n\n3. IND AS 16 (Property, Plant and Equipment) — bearer plants are like manufacturing equipment\n\n4. INITIAL RECOGNITION ONLY — once FV model used, must continue until disposal\n   (Presumption of reliable FV can be rebutted ONLY on initial recognition)\n\n5. NOT agricultural activity — ocean fishing is harvesting from UNMANAGED SOURCES; fish grow naturally with no management of biological transformation\n\n6. IMMEDIATELY in P&L in the period of birth — gain on initial recognition of new biological asset (procreation)\n\n7. IND AS 2 (Inventories) or another applicable standard\n\nBonus:\n→ Animals are NEVER bearer plants\n→ Unconditional government grant (FV model asset) → P&L when RECEIVABLE\n→ Conditional government grant (FV model asset) → P&L when CONDITIONS MET\n→ Government grant for cost-model biological asset → IND AS 20\n→ FV of agricultural produce at harvest: can ALWAYS be measured reliably (no exception)" },

  { id:318, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Quick Fire: True or False\n\n1. Ind AS 41 applies to wine production from harvested grapes.\n2. Produce growing on bearer plants is a biological asset.\n3. The cost model exception for biological assets can be applied at any time.\n4. Fair value of agricultural produce at harvest may sometimes not be reliably measurable.\n5. Contract prices are relevant in measuring FV of biological assets.\n6. Fish farming is agricultural activity.\n7. A loss may arise on initial recognition of a biological asset.",
    back:"1. FALSE\nWine production is post-harvest processing → Ind AS 2 applies. Not biological transformation.\n\n2. TRUE\nProduce growing on bearer plants = biological asset → Ind AS 41 applies to it.\n\n3. FALSE\nCost model exception can be rebutted ONLY ON INITIAL RECOGNITION.\nOnce FV model used → must continue until disposal. Cannot switch back to cost later.\n\n4. FALSE\nThe standard explicitly states FV of agricultural produce at the POINT OF HARVEST can ALWAYS be measured reliably. No exception is available for agricultural produce.\n\n5. FALSE\nContract prices are NOT necessarily relevant. FV reflects CURRENT MARKET CONDITIONS between market participants. FV is NOT adjusted because of the existence of a contract.\n\n6. TRUE\nFish farming = management of biological transformation (growth of fish) for sale → agricultural activity within scope of Ind AS 41.\n\n7. TRUE\nCosts to sell are deducted from FV → FV less CTS may be LESS than the cash paid.\nExample: Sheep purchased at auction — transport cost + auctioneer fee deducted → loss on initial recognition." },

  { id:319, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Quick Fire: Government Grants\n\n1. Unconditional grant + FV-model biological asset → recognise: ___\n2. Conditional grant + FV-model biological asset → recognise: ___\n3. Grant for cost-model biological asset → apply: ___\n4. Grant related to bearer plants → apply: ___\n5. Under Ind AS 20, two methods for asset-related grants: ___",
    back:"1. UNCONDITIONAL grant + FV model:\n→ Recognise in P&L when grant becomes RECEIVABLE\n→ Immediate recognition — not deferred\n\n2. CONDITIONAL grant + FV model:\n→ Recognise in P&L when CONDITIONS ATTACHING TO THE GRANT ARE MET\n→ Includes grants requiring entity NOT to engage in specified agricultural activity\n→ If all-or-nothing condition: full grant only after full period elapses\n→ If proportional retention allowed: recognise proportionately as time passes\n\n3. Grant for COST-MODEL biological asset:\n→ Apply IND AS 20 (standard government grant accounting)\n\n4. Grant related to BEARER PLANTS:\n→ Apply IND AS 20 (bearer plants are outside Ind AS 41 scope → Ind AS 16 + Ind AS 20)\n\n5. Under Ind AS 20, two acceptable methods:\n   (i) Deferred income → recognised in P&L systematically over useful life of asset\n   (ii) Deduct grant from carrying amount of asset → recognised as reduced depreciation expense\n\n📌 Ind AS 41 vs Ind AS 20 key contrast:\n→ Ind AS 41: immediate P&L when receivable (unconditional)\n→ Ind AS 20: deferred over useful life OR netted against asset" },

  // ── PRACTICAL ─────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:320, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Practical: Moon Ltd – Part 1\n[Illustration 5]\n\n1 April 20X1 transactions:\n• 200 dairy cows (2-yr old) purchased for ₹10,00,000\n• Unconditional government grant received: ₹10,00,000 (for cows)\n• Land purchased: ₹50,00,000\n\nFV per cow: 2-yr @ 1 Apr = ₹5,000; 3-yr @ 31 Mar 20X2 = ₹5,500\nMaintenance: ₹6,00,000 | Breeding fee: ₹4,00,000\n\nCalculate treatment of (a) Land (b) Cows at 31 March 20X2 (c) Government grant",
    back:"(a) LAND:\n→ Land is NOT covered by Ind AS 41 → Ind AS 16 applies\n→ Under Cost Model: recorded at cost ₹50,00,000\n→ No depreciation (land has infinite useful life)\n→ Balance sheet: PPE – Land = ₹50,00,000\n\n(b) DAIRY COWS at 31 March 20X2 (now 3-year old):\nFV at 31 March 20X2 = 200 × ₹5,500 = ₹11,00,000\n\nPrice change: 200 × (₹5,200 − ₹5,000) = ₹40,000\n[3-yr cow at new rate vs opening rate]\nPhysical change: 200 × (₹5,500 − ₹5,200) = ₹60,000\n[aged from 2-yr to 3-yr, using new rates]\nTotal gain = ₹1,00,000 → recognised in P&L\n\nBalance sheet: Biological assets (Dairy cows) = ₹11,00,000\n\n(c) GOVERNMENT GRANT:\n→ Unconditional grant related to biological asset measured at FV less CTS\n→ Ind AS 41 applies: Recognised in P&L when RECEIVABLE\n→ ₹10,00,000 credited to INCOME immediately on 1 April 20X1\n→ NOT spread over useful life of herd (contrast with Ind AS 20)\n\nNote: Maintenance costs (₹6,00,000) and breeding fees (₹4,00,000) are EXPENSED to P&L — they are costs incurred to generate the biological transformation, not to be capitalised" },

  { id:321, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Practical: Moon Ltd – Part 2\n[Illustration 5]\n\n1 October 20X1: 100 calves born\nFV less CTS per calf:\n• Newborn @ 1 Oct 20X1 = ₹1,100\n• 6-month old @ 31 Mar 20X2 = ₹1,300\n\n31 March 20X2: 3,000 litres unsold milk\nFV of milk = ₹24/litre\n\nCalculate: (a) Calves – BS & P&L (b) Milk in inventory (c) Full P&L and BS extract",
    back:"(a) CALVES:\n→ Born 1 Oct 20X1 → BIOLOGICAL ASSETS → FV less CTS at birth:\n   100 × ₹1,100 = ₹1,10,000 (gain on procreation → P&L immediately)\n→ By 31 March 20X2: 6-month old → FV = 100 × ₹1,300 = ₹1,30,000\n→ Balance sheet: Calves = ₹1,30,000\n→ Total change in FV of calves credited to P&L = ₹1,30,000\n\n(b) MILK:\n→ Agricultural produce → measured at FV less CTS at point of harvest\n→ 3,000 × ₹24 = ₹72,000\n→ Balance sheet: Inventory (milk) = ₹72,000\n→ This FV less CTS = COST for Ind AS 2 purposes\n\n(c) Statement of P&L extract:\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nIncome:\n  Change in FV – Dairy cows:         ₹1,00,000\n  Government grant:                 ₹10,00,000\n  Change in FV – Calves:             ₹1,30,000\n  Fair value of milk:                  ₹72,000\n  Total income:                     ₹13,02,000\nExpenses:\n  Maintenance costs:                 ₹6,00,000\n  Breeding fees:                     ₹4,00,000\n  Total expenses:                   ₹10,00,000\n  Net income:                        ₹3,02,000\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nBalance Sheet extract:\n  PPE – Land:                       ₹50,00,000\n  Biological assets – Dairy cows:   ₹11,00,000\n  Biological assets – Calves:        ₹1,30,000\n  Inventory – Milk:                    ₹72,000" },

  { id:322, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Practical: Cattle Auction\n[Test Your Knowledge Q1]\n\nEntity A purchased cattle at auction on 30 June 20X1:\n• Purchase price: ₹1,00,000\n• Transport to farm (paid by buyer): ₹1,000\n• Auctioneer fee (2% of purchase price, paid by buyer): ₹2,000\n\n31 March 20X2: Sales price = ₹1,10,000\nTo sell at auction: Transport ₹1,000 + auctioneer fee 2% of selling price\n\nCalculate initial recognition value and year-end value. Pass journal entries.",
    back:"INITIAL RECOGNITION (30 June 20X1):\nFV less costs to sell:\n   FV = ₹1,00,000\n   Less: Transport (cost to sell) = (₹1,000)\n   Less: Auctioneer fee 2% × ₹1,00,000 = (₹2,000)\n   FV less CTS = ₹97,000\n\nCash outflow (purchase + transport + auctioneer) = ₹1,03,000\nLoss on initial recognition = ₹1,03,000 − ₹97,000 = ₹6,000 → P&L\n\nJournal Entry (30 June 20X1):\nBiological Asset (Cattle)     Dr.  97,000\nLoss on initial recognition   Dr.   6,000\n   To Bank                         1,03,000\n\nYEAR-END MEASUREMENT (31 March 20X2):\nFV less costs to sell:\n   FV = ₹1,10,000\n   Less: Transport = (₹1,000)\n   Less: Auctioneer fee 2% × ₹1,10,000 = (₹2,200)\n   FV less CTS = ₹1,06,800\n\nGain = ₹1,06,800 − ₹97,000 = ₹9,800 → P&L\n\nJournal Entry (31 March 20X2):\nBiological Asset (Cattle)          Dr.  9,800\n   To Gain on remeasurement (P&L)         9,800\n\n📌 Costs to sell are deducted from FV regardless of who actually bears them\n📌 At year-end, deduct SELLING costs (transport to auction + auctioneer fee on sales price)" },

  { id:323, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 41", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 41 – Practical: Conditional Government Grant\n[Example 4 – Sun Ltd]\n\nSun Ltd cultivated land. Government offers ₹10 crore grant, condition: cultivate for 5 years. If shorter, ENTIRE grant must be returned.\n\n(a) When is the grant recognised?\n(b) What if the terms allowed PROPORTIONAL retention based on time elapsed?",
    back:"(a) ALL-OR-NOTHING CONDITION:\n→ Condition: cultivate for FULL 5 years; return ENTIRE grant if shorter\n→ This is a CONDITIONAL grant related to a biological asset (FV model applies)\n→ Grant is NOT recognised until the CONDITION IS FULLY MET\n→ Recognition: AFTER 5 YEARS of cultivation (₹10 crore in P&L at end of Year 5)\n→ NO income recognised in Years 1 through 4\n\n(b) PROPORTIONAL RETENTION:\n→ If terms allow entity to retain the grant proportional to time elapsed:\n→ Recognise proportionately as time passes\n→ ₹10 crore ÷ 5 years = ₹2 crore per annum\n→ Recognised: ₹2 crore in P&L each year for 5 years\n\nKey principle:\n→ Conditional grants → recognised in P&L only when CONDITIONS ARE MET\n→ If conditions allow proportional satisfaction → recognise proportionately\n\n📌 Contrast with unconditional grants:\n→ Unconditional → recognised IMMEDIATELY when RECEIVABLE\n\n📌 Grants requiring entity NOT TO ENGAGE in specified agricultural activity:\n→ Same rule: recognise in P&L only when conditions are met\n\n📌 If grant relates to cost-model biological asset or bearer plant:\n→ Ind AS 20 applies instead (deferred income or deduction from carrying amount)" },

  // AFM · Portfolio Management
  // ── CONCEPT ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:126, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What is Portfolio Management? What are its 3 core activities?",
    back:"Portfolio Management = Process of selecting, constructing and continuously managing an optimal mix of investments that best suits an investor's risk-return profile.\n\n📌 Based on the principle: 'Don't put all eggs in the same basket'\n\n3 Core Activities:\n1️⃣ Selection of Securities\n2️⃣ Construction of all Feasible Portfolios from selected securities\n3️⃣ Deciding optimal weights/proportions for each security\n\nGoal: Build an Optimal Portfolio commensurate with the investor's risk appetite.",
    exam:false },

  { id:127, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the 7 Objectives of Portfolio Management?",
    back:"1. 🔒 Safety of Principal\nKeep principal intact including its purchasing power\n\n2. 📊 Stability of Income\nFacilitate accurate planning and reinvestment\n\n3. 📈 Capital Growth\nVia reinvestment in growth securities\n\n4. 🔄 Marketability\nEase of buying/selling — essential for flexibility\n\n5. 💧 Liquidity\nNearness to money — to exploit attractive opportunities\n\n6. 🌐 Diversification\nReduce risk of loss of capital/income across securities & industries\n\n7. 💰 Favourable Tax Status\nMinimise tax burden → improve effective yield\n\n📌 Exam Tip: Write each with 1-line explanation for 4-mark theory Qs.",
    exam:false },

  { id:128, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the 5 Phases of Portfolio Management?",
    back:"1️⃣ Security Analysis\n→ Examine risk-return characteristics of individual securities\n→ Use Fundamental Analysis (intrinsic value) or Technical Analysis (price patterns)\n→ Goal: Identify underpriced (buy) / overpriced (sell) securities\n\n2️⃣ Portfolio Analysis\n→ Compute risk-return for each possible combination (Feasible Portfolios)\n\n3️⃣ Portfolio Selection\n→ Identify Efficient Portfolios → Select Optimal Portfolio per investor's risk appetite\n\n4️⃣ Portfolio Revision\n→ Add/remove securities as market conditions or investor needs change\n\n5️⃣ Portfolio Evaluation\n→ Measure actual return vs. risk over time\n→ Use Sharpe, Treynor, Jensen's Alpha ratios\n\n📌 All 5 phases are an ongoing, continuous cycle.",
    exam:false },

  { id:129, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Differentiate: Systematic Risk vs Unsystematic Risk",
    back:"📊 SYSTEMATIC RISK (Market Risk / Non-Diversifiable)\n→ Caused by macro/external factors affecting ALL companies\n→ Cannot be eliminated by diversification\n→ Sub-types:\n  • Interest Rate Risk: ↑ interest rate → ↓ security price\n  • Purchasing Power (Inflation) Risk: Erodes real return\n  • Market Risk: General market upswings/downswings (Bull/Bear)\n\n📌 UNSYSTEMATIC RISK (Idiosyncratic / Diversifiable)\n→ Caused by micro/internal factors specific to a company\n→ CAN be eliminated through diversification\n→ Sub-types:\n  • Business Risk: Variability in operating profits (measured by Operating Leverage)\n  • Financial Risk: Presence of debt; measured by Debt-Equity Ratio\n\n──────────────────────────────\nTotal Risk = Systematic Risk + Unsystematic Risk\n\n📌 Beta (β) measures ONLY Systematic Risk.",
    exam:true },

  { id:130, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Traditional Approach vs Modern Approach (Markowitz) to Portfolio Theory",
    back:"📜 Traditional Approach:\n→ Focuses on investor profile: age, income, liquidity, tax, risk attitude\n→ Diversify across different securities/assets → assumed enough\n→ Balances equities vs fixed income, high dividend vs growth stocks\n→ Relies on fundamental/technical analysis + expert advice\n→ Flaw: Any diversification was considered beneficial\n\n🔬 Modern Approach (Markowitz, 1950s):\n→ Proved random diversification is NOT optimal\n→ Key Insight: Correlation between securities matters\n→ Same expected return can be achieved at LOWER risk by choosing correctly correlated assets\n→ Provides mathematical framework: Optimize Risk-Return using Mean-Variance analysis\n→ Lower/negative correlation between assets → greater risk reduction\n\n📌 Markowitz questioned 'any basket is fine' — proved 'the RIGHT basket matters'.",
    exam:false },

  { id:131, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is the Efficient Frontier? What is the Optimal Portfolio?",
    back:"📐 Efficient Portfolio:\n→ Highest return for a given level of risk, OR\n→ Lowest risk for a given level of return\n\n📈 Efficient Frontier:\n→ The curve connecting ALL efficient portfolios on a risk-return graph\n→ Any portfolio BELOW the frontier is suboptimal (dominated)\n→ All points on the frontier are equally 'efficient' — choice depends on investor's risk appetite\n\nKey Points on the Frontier:\n• Point A (bottom): Minimum Variance Portfolio — lowest possible risk\n• Point D (top): Maximum return portfolio — also highest risk\n\n⭐ Optimal Portfolio:\n→ The specific point on the Efficient Frontier that matches the investor's indifference curve\n→ Varies across investors (different risk appetite = different optimal portfolio)\n\n📌 Markowitz: 'Move to the frontier — then choose your risk level'",
    exam:false },

  { id:132, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM)? What are its key assumptions?",
    back:"📊 CAPM: Links expected return of an asset to its systematic risk (Beta)\nFormula: Rj = Rf + β(Rm − Rf)\n\nKey Assumptions:\n1. Efficient Market — prices reflect full information; assets fairly priced\n2. Rational Investors — prefer higher return for same risk; risk-averse\n3. All assets divisible and liquid\n4. Investors can borrow/lend freely at risk-free rate\n5. Homogeneous expectations — all investors see same risk-return\n6. No taxes or transaction costs\n7. Single-period investment horizon\n8. Total risk = Systematic + Unsystematic; unsystematic can be diversified away\n\n📌 CAPM says: Compensation is given ONLY for Systematic Risk (Beta)\n📌 Unsystematic risk → not compensated since it can be diversified away.",
    exam:true },

  { id:133, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is the Arbitrage Pricing Theory (APT)? How does it differ from CAPM?",
    back:"📊 APT (Ross): Multi-factor model for expected return\nFormula: E(R) = Rf + λ₁β₁ + λ₂β₂ + … + λₙβₙ\n\nWhere:\n• λₙ = Risk premium for nth macro factor\n• βₙ = Sensitivity to that factor\n\nRoss's 4 Key Factors:\n• Changes in Inflation\n• Level of Industrial Production\n• Risk Premium (spread between T-bills and long bonds)\n• Term Structure of Interest Rates\n\n🆚 APT vs CAPM:\n• CAPM = ONE factor (market beta)\n• APT = MULTIPLE macro factors\n• APT doesn't need market portfolio assumption\n• APT more realistic but harder to implement (which factors?)\n• Both give same result in equilibrium for well-diversified portfolios\n\n📌 APT surprise formula: E(R) = Rf + Σ βₙ(EVₙ − AVₙ) when unexpected changes occur.",
    exam:false },

  { id:134, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"What is Capital Market Theory? What is the Capital Market Line (CML)?",
    back:"📈 Capital Market Theory extends Markowitz by introducing a Risk-Free Asset.\n\nKey Insight: When investors can borrow/lend at risk-free rate, the efficient frontier changes to a straight line — the Capital Market Line (CML).\n\n📐 CML Formula:\nE(Rp) = Rf + [(Rm − Rf) / σm] × σp\n\nWhere:\n• Rf = Risk-free rate\n• Rm = Market return\n• σm = SD of market\n• σp = SD of portfolio\n\nSlope of CML = (Rm − Rf) / σm = Reward per unit of TOTAL risk\n\nPortfolios on CML:\n• Rf to M = Lending portfolios (part in risk-free + part in market portfolio)\n• M to Z = Borrowing portfolios (borrow at Rf to invest more in market)\n\n🆚 CML vs SML:\n• CML → uses σ (total risk) → only for EFFICIENT portfolios\n• SML → uses Beta (systematic risk) → for ALL securities & portfolios",
    exam:true },

  { id:135, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is Sharpe's Single Index Model? How does it decompose risk?",
    back:"📊 Sharpe's Single Index Model assumes stock returns move together ONLY due to the common market index.\n\nReturn Equation:\nRi = αi + βi × Rm + εi\n\nWhere:\n• αi = Intercept (return independent of market)\n• βi = Slope (sensitivity to market)\n• εi = Error term (unsystematic component)\n\nRisk Decomposition:\n• Systematic Risk = βi² × σm²\n• Unsystematic Risk (εi²) = Total Variance − Systematic Risk\n• Also = Variance × (1 − r²) where r = correlation with market\n\nPortfolio Variance:\nσp² = (ΣXiβi)² × σm² + Σ(Xi² × εi²)\n\n📌 r² = Coefficient of Determination → % of return variation explained by market\n📌 βi = 1.5 means stock return changes 1.5% for every 1% change in market",
    exam:true },

  // ── FORMULA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:136, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 Expected Return Formula — Probability-based & Historical",
    back:"📊 When Probabilities Given:\nE(R) = Σ [Xi × p(Xi)]\n= Sum of (each possible return × its probability)\n\nExample:\nReturns: 20%, 30%, 40%, 50%, 60%\nProb:     0.20, 0.20, 0.40, 0.10, 0.10\nE(R) = (0.20×0.20)+(0.30×0.20)+(0.40×0.40)+(0.50×0.10)+(0.60×0.10)\n     = 0.04+0.06+0.16+0.05+0.06 = 0.37 = 37%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📊 When Historical Data Given:\nE(R) = (x₁ + x₂ + … + xₙ) / n\n= Simple Arithmetic Mean\n\nExample:\nReturns: 9.5, 7.0, 11.0, −6.0, 2.5\nSum = 24.00 → Mean = 24/5 = 4.80%\n\n📌 Use probability-weighted for forward-looking; use mean for historical data.",
    exam:true },

  { id:137, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 Variance & Standard Deviation Formula (Risk Measurement)",
    back:"📊 When Probabilities Given:\nσ² = Σ [(Xi − X̄)² × p(Xi)]\n\nExample:\nE(R) = 37%; Using above data:\nσ² = 0.0289×0.20 + 0.0049×0.20 + 0.0009×0.40 + 0.0169×0.10 + 0.0529×0.10\n   = 0.00578 + 0.00098 + 0.00036 + 0.00169 + 0.00529\n   = 0.0141\nσ = √0.0141 = 11.87%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📊 When Historical Data Given:\nσ² = Σ (xi − x̄)² / n\n\nExample:\nReturns: 9.5, 7.0, 11.0, −6.0, 2.5 → Mean = 4.80\nΣ(deviations²) = 22.09+4.84+38.44+116.64+5.29 = 187.30\nσ² = 187.30/5 = 37.46 → σ = 6.12%\n\n📌 σ = Standard Deviation = Square root of Variance\n📌 Higher σ = Higher Risk",
    exam:true },

  { id:138, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Portfolio Return & Portfolio Risk (2-Asset Portfolio) — Complete Formulas",
    back:"📊 Portfolio Return:\nRp = w₁R₁ + w₂R₂\n(Weighted average of individual returns)\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📊 Portfolio Variance:\nσp² = w₁²σ₁² + w₂²σ₂² + 2w₁w₂r₁₂σ₁σ₂\n\nWhere:\n• w₁, w₂ = weights\n• σ₁, σ₂ = standard deviations\n• r₁₂ = correlation coefficient\n\n3 Special Cases:\n✅ r = +1 → σp = w₁σ₁ + w₂σ₂ (maximum risk, no benefit)\n✅ r = −1 → σp = |w₁σ₁ − w₂σ₂| (minimum risk, can reach 0)\n✅ r = 0  → σp = √(w₁²σ₁² + w₂²σ₂²) (moderate reduction)\n\n📌 Risk reduction is GREATEST when correlation is NEGATIVE\n📌 r = −1 → Perfect negative correlation → Portfolio can be fully risk-free",
    exam:true },

  { id:139, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Covariance & Correlation Coefficient — Formulas & Interpretation",
    back:"📊 Covariance Formula (Historical):\nCovAB = Σ[(RA − R̄A)(RB − R̄B)] / N\n\nExample:\nYear: 1  2  3  4\nRx: 11 13 17 19 → R̄x = 15\nRy: 18 14 11  9 → R̄y = 13\nProducts: −20, −2, −4, −16 → Sum = −42\nCov = −42/4 = −10.5\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📊 Correlation Coefficient:\nr = CovAB / (σA × σB)\n\nInterpretation:\n• r = +1: Returns move perfectly TOGETHER\n• r = −1: Returns move perfectly OPPOSITE\n• r = 0: Returns are INDEPENDENT (no relationship)\n• −1 < r < 0: Partial negative correlation → best for diversification\n\n📌 Covariance shows direction of relationship; Correlation shows MAGNITUDE (−1 to +1)\n📌 Negative covariance → excellent for portfolio risk reduction",
    exam:true },

  { id:140, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"📐 CAPM / Security Market Line (SML) Formula & Beta Calculation",
    back:"📊 CAPM Formula (SML):\nRj = Rf + βj × (Rm − Rf)\n\nWhere:\n• Rj = Required return on security j\n• Rf = Risk-free rate\n• βj = Beta of security j\n• (Rm − Rf) = Market Risk Premium\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📊 Beta Calculation:\nβ = Cov(Ri, Rm) / σm²\n   = (σi × r) / σm\n\nAlternatively via regression:\nβ = [ΣXY − n·X̄·Ȳ] / [ΣY² − n·Ȳ²]\n(where X = security returns, Y = market returns)\n\n📌 β = 1: Moves with market\n📌 β > 1: More volatile than market (Aggressive Stock)\n📌 β < 1: Less volatile than market (Defensive Stock)\n📌 β = 0: Risk-free asset\n\nExample:\nRf = 5%, Rm = 13%, β = 1.2\nRj = 5 + 1.2(13 − 5) = 5 + 9.6 = 14.6%",
    exam:true },

  { id:141, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"📐 Sharpe Ratio, Treynor Ratio & Jensen's Alpha — All Three Formulas",
    back:"📊 Sharpe Ratio:\nS = (Rp − Rf) / σp\n→ Risk Premium per unit of TOTAL Risk (SD)\n→ Suitable for non-fully-diversified or overall portfolios\n→ Higher = Better\n\n📊 Treynor Ratio:\nT = (Rp − Rf) / βp\n→ Risk Premium per unit of SYSTEMATIC Risk (Beta)\n→ Suitable for well-diversified portfolios\n→ Higher = Better\n\n📊 Jensen's Alpha:\nα = Rp − [Rf + βp(Rm − Rf)]\n= Actual Return − CAPM Required Return\n\nInterpretation:\n• α > 0: Portfolio OUTPERFORMED (good manager)\n• α < 0: Portfolio UNDERPERFORMED\n• α = 0: Performed exactly per market risk\n\n📌 If Sharpe & Treynor give SAME ranking → perfectly diversified\n📌 If rankings DIFFER → some unsystematic risk exists",
    exam:true },

  { id:142, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"📐 Sharpe's Optimal Portfolio — Excess Return to Beta (Ci & C*) Formula",
    back:"Steps to Build Sharpe's Optimal Portfolio:\n\n1️⃣ Calculate Excess Return to Beta ratio for each stock:\n   (Ri − Rf) / βi   ← Treynor's ratio for individual stocks\n\n2️⃣ Rank all stocks from highest to lowest ratio\n\n3️⃣ Calculate Ci for each ranked stock:\nCi = [σm² × Σ{(Ri−Rf)βi / σεi²}] / [1 + σm² × Σ{βi² / σεi²}]\n\nWhere σεi² = Unsystematic variance of stock i\n\n4️⃣ C* = Highest value of Ci → Cut-off Rate\n\n5️⃣ Include all stocks where (Ri−Rf)/βi > C*\n\n6️⃣ Weights:\nZi = (βi/σεi²) × [(Ri−Rf)/βi − C*]\nXi = Zi / ΣZi\n\n📌 C* is the threshold: only stocks ABOVE C* make it into the portfolio\n📌 Once C* known, all higher-ranked stocks auto-qualify",
    exam:true },

  { id:143, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 APT Formula & Surprise Factor Variant",
    back:"📊 Standard APT:\nE(Ri) = Rf + λ₁β₁ + λ₂β₂ + … + λₙβₙ\n\nWhere:\n• λₙ = Risk premium for each macro factor\n• βₙ = Sensitivity to that factor\n\nExample (ICAI Illustration):\nRisk-free rate = 8%\nFactor 1 (Market): λ = 4%, β = 1.3\nFactor 2 (Growth): λ = 1%, β = 0.3\nFactor 3 (Inflation): λ = −4%, β = 0.2\n\nE(R) = 8% + 1.3×4% + 0.3×1% + 0.2×(−4%)\n     = 8% + 5.2% + 0.3% − 0.8%\n     = 12.7%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📊 APT with Surprise Factors:\nE(R) = Rf + Σβₙ(EVₙ − AVₙ)\n\nWhere (EV − AV) = Unexpected change in factor\n\n📌 If no surprises occur → Actual return = Expected return\n📌 Ross's 4 factors: Inflation, Industrial Production, Risk Premium, Interest Rate Term Structure",
    exam:true },

  // ── PRACTICAL ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:144, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Rf = 5%, Rm = 13%. Portfolio: 70% T-bills + 30% Market. Find Beta and Required Return.",
    back:"Step 1 — Beta of Portfolio:\nBeta of T-bills = 0 (risk-free)\nBeta of Market = 1.0\n\nPortfolio β = 0.70 × 0 + 0.30 × 1 = 0.30\n\nStep 2 — Required Return (CAPM):\nRj = Rf + β(Rm − Rf)\n   = 5% + 0.30 × (13% − 5%)\n   = 5% + 0.30 × 8%\n   = 5% + 2.4%\n   = 7.40%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Market Risk Premium = Rm − Rf = 13% − 5% = 8%\n📌 Beta is always the WEIGHTED AVERAGE of individual betas\n📌 Adding T-bills LOWERS portfolio beta and therefore LOWERS required return",
    exam:true },

  { id:145, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 Rf = 10%, Rm = 15%, β = 1.2. Projected return = 18%. Is stock correctly valued? What's your strategy?",
    back:"Step 1 — Required Return (CAPM):\nRj = Rf + β(Rm − Rf)\n   = 10 + 1.2 × (15 − 10)\n   = 10 + 6 = 16%\n\nStep 2 — Compare:\nRequired (CAPM) = 16%\nProjected Return = 18%\n\nProjected > Required → Stock is UNDERVALUED\n(Gives more return than it should for its risk level)\n\nStep 3 — Decision:\n✅ BUY the stock\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Decision Rules:\n• Projected > CAPM Required → Undervalued → BUY\n• Projected < CAPM Required → Overvalued → SELL\n• Projected = CAPM Required → Correctly Valued → HOLD\n\n📌 From price angle:\n• Actual Price < CAPM Price → Undervalued\n• Actual Price > CAPM Price → Overvalued",
    exam:true },

  { id:146, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 Security SD = 25%, Market SD = 15%, Correlation = 0.8. Find Beta. If Rf = 6%, Rm = 14%, find required return.",
    back:"Step 1 — Beta:\nβ = (σi × r) / σm\n  = (25% × 0.8) / 15%\n  = 20% / 15%\n  = 1.333\n\nStep 2 — Required Return (CAPM):\nRj = Rf + β(Rm − Rf)\n   = 6 + 1.333 × (14 − 6)\n   = 6 + 1.333 × 8\n   = 6 + 10.67\n   = 16.67%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Alternative Beta Formula:\nβ = Cov(i, m) / Var(m)\n  = (σi × r × σm) / σm²\n  = (σi × r) / σm ← same result\n\n📌 β > 1 → stock is more volatile than market (aggressive)\n📌 Risk Premium earned = β × Market Risk Premium",
    exam:true },

  { id:147, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 Portfolio has 50% in X (σ=√6.30) and 50% in Y (σ=√5.86). Market variance = 2.25. βx=0.71, βy=0.685. Unsystematic: X=5.166, Y=4.804. Find portfolio variance.",
    back:"Using Sharpe Single Index Model:\nσp² = (ΣXiβi)² × σm² + Σ(Xi² × εi²)\n\nStep 1 — Systematic component:\nΣXiβi = 0.5 × 0.71 + 0.5 × 0.685\n       = 0.355 + 0.3425 = 0.6975\n\n(0.6975)² × 2.25 = 0.4865 × 2.25 = 1.094\n\nStep 2 — Unsystematic component:\n(0.5)² × 5.166 + (0.5)² × 4.804\n= 0.25 × 5.166 + 0.25 × 4.804\n= 1.2915 + 1.201 = 2.493\n\nStep 3 — Portfolio Variance:\nσp² = 1.094 + 2.493 = 3.587\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Single Index model greatly simplifies computation vs full Markowitz covariance matrix\n📌 Requires only betas + unsystematic variances (not every pair's covariance)",
    exam:true },

  { id:148, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Portfolio A: Return=30%, SD=11%. Portfolio B: Return=25%, SD=5%. Rf=8%. Which is better using Sharpe Ratio?",
    back:"Sharpe Ratio = (Rp − Rf) / σp\n\nPortfolio A:\nSA = (30% − 8%) / 11% = 22/11 = 2.00\n\nPortfolio B:\nSB = (25% − 8%) / 5% = 17/5 = 3.40\n\n──────────────────────────────\n✅ Portfolio B is BETTER (Sharpe = 3.4 > 2.0)\n\nExplanation:\nAlthough A has higher absolute return (30% > 25%),\nB generates MORE return PER UNIT OF RISK.\nB has significantly lower volatility (SD = 5% vs 11%).\n\n📌 Sharpe Ratio corrects for risk — don't judge by return alone!\n📌 Rule: Higher Sharpe = Better risk-adjusted performance\n📌 Use this ratio especially when comparing OVERALL portfolios",
    exam:true },

  { id:149, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 Rebalancing Example: Portfolio = ₹1,00,000. Floor = ₹75,000. Multiplier = 2. Stock rises to 150 (from 100). Apply CPPI — what changes?",
    back:"Initial CPPI Setup:\nCushion = Portfolio − Floor = 1,00,000 − 75,000 = ₹25,000\nInvestment in Shares = Multiplier × Cushion = 2 × 25,000 = ₹50,000\nRemaining in Bonds = ₹50,000\n\nAfter Market rises to 150 (50% rise):\nShares value = 50,000 × 1.5 = ₹75,000\nBonds value = ₹50,000 (unchanged)\nNew Portfolio Value = ₹1,25,000\nNew Cushion = 1,25,000 − 75,000 = ₹50,000\n\nNew Required Share Investment = 2 × 50,000 = ₹1,00,000\n\n✅ Action: SELL ₹25,000 of Bonds → BUY ₹25,000 of Shares\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 CPPI Rule: BUY shares as they RISE; SELL shares as they FALL\n📌 This is OPPOSITE to Constant Mix strategy (which buys falling assets)\n📌 CPPI payoff = Convex; Constant Mix payoff = Concave",
    exam:true },

  // ── THEORY Q&A ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:150, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the assumptions of the Markowitz Model of Portfolio Theory?",
    back:"Markowitz Model Assumptions:\n\n1. Return on investment adequately summarises the outcome of an investment\n\n2. Investors can visualise a probability distribution of rates of return\n\n3. Investors' risk estimates are proportional to the variance of return they perceive\n\n4. Investment decisions are based on TWO criteria only:\n   → Expected Return (maximise)\n   → Variance of Return (minimise)\n\n5. Investors are risk-averse: prefer less risk for same expected return\n\n6. Utility is a function of only mean and variance of returns\n\n7. All assets are infinitely divisible and liquid\n\n📌 The model finds Mean-Variance Efficient portfolios → then selects the one matching investor's indifference curve\n📌 Limitation: Requires computing every pairwise covariance (n(n−1)/2 inputs) → computationally intensive",
    exam:false },

  { id:151, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the LIMITATIONS of CAPM? (5 key limitations)",
    back:"1. 📐 Beta Estimation\n→ Based on historical data; β in the future may differ from the past\n→ Also, estimation method (time period, market index chosen) affects β\n\n2. 🔒 Unrealistic Assumptions\n→ Risk-free borrowing/lending at same rate is not possible in reality\n→ No taxes, no transaction costs → impractical\n\n3. 📊 Systematic Risk Only\n→ CAPM ignores unsystematic risk which may still be relevant for undiversified investors\n\n4. 📰 Information Availability\n→ Difficult to get accurate risk-free rate (multiple T-bill rates exist)\n→ Market portfolio return changes constantly\n\n5. ⏱ Single Period Model\n→ Assumes single investment horizon → not suitable for multi-period decisions\n\n📌 Despite limitations, CAPM remains widely used for cost of equity, project evaluation, and portfolio benchmarking",
    exam:false },

  { id:152, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Compare Active Portfolio Strategy vs Passive Portfolio Strategy",
    back:"🎯 Active Portfolio Strategy (APS):\n→ Premise: Markets are INEFFICIENT — opportunities exist\n→ Goal: OUTPERFORM market after adjusting for risk (generate positive Alpha)\n→ Methods:\n  1. Market Timing: Shift allocation based on market forecast\n  2. Sector Rotation: Overweight/underweight sectors based on outlook\n  3. Security Selection: Pick mispriced stocks via FA/TA\n  4. Specialised Concepts: Growth stocks, out-of-favour stocks, asset stocks\n→ Higher costs but potential for higher alpha\n\n📊 Passive Portfolio Strategy:\n→ Premise: Markets are EFFICIENT — can't consistently beat the market\n→ Goal: Match benchmark return at lowest cost\n→ Guidelines:\n  1. Create well-diversified portfolio\n  2. Minimise transaction costs and portfolio revision\n→ Buy-and-Hold or Index replication approach\n\n📌 Fisher Black: Investors who exit market lose relative to a simple Buy-and-Hold strategy",
    exam:false },

  { id:153, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Compare the 3 Portfolio Rebalancing Policies: Buy & Hold, Constant Mix, CPPI",
    back:"📋 Buy & Hold (Do Nothing):\n→ Set floor, invest remainder in stocks, NEVER rebalance\n→ Stock portion drifts with market\n→ Portfolio value LINEARLY related to stock value\n→ Payoff: Straight line (linear)\n→ Best when: stocks outperform bonds steadily\n\n🔄 Constant Mix (Do Something):\n→ Maintain fixed stock:bond ratio (e.g., 60:40) always\n→ Rebalance when prices move by a set %\n→ Buy stocks when they FALL; sell when they RISE\n→ Payoff: Concave\n→ Best when: Markets are volatile/oscillating\n\n🛡 CPPI (Constant Proportion Portfolio Insurance):\n→ Set floor; invest multiplier × cushion in stocks\n→ Buy stocks when they RISE; sell when they FALL\n→ Payoff: Convex\n→ Best when: Trending (bull) markets\n→ Performs poorly in sharp reversals\n\n📌 CPPI = opposite of Constant Mix\n📌 Formula: Stock Investment = Multiplier × (Portfolio Value − Floor)",
    exam:true },

  { id:154, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are Fixed Income Portfolio Management Strategies?",
    back:"📊 PASSIVE Strategies:\n1. Buy & Hold: No churning; maintain initial selection; may set duration = benchmark\n2. Indexation: Replicate a predetermined bond index closely\n3. Immunization: Match duration of portfolio = investment horizon to neutralise interest rate risk. Popular in pension funds.\n4. Cash Flow Matching: Buy Zero Coupon Bonds maturing at exact dates of liabilities\n\n📊 ACTIVE Strategies:\n1. Forecasting Returns/Interest Rates:\n   • Bullet: Concentrate in ONE maturity (e.g., all in 5-year bonds)\n   • Barbell: Equal split in SHORTEST + LONGEST maturity (e.g., 1-yr + 10-yr)\n   • Ladder: Equal amounts across MULTIPLE maturities (e.g., 1yr to 5yr, 20% each)\n\n2. Yield Spread Analysis\n3. Credit Analysis\n4. Duration/Convexity Management\n\n📌 Interest Rate vs Bond Price: Inverse relationship\n📌 Longer duration bonds → higher interest rate sensitivity",
    exam:false },

  { id:155, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are Alternative Investments (AIs)? Key features and types?",
    back:"🏛 Alternative Investments = Non-traditional asset classes beyond listed stocks/bonds\n\nKey Features:\n1. Higher Risk-Return potential vs traditional investments\n2. Low correlation with traditional markets (great diversifier)\n3. Requires specialised knowledge\n\nKey Disadvantages:\n❌ Illiquid — limited secondary market\n❌ Less Transparent — limited public information\n❌ Extensive research required\n❌ Often highly leveraged\n\n📋 Types of Alternative Investments:\n1. Real Estate (tangible; land, buildings)\n2. Gold\n3. Private Equity\n4. REITs (Real Estate Investment Trusts)\n5. Hedge Funds\n6. ETFs (Exchange Traded Funds)\n7. Mutual Funds\n8. Commodities\n9. Distressed Securities\n\n📌 Real Estate is a tangible form of asset unlike paper/demat financial claims",
    exam:false },

  { id:164, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the 4 Asset Allocation Strategies?",
    back:"Many portfolios contain multiple asset categories. The 4 strategies are:\n\n1. 🔗 Integrated Asset Allocation\n→ Examines BOTH capital market conditions AND investor objectives/constraints together\n→ Allocation that best serves investor's needs while incorporating market forecast\n→ Most comprehensive approach\n\n2. 📊 Strategic Asset Allocation\n→ Generates optimal portfolio mixes based on returns, risk & covariances using HISTORICAL data\n→ Adjusted periodically to restore target allocation\n→ Within the context of investor's objectives and constraints\n\n3. 🔄 Tactical Asset Allocation\n→ Investor's risk tolerance assumed CONSTANT\n→ Asset allocation changed based on expectations about CAPITAL MARKET CONDITIONS\n→ More dynamic than strategic; adjusts to market outlook\n\n4. 🛡 Insured Asset Allocation\n→ Risk exposure adjusted for CHANGING PORTFOLIO VALUES (wealth)\n→ As portfolio value increases → more risk taken; as it decreases → less risk\n→ Similar in spirit to CPPI (protects against downside)\n\n📌 Exam Tip: Integrated = most holistic; Tactical = market-driven; Insured = wealth-driven",
    exam:false },

  // ── QUICK FIRE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:156, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ TRUE or FALSE:\n\nDiversification can eliminate ALL risk from a portfolio.",
    back:"❌ FALSE\n\nDiversification can ONLY eliminate UNSYSTEMATIC (diversifiable) risk.\n\nSystematic risk (market risk) CANNOT be eliminated by diversification — it affects ALL assets.\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Total Risk = Systematic + Unsystematic\n• As number of securities increases → Unsystematic risk → 0\n• Systematic risk remains CONSTANT regardless of portfolio size\n\nReal-life parallel:\nNo matter how many stocks you hold — a market crash, recession or interest rate hike will still impact your portfolio.\n\n📌 This is why CAPM says: only SYSTEMATIC RISK is priced/compensated.",
    exam:false },

  { id:157, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ FILL IN THE BLANK:\n\nA Beta of ___ means the security moves exactly with the market. A Beta of ___ means it's twice as volatile.",
    back:"📌 β = 1.0 → Moves EXACTLY with the market\n\n📌 β = 2.0 → Twice as volatile as the market\n(If market rises/falls by 1%, stock rises/falls by 2%)\n\n──────────────────────────────\nQuick Reference:\n• β > 1 → Aggressive stock (amplifies market moves)\n• β < 1 → Defensive stock (dampens market moves)\n• β = 0 → Risk-free asset (no market sensitivity)\n• β < 0 → Inverse to market (e.g., gold in some conditions)\n\n📌 Weighted average beta of all market securities = 1.0\n📌 Beta is the ONLY relevant risk measure in CAPM\n📌 Beta for T-bills / Government Securities = 0",
    exam:false },

  { id:158, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ MATCH: Which formula uses which risk measure?\n\nA. CML (Capital Market Line)\nB. SML (Security Market Line)\nC. Sharpe Ratio\nD. Treynor Ratio",
    back:"A. CML → Uses σp (TOTAL risk — Standard Deviation of Portfolio)\n→ Only for EFFICIENT PORTFOLIOS on the efficient frontier\n\nB. SML → Uses β (SYSTEMATIC risk — Beta)\n→ For ALL securities and portfolios (efficient or not)\n\nC. Sharpe Ratio → Uses σp (Total Risk / Standard Deviation)\n→ Risk premium per unit of TOTAL risk\n\nD. Treynor Ratio → Uses β (Beta / Systematic Risk)\n→ Risk premium per unit of SYSTEMATIC risk\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Memory Trick:\n• CML & Sharpe → Standard Deviation (Total Risk)\n• SML & Treynor → Beta (Systematic Risk)\n\n📌 CML applies ONLY to efficient portfolios\n📌 SML applies to ANY security (efficient or not)",
    exam:false },

  { id:159, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ What happens when r (correlation) between two assets = −1, 0, and +1?",
    back:"📊 Correlation = +1 (Perfect Positive):\n→ Assets move EXACTLY together\n→ NO diversification benefit\n→ σp = w₁σ₁ + w₂σ₂ (maximum portfolio risk)\n\n📊 Correlation = 0 (Independent):\n→ Returns are UNRELATED\n→ Moderate diversification benefit\n→ σp = √(w₁²σ₁² + w₂²σ₂²)\n\n📊 Correlation = −1 (Perfect Negative):\n→ Assets move EXACTLY opposite\n→ MAXIMUM diversification benefit\n→ Portfolio can be made RISK-FREE!\n→ σp = |w₁σ₁ − w₂σ₂|\n→ Zero risk when: w₁/w₂ = σ₂/σ₁\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 In real life, most assets have correlation between 0 and +1\n📌 Perfect −1 correlation is extremely rare\n📌 Even partial negative correlation meaningfully reduces portfolio risk",
    exam:false },

  { id:160, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ IDENTIFY: Jensen's Alpha = +2%. What does this tell you about the fund manager?",
    back:"✅ Alpha = +2% → POSITIVE ALPHA\n\n→ The portfolio OUTPERFORMED the CAPM expected return by 2%\n→ The fund manager generated EXCESS RETURN above what the market risk justified\n→ Indicates superior fund management / stock-picking ability\n\n──────────────────────────────\nFormula Reminder:\nα = Actual Rp − [Rf + β(Rm − Rf)]\n  = Actual Return − CAPM Required Return\n\nInterpretation:\n• α > 0 → Manager OUTPERFORMED ✅ (skilled manager)\n• α = 0 → Manager matched CAPM expectation ⚖️\n• α < 0 → Manager UNDERPERFORMED ❌ (poor manager)\n\n📌 Short-term alpha (< 1 year) is not valid — minimum 3-year period needed for reliable judgment\n📌 Positive alpha = Fund manager adding value above market compensation for risk",
    exam:false },

  { id:161, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ What is the difference between Feasible Portfolio, Efficient Portfolio and Optimal Portfolio?",
    back:"📦 Feasible Portfolio:\n→ Any possible combination of chosen securities\n→ ALL portfolios that can be constructed (the entire shaded region on the risk-return graph)\n→ Most are suboptimal\n\n⭐ Efficient Portfolio:\n→ A feasible portfolio that is NOT dominated\n→ Either: Highest return for a given risk level\n→ Or: Lowest risk for a given return level\n→ Lies on the EFFICIENT FRONTIER (the curved boundary)\n\n🎯 Optimal Portfolio:\n→ The SINGLE best portfolio for a SPECIFIC investor\n→ Point where investor's indifference curve is TANGENT to the Efficient Frontier\n→ Different for different investors (depends on risk appetite)\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Hierarchy: Feasible ⊃ Efficient ⊃ Optimal (1 point)\n📌 Optimal portfolio is UNIQUE per investor",
    exam:false },

  { id:162, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ Which type of analysis is best under which Market Efficiency level?\n(Technical / Fundamental / Random Selection)",
    back:"Market Efficiency Level → Best Approach:\n\n1️⃣ Inefficient Market\n→ Best: Technical Analysis\n→ Past patterns are useful; mispricing exists and persists\n\n2️⃣ Weak Form Efficiency\n→ Best: Fundamental Analysis\n→ Price history = no edge; but fundamentals can still reveal value\n\n3️⃣ Semi-Strong Form Efficiency\n→ Best: Fundamental Analysis (still good)\n→ All public info reflected in price; fundamentals + private info helps\n\n4️⃣ Strong Form Efficiency\n→ Best: Random Selection\n→ ALL info (including insider) reflected; no analysis adds value\n\n📌 EMH = Efficient Market Hypothesis\n📌 In practice, markets are NEVER perfectly efficient\n📌 Random Walk Theory: Share price movements are random; neither FA nor TA gives sustained advantage",
    exam:false },

  { id:163, subject:"AFM", standard:"Portfolio Management", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ Full forms & 1-line meaning:\nCAPM | CML | SML | APT | EMH | CPPI | APS",
    back:"📋 Quick Reference:\n\nCAPM → Capital Asset Pricing Model\n(Links expected return to systematic risk via Beta)\n\nCML → Capital Market Line\n(Risk-return line for EFFICIENT portfolios; uses SD)\n\nSML → Security Market Line\n(Risk-return line for ALL securities; uses Beta — this IS CAPM plotted graphically)\n\nAPT → Arbitrage Pricing Theory\n(Multi-factor alternative to CAPM; uses macro factors)\n\nEMH → Efficient Market Hypothesis\n(Markets fully reflect available information; no consistent excess returns)\n\nCPPI → Constant Proportion Portfolio Insurance\n(Rebalancing: buy shares as they rise; set floor value)\n\nAPS → Active Portfolio Strategy\n(Aim to outperform market via timing, rotation, selection)\n\n📌 SML and CML differ in risk measure — this is a COMMON MCQ trap",
    exam:false },

  // AFM · Mutual Funds
  // ── CONCEPT ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:165, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What is a Mutual Fund?",
    back:"A trust that pools savings of numerous investors sharing a common financial goal, managed by professional money managers who invest in capital market instruments (shares, debentures, bonds) and money-market instruments (CPs, CDs, T-Bills).\n\n📌 Net income + capital appreciation shared in proportion to units held.",
    exam:false },
  { id:166, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the 3 classifications of Mutual Funds?",
    back:"1️⃣ Functional Classification\n→ Open-Ended, Close-Ended, Interval Funds\n\n2️⃣ Portfolio Classification\n→ Equity Funds, Debt Funds, Special Funds\n\n3️⃣ Ownership Classification\n→ Public Sector, Private Sector, Foreign MFs\n\n📌 Exam Tip: All 3 types are frequently asked as short theory.",
    exam:false },

  // FIX #3 — Interval fund description: removed "no defined maturity" claim
  { id:167, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"Differentiate: Open-Ended vs Close-Ended vs Interval Funds",
    back:"🔓 Open-Ended: Enter/exit anytime. Unlimited capital. Redemption indefinite. Transact at NAV.\n\n🔒 Close-Ended: Entry only via NFO or stock exchange. Limited life. Exit via stock exchange or maturity. Traded like shares.\n\n⏱ Interval: Hybrid of both. Open for purchase/redemption only during specified intervals. Behaves like close-ended between intervals. NOT required to be listed.\n\n📌 Key distinction from Close-Ended: no mandatory listing requirement.",
    exam:false },
  { id:168, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Name the 3 types of Equity Funds and who they suit",
    back:"📈 Growth Funds\n→ Long-term capital appreciation\n→ Best for: Long-term investors\n\n🚀 Aggressive Funds\n→ Super-normal returns via startups, IPOs, speculative shares\n→ Best for: Risk-takers\n\n💰 Income Funds\n→ Maximize current income via high-dividend stocks + high-yield MM instruments\n→ Best for: Investors seeking current income\n\n📌 Exam Tip: Match fund type to investor profile in MCQs.",
    exam:false },
  { id:169, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the 4 risks in Bond / Debt Funds?",
    back:"1. 📉 Interest Rate Risk\nInverse relationship: ↑ interest rate → ↓ bond market value\n\n2. ❌ Credit Risk\nDefault in interest/principal payment. Higher risk for lower credit-rated companies.\n\n3. 🔁 Prepayment Risk\nEarly redemption by issuer (Callable Bonds) when interest rates fall.\n\n4. 🔄 Reinvestment Risk\nOn maturity in falling rate environment, proceeds reinvested at lower rate → reduces yield.\n\n📌 Prepayment and Reinvestment Risk are opposites in falling rate scenario.",
    exam:false },
  { id:170, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is an Index Fund? How is it different from a Quant Fund?",
    back:"📊 Index Fund\n→ Passively tracks benchmark index (e.g., NIFTY 50)\n→ Invests in same weightage as index stocks\n→ Low cost; Fund manager follows index\n\n🤖 Quant Fund\n→ Uses data-driven mathematical/statistical models\n→ Fund manager DESIGNS + MONITORS models\n→ Decisions based on model outcomes\n→ Eliminates human bias\n\n⚡ Key Difference: Index Fund Manager = no active decision. Quant Fund Manager = designs model.\n\n📌 Expense ratio of Quant funds < Actively managed funds.",
    exam:false },
  { id:171, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is an ETF? How does it differ from open-ended MF?",
    back:"📦 Exchange Traded Fund (ETF)\n→ Hybrid: features of listed stocks + index fund\n→ Listed on stock exchange\n→ Can be bought/sold ANY TIME during market hours\n→ No paperwork; buy like any stock via broker\n→ Low cost, tax efficient\n\n🆚 vs. Open-Ended MF:\n• Open-ended: transact at END-OF-DAY NAV\n• ETF: transact at REAL-TIME prices\n• ETF authorized participants act as market makers\n\nTypes: Index ETF, Commodity ETF, Bond ETF, Currency ETF\n\n📌 ETF = closed-end tradability + open-end valuation features.",
    exam:false },
  { id:172, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is Side Pocketing in Mutual Funds?",
    back:"🗂 Side Pocketing = Separation of risky/stressed assets from liquid assets in a fund.\n\nPurpose:\n✅ Protect liquid asset holders from distress selling\n✅ Lock stressed assets until recovery\n✅ NAV reflects only liquid asset value after side pocketing\n\nHow it works:\n→ When a security's rating falls, it's moved to 'side pocket'\n→ Remaining portfolio carries on normally\n\nReal Example: IL&FS crisis — funds wrote off IL&FS exposure.\n\n⚠️ Con: Can also be misused to deprive investors of genuine returns.\n\n📌 Common internationally; gaining prominence in India post-IL&FS.",
    exam:false },

  // FIX #4 — Tracking Error: "Higher TE = Higher risk profile" replaced with "poorer index tracking"
  { id:173, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is Tracking Error? What causes it?",
    back:"📐 Tracking Error = Deviation of a fund's return from its benchmark index return\n\nFormula:\nTE = √[Σ(d - d̄)² / (n-1)]\nwhere d = differential return, d̄ = average differential return\n\nGoal: TE → 0 (perfect replication)\n\nCauses of Tracking Error:\n• Transaction costs\n• AMC fees\n• Fund expenses\n• Cash holdings\n• Sampling bias\n\n📌 Higher TE = Poorer index tracking (greater deviation from benchmark).\n📌 Mainly relevant for Passively Managed / Index Funds.",
    exam:false },
  { id:174, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"What are Direct Plans in Mutual Funds? Why do they outperform Regular Plans?",
    back:"📋 Direct Plans (introduced by SEBI on 1 Jan 2013):\n→ Investor invests directly with AMC\n→ No distribution expenses, trail fees, or transaction charges\n→ Higher NAV compared to Regular Plan\n\nWhy Direct > Regular:\n→ Lower Total Expense Ratio (TER)\n→ The fee difference compounds over time\n→ Studies confirm Direct Plans outperform Regular Plans across almost all schemes\n\n📌 Before Jan 2013, even direct investors were tracked under regular plan NAV — no separate plans existed.",
    exam:false },

  // ── FORMULA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:175, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 NAV Formula — Write it completely",
    back:"NAV = Net Assets of Scheme / No. of Units Outstanding\n\n──────────────────────────────\nNet Assets = Market Value of Investments\n  + Receivables\n  + Other Accrued Income\n  + Other Assets\n  − Accrued Expenses\n  − Other Payables\n  − Other Liabilities\n──────────────────────────────\n\n📌 KEY: NAV is calculated on 'mark-to-market' basis (use MARKET VALUE, not cost)\n📌 If market value not given → use book value\n📌 NAV changes DAILY",
    exam:true },
  { id:176, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 Return on Mutual Fund — Period Return Formula",
    back:"r = [(NAVt − NAVt-1) + It + Gt] / NAVt-1\n\nWhere:\n• NAVt = NAV at end of period\n• NAVt-1 = NAV at start\n• It = Income/Dividend per unit\n• Gt = Capital Gain distribution per unit\n\n──────────────────────────────\nExample (ICAI):\nNAV₀ = ₹20, NAVt = ₹20.06\nDividend = ₹0.0375, Cap. Gain = ₹0.03\n\nr = (0.06 + 0.0375 + 0.03) / 20\n  = 0.1275 / 20 = 0.6375% monthly\n  = 7.65% p.a.\n\n📌 Annualize by × 12 (months) or × 365/days",
    exam:true },
  { id:177, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Required MF Earnings Formula (when expenses given)",
    back:"R₂ = [1 / (1 − Initial Expenses%)] × R₁ + Recurring Expenses%\n\nWhere:\n• R₁ = Investor's desired return\n• R₂ = MF needs to earn this\n\n──────────────────────────────\nExample (ICAI Practical Q1):\nR₁ = 16%, Initial exp = 5.5%, Recurring = 1.5%\n\nR₂ = [1/(1−0.055)] × 16% + 1.5%\n   = [1/0.945] × 16% + 1.5%\n   = 16.93% + 1.5%\n   = 18.43%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Logic: Initial expense reduces the investable amount, so fund must earn more to compensate.",
    exam:true },

  // FIX #1 & #2 — Corrected Front-End Load formula (divide by POP, not NAV) and Exit Load formula
  { id:178, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"📐 Front-End Load (Entry Load) & Back-End Load (Exit Load) Formulas",
    back:"🟢 Entry Load (Front-End):\nPOP = NAV / (1 − Front-end Load)\nor\nFront-end Load% = (POP − NAV) / POP  ← divide by POP\n\n🔴 Exit Load (Back-End):\nRedemption Price = NAV × (1 − Back-end Load%)\nor\nBack-end Load% = (NAV − Redemption Price) / NAV\n\n──────────────────────────────\nExample:\nNAV = ₹10, POP = ₹10.204\nFront-end = (10.204 − 10) / 10.204 = 2.00%\n\nExit load = 2%\nRedemption = 10 × (1 − 0.02) = ₹9.80\n\n📌 Currently NO entry load charged in India.\n📌 Front-end load denominator is POP (not NAV).",
    exam:true },
  { id:179, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"📐 Sharpe, Treynor & Sortino Ratios — Formulas & Differences",
    back:"📊 Sharpe Ratio = (Rp − Rf) / σp\n→ Uses TOTAL risk (std deviation)\n→ Suitable when portfolio is NOT fully diversified\n→ Higher = Better\n\n📊 Treynor Ratio = (Rp − Rf) / βp\n→ Uses SYSTEMATIC risk (Beta)\n→ Suitable for WELL-DIVERSIFIED portfolios\n→ Higher = Better\n\n📊 Sortino Ratio = (Rp − Rf) / Downside Deviation\n→ Variation of Sharpe\n→ Uses DOWNSIDE deviation only\n→ More relevant when returns are asymmetric\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 If both Sharpe & Treynor rank same → perfectly diversified fund.\nIf different rankings → some unsystematic risk exists.",
    exam:true },
  { id:180, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"📐 Jensen's Alpha — Formula & Interpretation",
    back:"Jensen's Alpha (α) = Rp − [Rf + βp(Rm − Rf)]\n\nOR:\nα = Actual Return − CAPM Required Return\n\n──────────────────────────────\nInterpretation:\n✅ α > 0: Fund OUTPERFORMED (good manager)\n❌ α < 0: Fund UNDERPERFORMED (poor manager)\n⚖️ α = 0: Performed exactly as per market risk\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Beta calculation when not given:\nβ = (σp × r) / σm\nwhere r = correlation, σm = market std deviation\n\n📌 Exam Tip (May 2023): NAV computation with Sharpe + Treynor → first derive Beta using both ratios → then compute new NAV.",
    exam:true },
  { id:181, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"📐 Effective Yield per Annum — Formula",
    back:"Effective Yield p.a. = (Total Gain / Investment) × (365 / Days held) × 100\n\nTotal Gain = Change in NAV + Dividends Received\n\n──────────────────────────────\nExample (ICAI Q10 — Mr. Sinha):\nInvestment = ₹5,00,000\nNAV change = −₹4,761.88\nDividend = ₹9,500\nTotal Gain = ₹4,738.12\nDays = 121\n\nEY = (4738.12/5,00,000) × (365/121) × 100\n   = 2.859% p.a.\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 This formula is REPEATEDLY asked across multiple ICAI questions (Q10, Q11 pattern).",
    exam:true },

  // FIX #4 — Tracking Error formula card updated
  { id:182, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"📐 Tracking Error Formula",
    back:"TE = √[Σ(d − d̄)² / (n−1)]\n\nWhere:\n• d = Differential return (Fund return − Benchmark return)\n• d̄ = Average of all differential returns\n• n = Number of observations\n\n──────────────────────────────\nIdeal Value: TE → 0\n\nInterpretation:\n• Low TE: Fund closely replicates benchmark ✅\n• High TE: Fund deviates significantly from benchmark ❌\n\n📌 Higher TE = Poorer index tracking (not necessarily higher risk).\n📌 Used mainly for Index Funds / Passive Funds.",
    exam:false },

  // ── PRACTICAL ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:183, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: Mr. X earns 10% on equity. An MF has 6% initial expenses and 2% recurring expenses. What must the MF earn to give Mr. X 10%?",
    back:"Using formula:\nR₂ = [1/(1 − Initial Exp)] × R₁ + Recurring Exp\n\nR₂ = [1/(1 − 0.06)] × 0.10 + 0.02\n   = [1/0.94] × 0.10 + 0.02\n   = 0.1064 + 0.02\n   = 0.1264 = 12.64%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n✅ Answer: MF must earn 12.64%\n\n📌 Step-by-step logic:\n1. Initial expense reduces investable corpus\n2. Divide desired return by (1 − initial expense)\n3. Add back recurring expenses",
    exam:true },
  { id:184, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q: NAV = ₹20. Income distribution = ₹0.0375. Capital gain = ₹0.03. End NAV = ₹20.06. Find monthly return.",
    back:"r = [(NAVt − NAVt-1) + It + Gt] / NAVt-1\n\nr = [(20.06 − 20) + 0.0375 + 0.03] / 20\n  = [0.06 + 0.0675] / 20\n  = 0.1275 / 20\n  = 0.006375\n  = 0.6375% per month\n  = 7.65% per annum\n\n──────────────────────────────\n✅ Monthly return = 0.6375%\n✅ Annual return = 7.65%\n\n📌 Always annualize by multiplying by 12 unless exam specifies otherwise.",
    exam:true },
  { id:185, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"🧮 300 units of MF purchased at ₹12.25. Dividend = ₹1.25/unit. Cap gain = ₹1.00/unit. End NAV = ₹13.00. Find return on investment.",
    back:"Return per unit:\n• Change in price = 13.00 − 12.25 = ₹0.75\n• Dividend = ₹1.25\n• Cap gain = ₹1.00\n• Total = ₹3.00\n\nReturn = 3.00 / 12.25 × 100\n       = 24.49%\n\n──────────────────────────────\n🔄 If REINVESTED at ₹12.50/unit:\nTotal reinvested = ₹2.25 × 300 = ₹675\nNew units = 675 / 12.50 = 54 units\nTotal units = 354\nEnd value = 354 × ₹13 = ₹4,602\nCost = 300 × 12.25 = ₹3,675\nReturn = (4602 − 3675) / 3675 = 25.22%\n\n✅ Reinvestment gives higher return (25.22% > 24.49%)",
    exam:true },
  { id:186, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 NAV Calculation: A fund holds shares worth ₹4,20,20,000. Accrued expenses = ₹2,50,000. Other liabilities = ₹2,00,000. Total units = 10 lakh. Find NAV per unit.",
    back:"Net Assets = Market Value − Liabilities\n\nTotal MV of shares = ₹4,20,20,000\nLess: Accrued Expenses = ₹2,50,000\nLess: Other Liabilities  = ₹2,00,000\n────────────────────────\nNet Assets = ₹4,15,70,000\n\nNAV per unit = ₹4,15,70,000 / 10,00,000\n             = ₹41.57\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Always use MARKET VALUE of investments\n📌 When new investor adds money → new units = Amount / Current NAV\n📌 Total units increases; per unit NAV remains same",
    exam:true },
  { id:187, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 EXAM Q (May 2023 pattern): MF has Sharpe = 2, Treynor = 15, SD = 11.25. Market falls 5%. NAV = ₹70.71 (99% equity, 1% cash). Cost = ₹3/unit p.a. Find NAV after 1 month.",
    back:"Step 1 — Find Beta using both ratios:\nSharpe: E(R)−Rf = 2 × 11.25 = 22.50\nTreynor: 15 = 22.50 / β → β = 1.50\n\nStep 2 — Equity & Cash split:\nEquity = 99% × 70.71 = ₹70\nCash = 1% × 70.71 = ₹0.71\n\nStep 3 — Equity falls by:\nMarket fell 5% × β 1.50 = 7.5%\nNew Equity = 70 × (1 − 0.075) = ₹64.75\n\nStep 4 — Adjust cash for monthly cost:\nMonthly cost = 3/12 = ₹0.25\nCash after 1 month = 0.71 − 0.25 = ₹0.46\n\n✅ New NAV = 64.75 + 0.46 = ₹65.21",
    exam:true },
  { id:188, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"🧮 Hedge Fund Fee: ANP Fund assets = ₹20 Cr. Fixed fee = 0.10%. Incentive fee = 2% on excess over ₹21 Cr high watermark. Return = 29%. Calculate total fee.",
    back:"Fixed Fee = 0.10% × ₹20 Cr = ₹2,00,000\n\nNew Fund Value = 1.29 × ₹20 Cr = ₹25.80 Cr\n\nExcess over high watermark:\n= 25.80 − 21.00 = ₹4.80 Cr\n\nIncentive Fee = 2% × ₹4.80 Cr\n              = ₹9,60,000\n\n✅ Total Fee = 2,00,000 + 9,60,000 = ₹11,60,000\n\n──────────────────────────────\nScenario B (4.5% return):\nNew value = ₹20.90 Cr < ₹21 Cr (HWM)\n→ No incentive fee → Total = ₹2,00,000\n\nScenario C (−1.8% return):\n→ Only fixed fee = ₹2,00,000\n\n📌 High Watermark: Incentive only when fund exceeds all-time peak.",
    exam:true },

  // ── THEORY Q&A ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:189, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"How do you establish a Mutual Fund in India? Key SEBI requirements?",
    back:"1. Register with SEBI before collecting public funds\n\n2. Sponsor:\n→ Body corporate in financial services ≥ 5 years\n→ Financially sound\n→ Must contribute ≥ 40% of AMC net worth\n\n3. Trust structure:\n→ Established under Indian Trust Act\n→ Trust deed registered under Indian Registration Act 1908\n\n4. AMC:\n→ Limited liability company\n→ Minimum net worth = ₹100 Crores\n→ 50% independent directors\n→ Can be terminated by majority trustees or 75% unit holders\n\n5. Board of Trustees:\n→ At least 2/3 independent directors\n\n6. Custodian: Must be independent of sponsor & AMC",
    exam:false },

  // FIX #5 — Expense ratio cap updated to reflect AUM-slab structure
  { id:190, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What are the key ADVANTAGES of Mutual Funds? (List 6 exam-worthy ones)",
    back:"1. 🧑‍💼 Professional Management\nSkilled managers + research team\n\n2. 🌐 Diversification\nReduces concentration risk\n\n3. 💧 Liquidity\nOpen-ended: direct redemption; Close-ended: stock exchange listing\n\n4. 🔍 Transparency\nSEBI mandates half-yearly portfolio disclosure; daily NAV via AMFI\n\n5. 💸 Low Cost\nSEBI places upper caps on TER based on AUM slabs (around 2.25–2.5% for equity MFs; declines as AUM grows)\n\n6. 📊 Economies of Scale\nPooled funds → lower transaction costs vs. direct market investment\n\n+ Flexibility (SIP, SWP), Convenience, Highly Regulated by SEBI\n\n📌 Write 6–8 with 1-line explanation each for 4-mark questions.",
    exam:false },
  { id:191, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What are the DRAWBACKS of Mutual Funds? (4 key drawbacks)",
    back:"1. ❌ No Guarantee of Return\n• Some schemes underperform benchmark\n• Different entry/exit points → different investor returns\n• Short-term loss possible in market crashes (2008, Covid 2020)\n\n2. 📉 Diversification Dilutes Gains\n• Can't match returns of a single high-performing stock\n• Neither exceptionally good nor bad\n\n3. 🔍 Difficult Fund Selection\n• Past performance ≠ future performance\n• Harder than picking stocks\n\n4. 💰 Cost Factor\n• Annual Management Fee (regardless of performance)\n• Exit Load if redeemed before stipulated period",
    exam:false },
  { id:192, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"Describe the Role of a Fund Manager in Active vs Passive funds",
    back:"🎯 Actively Managed Funds:\n→ Use extensive research, judgement & due diligence\n→ Aim to OUTPERFORM market (generate positive Alpha)\n→ Right stock picking = competitive advantage\n\n📊 Passively Managed Funds:\n→ Match benchmark return with minimum Tracking Error\n→ No stock selection; purely replication\n\nOther roles of Fund Manager:\n1. Compliance — SEBI, AMFI guidelines, timely reporting\n2. Continuous monitoring — enter/exit decisions\n3. Wealth Creation — Fundamental + Technical analysis\n4. Control over outsourced work\n\n📌 Performance judged on: return ABOVE inflation + interest rate.",
    exam:false },

  // FIX #6 — Trail commission: removed spurious 0.30–0.75% range
  { id:193, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"What is Trail Commission? What is Expense Ratio (TER)?",
    back:"💸 Trail Commission:\n→ Annual fee paid by MF investor to distributor/advisor\n→ A percentage of daily average AUM paid periodically to distributors\n→ Paid MONTHLY (% of daily avg AUM)\n→ Purpose: Incentivize advisor to review + advise holdings periodically\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📊 Expense Ratio (TER / MER):\n→ % of assets spent to RUN the mutual fund annually\n→ Includes: Management fees, advisory fees, audit, custodian, registrar, consultancy fees\n→ Does NOT include brokerage costs\n→ SEBI places upper caps on TER based on AUM slabs (around 2.25–2.5% for equity MFs)\n→ Can significantly impact long-term returns\n\n📌 Lower expense ratio = better for investor (especially in Direct Plans).",
    exam:false },

  // FIX #7 — FIIs → FPIs correction
  { id:194, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"What is the role of Foreign Investors in Mutual Funds? (3 key impacts)",
    back:"Foreign Portfolio Investors (FPIs) and NRIs can invest in Indian mutual funds:\n→ Directly from issuer, OR\n→ Via registered stock broker on recognized exchange\n→ Subject to SEBI limits\n\n📌 Note: FPIs mainly invest directly in listed securities; FPI investment in MF units is a subset.\n\n3 Key Impacts on Indian Economy:\n\n1. 🏛 Enhanced Corporate Governance\n→ Foreign investors conduct thorough due diligence → forces companies to improve governance\n\n2. 📈 Improved Market Competition\n→ Their entry increases efficiency and competition\n\n3. 💵 Improved Capital Inflow + Foreign Exchange\n→ Generates employment + strengthens forex reserves\n\n⚠️ Note: Foreign flows can fuel a BULLISH market for SHORT periods → can reverse quickly.",
    exam:false },

  // ── QUICK FIRE ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  { id:195, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ TRUE or FALSE:\n\nEntrance Load is currently charged by all Mutual Funds in India.",
    back:"❌ FALSE\n\nAs of now, NO Mutual Fund Scheme charges any Entry Load/Entry Charge.\n\nExit Load is still charged if units are redeemed before a stipulated holding period.\n\n📌 This was abolished by SEBI to reduce mis-selling by distributors who were incentivized to churn portfolios.",
    exam:false },
  { id:196, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ FILL IN THE BLANK:\n\nIn a Close-Ended fund, at least _____ of unit holders can terminate the AMC.",
    back:"✅ 75%\n\nAlso note:\n• Majority of trustees can ALSO terminate the AMC\n• 2/3 of trustees must be INDEPENDENT\n• 50% of AMC directors must be INDEPENDENT\n\n📌 Full structure of control:\nTrustees (majority) → terminate AMC\nUnit holders (75%) → terminate AMC\n\nThis ensures investor protection under SEBI Mutual Fund Regulations.",
    exam:false },
  { id:197, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ MATCH: Which ratio uses which risk measure?\n\nA. Sharpe Ratio\nB. Treynor Ratio\nC. Sortino Ratio\nD. Jensen's Alpha",
    back:"A. Sharpe → Standard Deviation (Total Risk)\n\nB. Treynor → Beta (Systematic Risk only)\n\nC. Sortino → Downside Deviation only (not full SD)\n\nD. Jensen's Alpha → Beta via CAPM\n   (Actual Return − CAPM Expected Return)\n\n──────────────────────────────\n📌 Memory trick:\n• SHARP → Standard deviation\n• TREYNOR → TRacks Beta\n• SorTINO → only downside TIN (negative)\n• Jensen = Excess alpha above CAPM",
    exam:false },

  // Minor improvement: added "NAV drops ex-dividend" note
  { id:198, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ What happens to NAV when a dividend is declared and paid out?",
    back:"📉 NAV FALLS by the amount of dividend paid out (on ex-dividend date).\n\nExample:\nNAV before dividend = ₹16\nDividend paid = ₹4 per unit\nNAV after dividend = ₹12 (ex-dividend NAV)\n\n──────────────────────────────\nOptions for investors:\n\n1. Dividend Payout: Receive cash; NAV falls\n2. Dividend Reinvestment: Cash reinvested at ex-dividend NAV; get more units; NAV still falls but unit count increases\n3. Growth Option: No dividend; NAV keeps growing until you sell\n\n📌 In dividend reinvestment, total investment value remains same on ex-dividend date — only unit count changes.",
    exam:false },
  { id:199, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Advanced",
    front:"⚡ Which fund type is close-ended by SEBI mandate?\n\nA. ETF\nB. Capital Protection Oriented Fund\nC. Real Estate MF (REMF)\nD. Both B and C",
    back:"✅ Answer: D — Both B and C\n\n📋 Capital Protection Oriented Fund:\n→ Must be CLOSE-ENDED\n→ Listed on stock exchange\n→ Portfolio structure rated by credit rating agency\n→ Invests majority in high-rated debt + some equity for appreciation\n→ ≠ Capital Guaranteed (no bank guarantee)\n\n🏠 Real Estate MF (REMF):\n→ Close-ended by nature\n→ Listed on stock exchange\n→ Earns rentals + capital appreciation\n→ Also invests in equity/debentures of real estate companies",
    exam:false },
  { id:200, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ What does ELSS stand for and what are its key features?",
    back:"ELSS = Equity Linked Savings Scheme\n\nKey Features:\n✅ Tax saving under Section 80C of Income Tax Act\n✅ Lock-in period: 3 YEARS (shortest among all 80C instruments)\n✅ Invests in equity → potential for higher returns vs traditional tax savers\n✅ Can invest via SIP (benefit of rupee cost averaging)\n\n📌 Comparison with other 80C instruments:\n• PPF: 15 years lock-in\n• ELSS: 3 years lock-in → most liquid tax-saving option\n• NSC: 5 years\n\n📌 ELSS = equity-oriented; hence higher risk but higher potential returns.",
    exam:false },
  { id:201, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Intermediate",
    front:"⚡ What is a Fund of Funds (FoF)?",
    back:"📦 Fund of Funds = Mutual fund scheme that invests in OTHER mutual fund schemes (not directly in securities)\n\nKey Points:\n• Underlying investment = units of other MF schemes\n• From same fund family OR other fund houses\n• Popular where MF offerings are numerous and choosing is complex\n\nExample: Indian MFs investing in International MF schemes\n\nPros:\n✅ Diversification across fund managers\n✅ Access to international markets easily\n\nCons:\n❌ Double expense ratio (own + underlying fund's expense)\n\n📌 FoF is categorized under Special Funds in Portfolio Classification.",
    exam:false },
  { id:202, subject:"AFM", standard:"Mutual Funds", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic",
    front:"⚡ Full form & meaning:\nAMFI | AMC | NFO | SIP | SWP | TER",
    back:"📋 Quick Reference:\n\nAMFI → Association of Mutual Funds in India\n(Publishes daily NAV, regulates distributors)\n\nAMC → Asset Management Company\n(Manages the MF; runs schemes; TER capped per SEBI AUM slabs)\n\nNFO → New Fund Offer\n(Like IPO for MFs; initial subscription period)\n\nSIP → Systematic Investment Plan\n(Regular fixed investment at intervals)\n\nSWP → Systematic Withdrawal Plan\n(Regular fixed withdrawal from investment)\n\nTER → Total Expense Ratio\n(Same as MER — Management Expense Ratio)\n\n📌 NAV published daily through AMFI in newspapers.",
    exam:false }

// ══ FR · Ind AS 23 — Borrowing Costs ════════════════════════════

  { id:325, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Core Principle & Scope\n\nState the CORE PRINCIPLE.\nWhat 3 items are EXCLUDED from scope?",
    back:"Core Principle:\n(a) Borrowing costs DIRECTLY ATTRIBUTABLE to acquisition, construction or production of a QUALIFYING ASSET → must be CAPITALISED as part of that asset's cost.\n(b) All OTHER borrowing costs → recognised as EXPENSE in the period incurred.\n\nScope Exclusions (standard does NOT apply to):\n(a) Actual or imputed COST OF EQUITY — including preference capital NOT classified as a liability\n(b) Qualifying assets measured at FAIR VALUE — e.g., biological assets under Ind AS 41 (capitalisation would only reallocate between finance cost and FV movement; no balance sheet effect)\n(c) INVENTORIES manufactured/produced in LARGE QUANTITIES ON A REPETITIVE BASIS — due to difficulty in allocating borrowing costs to such inventories\n\n📌 Equity dividends on redeemable preference shares classified as financial liabilities (Ind AS 32) → DO qualify as borrowing costs.\n📌 Notional/imputed borrowing cost (e.g., forgone interest on own cash) → CANNOT be capitalised.", exam:true },

  { id:326, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Key Definitions\n\nDefine:\n1. Borrowing Costs (with 3 components)\n2. Qualifying Asset (include/exclude examples)",
    back:"1. BORROWING COSTS — Interest and other costs incurred in connection with borrowing funds. Includes:\n   (a) Interest expense calculated using the EFFECTIVE INTEREST RATE METHOD (Ind AS 109)\n   (b) Interest on LEASE LIABILITIES recognised per Ind AS 116\n   (c) EXCHANGE DIFFERENCES on foreign currency borrowings — to the extent regarded as an adjustment to interest costs\n\n2. QUALIFYING ASSET — Asset that NECESSARILY TAKES A SUBSTANTIAL PERIOD OF TIME to get ready for its intended use or sale.\n\n✅ Examples (QA): Manufacturing plants, power generation facilities, investment properties, intangible assets, inventories with long production cycle (e.g., cheese, whisky), bearer plants, real estate, infrastructure (bridges, railways)\n\n❌ NOT qualifying assets:\n• Financial assets\n• Inventories produced in large quantities on repetitive basis\n• Assets READY for intended use/sale WHEN ACQUIRED\n\n📌 12 months or more is likely 'substantial' — but no bright-line rule in Ind AS 23 (unlike AS 16 which explicitly states 12 months).", exam:true },

  { id:327, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Exchange Difference as Borrowing Cost\n\nWhen is an exchange difference on a foreign currency borrowing treated as a borrowing cost?\nWhat is the cap?",
    back:"Rule: Exchange differences on foreign currency borrowings are included as borrowing costs only to the extent they are an ADJUSTMENT TO INTEREST COSTS.\n\nCap Formula:\nMax exchange diff treatable as BC = Interest at FUNCTIONAL CURRENCY rate − Interest at FOREIGN CURRENCY rate\n\nIn other words: Exchange diff eligible = INR equivalent borrowing cost − Actual foreign currency interest\n\nLogic: The entity borrowed in foreign currency assuming total cost (interest + exchange) ≤ INR borrowing cost. Only the interest rate differential benefit is the 'adjustment'.\n\nExample 2 (ICAI):\n• INR rate: 12% → INR interest = ₹4,800\n• USD rate: 4% → USD interest converted = ₹2,000\n• Exchange loss = ₹10,000 (large, due to depreciation of INR)\n• Eligible exchange diff = ₹4,800 − ₹2,000 = ₹2,800\n• Total eligible BC = ₹2,000 + ₹2,800 = ₹4,800 (= INR equivalent)\n• Remaining ₹7,200 exchange loss → P&L as finance cost\n\n📌 If exchange loss < differential → entire exchange loss is eligible BC.\n📌 If subsequently exchange GAIN arises → reverse previous exchange loss recognized as BC (up to amount previously capitalized).", exam:true },

  { id:328, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Borrowing Costs Eligible for Capitalisation\n\nDistinguish between SPECIFIC and GENERAL borrowings.\nWhat is the eligible amount under each?",
    back:"SPECIFIC BORROWINGS:\n→ Borrowed specifically to obtain a qualifying asset.\n→ Eligible BC = Actual borrowing costs incurred LESS investment income on TEMPORARY INVESTMENT of those funds\n→ Note: Notional/imputed interest cannot be capitalised. Only actual costs.\n\nExample: Borrowed ₹30L @ 9%. Used ₹15L immediately; remaining ₹15L temporarily invested @ 7% for 6 months.\n→ BC eligible = (30L × 9%) − (15L × 7% × 6/12)\n\nGENERAL BORROWINGS:\n→ Funds not borrowed for a specific asset.\n→ Eligible BC = Expenditure on qualifying asset × Capitalisation Rate\n→ Capitalisation Rate = Weighted average of borrowing costs on ALL general borrowings outstanding during the period\n→ Amount capitalised ≤ actual total borrowing costs incurred\n\n📌 When specific borrowing remains outstanding AFTER the related asset is ready → it joins the general borrowings pool.\n📌 Specific borrowings EXCLUDED from the capitalisation rate calculation.\n📌 Expenditures include: cash payments + transfers of other assets + assumption of interest-bearing liabilities. Reduced by progress payments and grants received.", exam:true },

  { id:329, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Formula", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Capitalisation Rate Formula\n\nWrite the formula for Capitalisation Rate.\nBeta Ltd: 18% Bank Loan ₹10L, 16% Term Loan ₹30L outstanding.\n14% Debentures ₹20L raised specifically for office building.\nPlant (general): ₹5L on 1 Apr + ₹25L on 1 Jan. Year end 31 Mar.\n\nCompute: (a) Capitalisation rate (b) Borrowing cost to capitalise",
    back:"Capitalisation Rate (CR) formula:\nCR = (Total BC on general borrowings) / (Total general borrowings outstanding)\nSpecific borrowings → EXCLUDED from both numerator and denominator\n\n(a) CR calculation (exclude 14% Debentures — specific):\nNumerator   = (₹10L × 18%) + (₹30L × 16%) = ₹1.80L + ₹4.80L = ₹6.60L\nDenominator = ₹10L + ₹30L = ₹40L\nCR = 6.60 / 40 = 16.5%\n\n(b) Borrowing cost to capitalise (plant):\nOn ₹5,00,000 × 16.5% × 12/12 = ₹82,500\nOn ₹25,00,000 × 16.5% × 3/12 = ₹1,03,125\nTotal BC capitalised = ₹1,85,625\n\n📌 Cap check: Actual total BC incurred on general borrowings = ₹6.60L → ₹1.85L < ₹6.60L ✅\n📌 CR is WEIGHTED AVERAGE — weights are based on outstanding loan amounts.", exam:true },

  { id:330, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Period of Capitalisation\n\nState the COMMENCEMENT DATE conditions (all 3 must be met).\nWhat date is used when conditions are met on different dates?",
    back:"Commencement date = Date when ALL THREE conditions are FIRST met SIMULTANEOUSLY:\n(a) Entity INCURS EXPENDITURES for the asset\n    (includes: cash payments, transfers of assets, assumption of interest-bearing liabilities; reduced by progress payments and grants)\n(b) Entity INCURS BORROWING COSTS\n(c) Entity UNDERTAKES ACTIVITIES necessary to prepare the asset for intended use or sale\n    (includes: technical/administrative work like obtaining permits before physical construction)\n    (excludes: merely holding land with no development activity)\n\nCommencement = The LATEST DATE on which all 3 are satisfied\n\nIllustration 10 (ICAI):\n• BC incurred: 15 May 20X1\n• Activities started: 2 June 20X1\n• Expenditure incurred: 19 June 20X1\n• Construction starts: 18 July 20X1\n→ Commencement = 19 June 20X1 (all 3 conditions first satisfied)\n\n📌 Physical construction starting (18 July) is NOT the commencement date — activities (planning, permits) already count.\n📌 Land held without development → borrowing costs on related funding → NOT capitalised.", exam:true },

  { id:331, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Suspension & Cessation of Capitalisation\n\nWhen is capitalisation SUSPENDED?\nWhen does it CEASE?\nGive an example of each.",
    back:"SUSPENSION:\n→ Suspended during EXTENDED PERIODS when active development is INTERRUPTED.\n→ During suspension: costs = holding partially completed asset → NOT eligible.\n\n📌 NOT suspended for TEMPORARY delays that are a NECESSARY PART of the process:\n• High water levels delaying bridge construction (if common in that region) → continue capitalising\n• Slow-maturing inventories (whisky, cognac aging) → continue capitalising\n\nExample: Construction suspended Oct 20X1 – Jan 20X2 because heavy equipment was shifted to another site → SUSPEND capitalisation.\nBut: 20-day technical delay near completion → CONTINUE capitalisation (temporary).\n\nCESSATION:\n→ Cease when SUBSTANTIALLY ALL activities necessary to prepare the qualifying asset for intended use or sale are COMPLETE.\n→ Physical construction complete even if routine admin work continues → CEASE.\n→ Minor modifications (e.g., decoration per purchaser's spec) outstanding → CEASE.\n\nParts of an asset:\n• Business park (each building usable separately) → cease when EACH PART is complete.\n• Steel mill (sequential processes, all needed before use) → cease when ENTIRE plant is complete.\n\nExample 5: Commercial complex complete 31 May 20X1 but only 10% rented by 31 Mar 20X2. → Cease 31 May 20X1. Occupancy level is irrelevant.", exam:true },

  { id:332, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Disclosure Requirements\n\nWhat 2 items must be disclosed?\nAlso state: Can capitalisation continue when carrying amount exceeds recoverable amount?",
    back:"Mandatory Disclosures (only 2):\n(a) Amount of BORROWING COSTS CAPITALISED during the period\n(b) CAPITALISATION RATE used to determine borrowing costs eligible for capitalisation\n\n📌 Simple disclosure — only 2 items. (AS 16 does NOT require disclosure of capitalisation rate.)\n\nCarrying amount > Recoverable amount:\n→ When expected ultimate cost of qualifying asset exceeds its recoverable amount or NRV → write down or write off per requirements of other standards (e.g., Ind AS 36).\n→ In certain circumstances, amount can be written back per those other standards.\n\nGroup Capitalisation (Ind AS 23.18):\n→ Where borrowings are in Parent and qualifying asset is in Subsidiary → appropriate to capitalise in consolidated FS based on group borrowings.\n→ The entity that has no borrowings (subsidiary developing asset) → CANNOT capitalise in its own FS.\n→ BUT: if subsidiary has intra-group borrowings → can capitalise interest on those in its own FS.", exam:false },

  { id:333, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 vs AS 16 – Key Differences\n\nState 5 significant differences.",
    back:"1. SCOPE — FV Assets:\nInd AS 23: Does NOT apply to QAs measured at FAIR VALUE (e.g., biological assets under Ind AS 41)\nAS 16: No such exclusion\n\n2. SCOPE — Repetitive Inventories:\nInd AS 23: Does NOT apply to inventories manufactured in LARGE QUANTITIES ON REPETITIVE BASIS\nAS 16: Applies to all inventories requiring substantial time\n\n3. SUBSTANTIAL PERIOD:\nInd AS 23: No bright-line rule; facts & circumstances; 12+ months likely substantial\nAS 16: Explicitly defines substantial period as TWELVE MONTHS\n\n4. LEASE INTEREST:\nInd AS 23: Includes interest on LEASE LIABILITIES (Ind AS 116)\nAS 16: Includes finance charges on assets under FINANCE LEASE only\n\n5. DISCLOSURE:\nInd AS 23: Requires disclosure of CAPITALISATION RATE\nAS 16: No such disclosure requirement\n\n6. HYPERINFLATIONARY ECONOMIES:\nInd AS 23: Part of BC compensating for inflation → expense (per Ind AS 29)\nAS 16: No similar provision (no Indian standard on hyperinflation)\n\n7. EXCHANGE DIFFERENCE:\nInd AS 23: Differential computed vs FUNCTIONAL CURRENCY\nAS 16 read with AS 11: Differential vs LOCAL CURRENCY (same in practice for Indian entities)", exam:true },

  { id:334, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Quick Fire\n\n1. Borrowing cost on equity is ___\n2. Inventories on repetitive basis: capitalisation ___\n3. Capitalisation rate excludes ___ borrowings\n4. Commencement requires ___ conditions\n5. Capitalisation ceases when ___\n6. Disclosures required: ___",
    back:"1. Borrowing cost on equity: NOT APPLICABLE — excluded from scope of Ind AS 23\n\n2. Inventories on repetitive basis: Capitalisation NOT REQUIRED (scope exclusion)\n\n3. Capitalisation rate excludes SPECIFIC borrowings (only general borrowings used)\n\n4. Commencement requires 3 CONDITIONS (expenditure + borrowing costs + activities — all met simultaneously)\n\n5. Capitalisation ceases when SUBSTANTIALLY ALL activities to prepare asset for intended use or sale are COMPLETE\n\n6. Disclosures required:\n   (a) Amount of BC capitalised during the period\n   (b) Capitalisation rate used\n\nBonus quick facts:\n→ Notional/imputed interest on own cash → CANNOT be capitalised\n→ Temporary delay that is necessary part of process → do NOT suspend\n→ Extended interruption to active development → SUSPEND\n→ Specific borrowing after asset is ready → joins GENERAL borrowings pool\n→ BC capitalised ≤ actual BC incurred (hard cap)", exam:true },

  { id:335, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Practical: Specific Borrowings\n[Illustration 7 — Alpha Ltd]\n\nAlpha Ltd. borrowed ₹30,00,000 @ 9% on 1 Apr 20X1. Funds used for 2 qualifying assets. Remaining funds invested @ 7%.\n\nFactory Building: ₹5,00,000 on 1 Apr + ₹5,00,000 on 1 Oct\nOffice Building: ₹10,00,000 on 1 Apr + ₹10,00,000 on 1 Oct\n\nCalculate BC eligible for capitalisation and total cost of each asset.",
    back:"FACTORY BUILDING (loan allocated = ₹10,00,000):\nBorrowing cost = 10,00,000 × 9% = ₹90,000\nLess: Investment income = 5,00,000 × 7% × 6/12 = (₹17,500)\n  [₹5L unused Apr–Sep, invested @ 7%]\nNet BC eligible = ₹72,500\nTotal cost = ₹10,00,000 + ₹72,500 = ₹10,72,500\n\nOFFICE BUILDING (loan allocated = ₹20,00,000):\nBorrowing cost = 20,00,000 × 9% = ₹1,80,000\nLess: Investment income = 10,00,000 × 7% × 6/12 = (₹35,000)\n  [₹10L unused Apr–Sep, invested @ 7%]\nNet BC eligible = ₹1,45,000\nTotal cost = ₹20,00,000 + ₹1,45,000 = ₹21,45,000\n\n📌 KEY RULE: Specific BC = Actual BC incurred − Investment income on TEMPORARY INVESTMENT\n📌 Only actual costs — notional interest cannot be added\n📌 Investment income MUST be deducted (not optional)", exam:true },

  { id:336, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Practical: Mixed Specific + General Borrowings\n[Question 4 — K Ltd]\n\nBuilding construction started 1 Apr 20X1. Specific loan: ₹2L @ 9%.\nGeneral loans: ₹7L @ 12% and ₹9L @ 11%.\n\nExpenditures: Apr=₹1.5L, Aug=₹2L, Oct=₹3.5L, Jan=₹1L\nConstruction completed 31 Jan 20X2.\n\nCalculate: (a) Capitalisation rate (b) BC capitalised (c) Total asset cost",
    back:"(a) CAPITALISATION RATE (general borrowings only):\nNumerator   = (7,00,000 × 12%) + (9,00,000 × 11%) = 84,000 + 99,000 = 1,83,000\nDenominator = 7,00,000 + 9,00,000 = 16,00,000\nCR = 1,83,000 / 16,00,000 = 11.4375%\n\n(b) BC CAPITALISED:\n[Specific loan ₹2L used from Apr; remaining spent from general borrowings]\nDate    Amount    Financed by    Calculation                 BC\nApr     1,50,000  Specific       1,50,000 × 9% × 10/12   = 11,250\nAug     2,00,000  Specific(50K)  50,000 × 9% × 6/12      =  3,750\n                  General(1.5L)  1,50,000 × 11.4375% × 6/12 = 8,578\nOct     3,50,000  General        3,50,000 × 11.4375% × 4/12 = 13,344\nJan     1,00,000  General        1,00,000 × 11.4375% × 1/12 =    953\nTotal BC capitalised = ₹37,875\n\n(c) TOTAL ASSET COST:\nConstruction cost = 1,50,000+2,00,000+3,50,000+1,00,000 = ₹8,00,000\nAdd: BC capitalised                                       = ₹37,875\nTotal = ₹8,37,875\n\nJournal Entry (31 Jan 20X2):\nBuilding A/c Dr. 8,37,875\n  To Bank A/c       8,00,000\n  To Interest Payable  37,875", exam:true }

{ id:337, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Qualifying Asset: Management Intention & Part of Wider Project\n[Illustrations 2, 3 & 4]\n\n(i) Is computer software a qualifying asset?\n(ii) Does management intention matter in assessing a qualifying asset?\n(iii) A telecom company acquires a 3G licence (can be sold to 3rd party) to operate a wireless network. Is BC on the licence capitalisable?\n(iv) A real estate company acquires a permit (specific to one building) AND equipment (used for multiple buildings). Which qualifies?",
    back:"(i) Computer software — YES, qualifies if it takes substantial time to complete development (internally generated software in development phase). It is an intangible asset under Ind AS 38.\n\n(ii) Management intention — YES, it matters. If an acquired asset can only be used in combination with a larger group of fixed assets, or was acquired specifically for construction of one qualifying asset, the assessment is made on a COMBINED BASIS (not the asset in isolation).\n\n(iii) 3G Licence — YES, BC is capitalisable. The licence is the FIRST STEP in a wider investment project (building the network). The fact that it can be sold/licensed to 3rd parties is IRRELEVANT. What matters is management's intended use.\n\n(iv) Permit vs Equipment:\n✅ PERMIT → capitalise BC (specific to one building; first step in wider project)\n❌ EQUIPMENT → do NOT capitalise BC (used for multiple projects; ready for intended use at acquisition date)\n\n📌 Key rule: Assets that are ready for their intended use WHEN ACQUIRED are NOT qualifying assets, regardless of how they are used subsequently.", exam:true },

  { id:338, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Lease Interest & Dairy Products\n[Illustrations 1 & 5]\n\n(i) A dairy company produces ghee, butter and cheese. Cheese takes substantially longer to ready for sale. Can BC on cheese production be capitalised?\n\n(ii) A crane/dockyard is leased to construct a ship (qualifying asset). Can interest on the lease be capitalised as BC?",
    back:"(i) Cheese — YES, BC can be capitalised.\nInd AS 23 does not require capitalisation for inventories manufactured in LARGE QUANTITIES ON A REPETITIVE BASIS. However, if the production cycle takes a SUBSTANTIAL PERIOD OF TIME (as with cheese), interest capitalisation IS PERMITTED.\n\nNote: Ghee and butter produced quickly → NOT qualifying assets → no capitalisation.\nCheese takes substantial time → qualifying asset → capitalisation permitted.\n\n(ii) Crane/Dockyard lease — YES, interest on the lease IS capitalised.\nInterest on a lease is specific to an asset. It is capitalised if:\n• The leased asset IS a qualifying asset, OR\n• The leased asset is used SOLELY FOR CONSTRUCTION of a qualifying asset\n\nHere: ship = qualifying asset; crane/dockyard used solely for constructing the ship → interest on crane/dockyard lease capitalised as BC.\nCessation: capitalisation stops when construction of the ship (qualifying asset) is complete.\n\n📌 Lease interest meeting definition of BC → same rules apply as any other borrowing cost.", exam:true },

  { id:339, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Specific Borrowing Joining General Pool\n[Illustration 8 — A Ltd]\n\nA Ltd took ₹50L @ 8% on 1 Apr 20X1 specifically to construct Building A. Construction completed 31 Mar 20X3. Loan repayable 31 Mar 20X7.\nA Ltd begins construction of Building B in 20X3-20X4 using existing borrowings (₹25L @ 9% and ₹15L @ 7%).\n\nShould the specific borrowing (₹50L @ 8%) be transferred to the general pool after Building A is complete?",
    back:"YES — the specific borrowing MUST be transferred to the general borrowings pool once the related qualifying asset is complete.\n\nReason:\nBorrowing costs directly attributable to a qualifying asset are those that WOULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED if expenditure on that asset had not been made.\n\nOnce Building A is complete:\n→ If no new qualifying assets were being constructed, the entity could have used cash to REPAY the ₹50L loan.\n→ Since cash is being used for Building B instead of repaying the loan, those interest costs COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED.\n→ Therefore, the ₹50L loan is now attributable to Building B (or other QAs) → joins the general pool.\n\nFor Building B capitalisation rate:\nLoans: ₹50L @ 8% + ₹25L @ 9% + ₹15L @ 7%\nCR = (50L×8% + 25L×9% + 15L×7%) / (50L+25L+15L)\n   = (4L + 2.25L + 1.05L) / 90L\n   = 7.30L / 90L = 8.11%\n\n📌 Key principle: Once specific borrowing's qualifying asset is ready, treat that borrowing as GENERAL for any subsequent qualifying assets.", exam:true },

  { id:340, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Section 3.5.3 & 3.5.4: Expenditure Base & CA Exceeding Recoverable Amount\n\n(a) What expenditures form the BASE for applying the capitalisation rate?\n(b) What happens when carrying amount of a qualifying asset EXCEEDS its recoverable amount during construction?",
    back:"(a) EXPENDITURE BASE for capitalisation rate:\nIncludes ONLY expenditures that result in:\n✅ Payments of CASH\n✅ TRANSFERS of other assets\n✅ Assumption of INTEREST-BEARING LIABILITIES\n\nREDUCED by:\n❌ Progress payments received from third parties\n❌ Government grants received in connection with the asset (Ind AS 20)\n\nPractical approximation:\n→ Average carrying amount of the asset during the period (including BC previously capitalised) is normally a reasonable approximation of expenditure for applying the cap rate.\n\n(b) CA EXCEEDS RECOVERABLE AMOUNT:\n→ When carrying amount OR expected ultimate cost of the qualifying asset EXCEEDS its recoverable amount (Ind AS 36) or NRV (Ind AS 2) → the carrying amount is WRITTEN DOWN or WRITTEN OFF per requirements of those standards.\n→ In certain circumstances, the write-down/write-off may be WRITTEN BACK per those other standards.\n\n📌 This is a write-down trigger — not a suspension of capitalisation. BC continues to be capitalised until cessation criteria are met; separately, Ind AS 36 impairment is assessed.", exam:true },

  { id:341, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Dividends on Redeemable Preference Shares & Group Capitalisation\n[Section 3.8.1 & 3.8.2 | Illustration 11]\n\n(i) Redeemable preference shares classified as financial liabilities (Ind AS 32). Are dividends on these borrowing costs?\n(ii) Parent borrows; subsidiary constructs a qualifying asset. Who capitalises?\n(iii) Subsidiary has intra-group loan and constructs qualifying asset. Can it capitalise?",
    back:"(i) Dividends on redeemable preference shares classified as financial liabilities:\n→ YES — dividends on such instruments meet the definition of BORROWING COSTS.\n→ They are treated as interest expense and should be CAPITALISED following specific borrowing principles if used to fund a qualifying asset.\n→ Reason: Classification as financial liability (Ind AS 32) makes dividend economically equivalent to interest.\n\n(ii) Parent borrows; subsidiary constructs qualifying asset (no intra-group loan):\n→ Consolidated FS: MAY capitalise interest in consolidated FS if it fairly reflects interest cost of the group that could have been avoided.\n→ Subsidiary's own FS: CANNOT capitalise — subsidiary has NO BORROWINGS of its own.\n\n(iii) Subsidiary has INTRA-GROUP BORROWING and constructs qualifying asset:\n→ YES — subsidiary CAN capitalise in its own FS.\n→ Interest on intra-group borrowings is capitalised to the extent of actual costs incurred by the subsidiary.\n\n[Illustration 11]: Subsidiary finances construction of qualifying asset with inter-company loan → BC on inter-company loan IS capitalised in subsidiary's separate FS (actual costs incurred).\n\n📌 Summary: Own borrowings or intra-group borrowings = CAN capitalise. No borrowings at all = CANNOT capitalise.", exam:true },

  { id:342, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 23 – Cessation for Maturing Inventories\n[Section 3.8.3 | Example 7 — Whisky]\n\nWhen does capitalisation CEASE for maturing inventories (e.g., whisky)?\nWhat is the test applied?",
    back:"Challenge: For maturing inventories, it is difficult to determine when the 'production period' ends — i.e., when inventory is being held to MATURE vs held for SALE.\n\nRule:\n→ Capitalisation of BC MAY CONTINUE as long as it can be DEMONSTRATED that the inventory continues to INCREASE IN VALUE solely on account of INCREASING AGE.\n\nExample 7 — Whisky:\n→ Whisky is 'mature' after 3 years but improves further with age.\n→ If consistent with entity's business model to hold further for maturation, AND it can be demonstrated that value increase is solely due to age (NOT market fluctuations or inflation) → continue capitalising.\n→ If this CANNOT be demonstrated → treat inventory as HELD FOR SALE → cease capitalisation.\n\n📌 Two conditions to continue capitalisation:\n(a) Entity's business model supports continued holding for maturation\n(b) Value increase attributable SOLELY to age — not to market or inflation factors\n\n📌 If both cannot be met → inventories regarded as held for sale → NO further BC capitalisation.", exam:false },

  { id:343, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Practice Q1: Marine Transport Ltd (Commencement Date)\n\nMarine Transport ordered 3 ships on 1 Apr 20X0. Down payment (25%) from long-term borrowings made on 1 Apr 20X0. Delivery to commence FY 20X7. On 1 Mar 20X2, shipbuilder confirms production started on ONE ship only. No progress on other 2 ships.\n\nCan Marine Transport capitalise BC for FY ended 31 Mar 20X1 or 31 Mar 20X2?",
    back:"Ship = QUALIFYING ASSET (takes substantial time to construct).\n\nCommencement date test (ALL 3 must be met):\n(a) Expenditure incurred: ✅ 1 Apr 20X0 (down payment)\n(b) Borrowing costs incurred: ✅ 1 Apr 20X0 (long-term loan)\n(c) Activities necessary to prepare asset: ❌ NOT met until 1 Mar 20X2 (for 1 ship only)\n\nFY ended 31 Mar 20X1:\n→ Conditions (a) and (b) met. Condition (c) NOT met (no construction activity).\n→ NO CAPITALISATION permissible for any ship.\n\nFY ended 31 Mar 20X2:\n→ For the ONE ship: condition (c) met on 1 Mar 20X2.\n→ Capitalise BC from 1 Mar 20X2 to 31 Mar 20X2 (1 month) for that ship only.\n→ For the OTHER 2 ships: condition (c) still not met → no capitalisation.\n→ All other BC → expensed to P&L.\n\n📌 Key learning: Down payment + borrowing alone are NOT sufficient. Physical activity (production/construction) must also have commenced.\n📌 Each qualifying asset assessed independently.", exam:true },

  { id:344, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Practice Q2: X Ltd (Pure General Borrowings)\n\nX Ltd — general borrowings only:\nLong term loan @ 10%: Avg ₹10L, Interest ₹1,00,000\nWorking capital loan: Avg ₹5L, Interest ₹65,000\n\nExpenditure on qualifying asset:\n1 Jul 20X1: ₹2,50,000\n1 Dec 20X1: ₹3,00,000\n\nCompute BC to capitalise (year end 31 Mar 20X2).",
    back:"Step 1 — Capitalisation Rate:\nCR = Total BC / Total Borrowings\nCR = 1,65,000 / 15,00,000 = 11%\n\nStep 2 — BC Capitalised (time-weighted expenditure):\nOn ₹2,50,000 @ 11% × 9/12 (Jul 20X1 to Mar 20X2) = ₹20,625\nOn ₹3,00,000 @ 11% × 4/12 (Dec 20X1 to Mar 20X2) = ₹11,000\n\nTotal BC capitalised = ₹31,625\n\n📌 Note: Working capital loan is included in general borrowings pool (no restriction on type of borrowing — all non-specific borrowings qualify).\n📌 Time weighting: From date of expenditure to year end.\n📌 Cap check: ₹31,625 < ₹1,65,000 actual BC ✅", exam:true },

  { id:345, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Practice Q3: Capitalisation Rate with Variable Overdraft\n\nHead office construction: 1 Sep–31 Dec 20X1 (general borrowings only).\nExpenditures: ₹1L in Sep; ₹2.5L each in Oct, Nov, Dec.\n\nBorrowings during construction:\n• 10% Debentures ₹20L (full period)\n• Overdraft ₹5L @ 15% till 30 Sep, then @ 16%\n• Overdraft increases to ₹7.5L in December\n\nCalculate the capitalisation rate.",
    back:"Finance costs during Sep–Dec 20X1 (4 months):\n\n10% Debentures (₹20L × 10% × 4/12): ₹66,667\nOD ₹5L @ 15% (Sep only, 1 month): ₹6,250\nOD ₹5L @ 16% (Oct–Nov, 2 months): ₹13,333\nOD ₹7.5L @ 16% (Dec only, 1 month): ₹10,000\nTotal finance costs = ₹96,250\n\nWeighted Average Borrowings (over 4 months):\n= [(₹20L × 4) + (₹5L × 3) + (₹7.5L × 1)] / 4\n= [₹80L + ₹15L + ₹7.5L] / 4\n= ₹1,02,50,000 / 4\n= ₹25,62,500\n\nCapitalisation Rate = 96,250 / 25,62,500 = 3.756%\n\n📌 When overdraft fluctuates: use time-weighted average for the denominator.\n📌 When interest rates change during the period: calculate separately for each rate period.\n📌 Debentures carry full 4-month cost; overdraft carries proportionate months.", exam:true },

  { id:346, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Practice Q5: Entity A (Specific + General, Expenditure Allocation)\n\nEntity A — building contracted ₹22L, completed 31 Mar 20X2.\nPayments: 1 Apr ₹2L | 30 Jun ₹6L | 31 Dec ₹12L | 31 Mar ₹2L\n\nBorrowings:\n(a) Specific 10% note: ₹7L outstanding; interest ₹65,000; investment income ₹20,000\n(b) General 12.5% note: ₹10L\n(c) General 10% note: ₹15L\n\nDetermine BC eligible for capitalisation.",
    back:"Step 1 — Capitalisation Rate (general borrowings only):\nCR = (10L×12.5% + 15L×10%) / (10L+15L)\n   = (1.25L + 1.5L) / 25L = 2.75L/25L = 11%\n\nStep 2 — Expenditure allocation to general borrowings:\nSpecific loan ₹7L covers first ₹7L of expenditure.\n1 Apr: ₹2L → 100% specific → 0 to general\n30 Jun: ₹6L → ₹5L from specific (₹7L−₹2L) + ₹1L from general → ₹1L×9/12 = ₹75K weighted\n31 Dec: ₹12L → 100% general → ₹12L×3/12 = ₹3L weighted\n31 Mar: ₹2L → 100% general → ₹2L×0/12 = ₹0 weighted\nTotal weighted general expenditure = ₹75K + ₹3L = ₹3,75,000\n\nStep 3 — BC Capitalised:\nOn specific: ₹65,000\nOn general: ₹3,75,000 × 11% = ₹41,250\nTotal = ₹1,06,250\nLess: Investment income on specific: (₹20,000)\nEligible BC = ₹86,250\n\n📌 Investment income deducted ONLY from specific borrowings (not general).\n📌 Expenditure allocated to specific first, remainder to general.", exam:true },

  { id:347, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Practice Q6: Group Capitalisation (4 entities)\n\nGroup: Parent P, Real Estate Co A (₹10L @ 7%, QA expenditure ₹15.4L), Construction Co B (no borrowings, ₹10L own cash on QA), Finance Co C (raised ₹20L @ 7% externally, lent to Parent @ 8%).\nConstruction Co charged 10% profit on work for Real Estate Co.\n\nCompute BC eligible in each entity's FS and consolidated FS.",
    back:"FINANCE CO C:\n→ No expenditure on qualifying assets → CANNOT capitalise anything. ₹NIL\n\nREAL ESTATE CO A (own FS):\n→ Interest = ₹10L × 7% = ₹70,000\n→ QA expenditure (₹15.4L) > borrowings (₹10L)\n→ Expenditures on QA EXCEED borrowings → entire interest of ₹70,000 capitalisable.\nBC = ₹70,000\n\nCONSTRUCTION CO B (own FS):\n→ No interest expense → CANNOT capitalise anything. ₹NIL\n\nCONSOLIDATED FS (Parent P):\nGroup general borrowings: ₹10L (A) + ₹20L (C) = ₹30L\n[Parent's loan from C cannot be excluded — used for acquiring subsidiary, still part of pool]\nGroup interest: ₹30L × 7% = ₹2,10,000; Cap rate = 7%\n\nGroup QA expenditure (eliminate intra-group profit):\nReal Estate A: ₹15.4L ÷ 1.10 = ₹14L (10% profit eliminated)\nConstruction B: ₹10L\nTotal = ₹24L\n\nBC eligible (consolidated) = ₹24L × 7% = ₹1,68,000\n[₹1,68,000 < ₹2,10,000 actual BC → capped at ₹1,68,000]\n\n📌 Parent loan for non-QA purpose (acquiring subsidiary) → still in general pool.\n📌 Intra-group profit on construction services → eliminated before computing QA expenditure.", exam:true },

  { id:348, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 23", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 23 – Illustration 6: ABC Ltd (Exchange Difference — Full Calculation)\n\nABC Ltd: USD 20,000 loan @ 5% p.a. on 1 Apr 20X1 for constructing a plant.\nRate on 1 Apr 20X1: ₹45/USD | Rate on 31 Mar 20X2: ₹48/USD\nCorresponding INR borrowing rate: 11% p.a.\n\nCompute BC to be capitalised for 31 Mar 20X2.",
    back:"Step 1 — Interest on foreign currency loan (at year-end rate):\nUSD 20,000 × 5% = USD 1,000\nConverted: USD 1,000 × ₹48 = ₹48,000\n\nStep 2 — INR equivalent interest (had loan been in INR):\nUSD 20,000 × ₹45 × 11% = ₹99,000\n\nStep 3 — Exchange loss on principal:\nUSD 20,000 × (₹48 − ₹45) = ₹60,000\n\nStep 4 — Eligible exchange difference:\nDifferential = INR interest − USD interest converted\n= ₹99,000 − ₹48,000 = ₹51,000\nExchange loss = ₹60,000 > ₹51,000 differential\n→ Eligible exchange diff = ₹51,000 (capped at differential)\n\nStep 5 — Total BC capitalised:\n(a) Interest on loan: ₹48,000\n(b) Eligible exchange diff: ₹51,000\nTotal BC = ₹99,000 (= INR equivalent — makes sense)\n\nBalance of exchange loss → P&L:\n₹60,000 − ₹51,000 = ₹9,000 → expensed as finance cost\n\n📌 Total eligible BC cannot exceed what would have been paid in functional currency.\n📌 If exchange loss < differential → entire exchange loss is BC (no cap needed).", exam:true }

// ══ FR · Ind AS 20 — Government Grants ══════════════════════════

  { id:349, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Scope & Key Definitions\n\nWhat does Ind AS 20 apply to?\nWhat 4 areas does it NOT apply to?\nDefine: (a) Government (b) Government assistance (c) Government grants (d) Grants related to assets (e) Grants related to income (f) Forgivable loans",
    back:"APPLIES TO:\n(a) Accounting & disclosure of government grants\n(b) Disclosure of other forms of government assistance\n\nDOES NOT APPLY TO:\n(a) Grants in financial statements reflecting changing prices\n(b) Government assistance as tax benefits — income tax holidays, investment tax credits, accelerated depreciation\n(c) Government PARTICIPATION IN OWNERSHIP of the entity\n(d) Government grants covered by Ind AS 41 (Agriculture)\n\nDEFINITIONS:\n(a) Government = government, agencies and similar bodies — local, national or international\n(b) Government assistance = action to provide an economic benefit specific to an entity. Does NOT include benefits indirectly through general trading conditions (e.g., infrastructure for entire community, improved transport networks)\n(c) Government grants = transfers of resources to an entity in return for past or future compliance with conditions relating to OPERATING ACTIVITIES. Exclude: assistance with no value placed on it; transactions indistinguishable from normal trading.\n→ Also called: subsidies, subventions, premiums\n(d) Grants related to assets = grants where PRIMARY CONDITION is that entity should purchase/construct/acquire long-term assets\n(e) Grants related to income = all grants OTHER than those related to assets\n(f) Forgivable loans = loans where lender undertakes to waive repayment under certain prescribed conditions", exam:true },

  { id:350, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Recognition of Government Grants\n\nWhat are the 2 conditions for recognition?\nDoes receipt of the grant confirm recognition?\nHow are forgivable loans treated?\nHow are below-market rate loans treated?",
    back:"2 CONDITIONS (both required — 'reasonable assurance' standard):\n(a) Entity will COMPLY WITH CONDITIONS attached to the grant\n(b) Grant WILL BE RECEIVED\n\n📌 Receipt of grant does NOT by itself provide conclusive evidence that conditions have been or will be fulfilled.\n\nMethod of receipt irrelevant:\n→ Cash received / reduction of liability to government / non-monetary asset → all accounted for in the same manner.\n\nFORGIVABLE LOANS:\n→ Treated as GOVERNMENT GRANT when there is reasonable assurance entity will meet the TERMS FOR FORGIVENESS.\n\nBELOW-MARKET RATE LOANS:\n→ Loan measured per Ind AS 109 (at FAIR VALUE)\n→ Government grant = DIFFERENCE between proceeds received and initial carrying value (FV per Ind AS 109)\n→ Grant accounted for per Ind AS 20\n→ Entity considers conditions and obligations to identify the costs being compensated\n\n📌 Capital approach (credit directly to equity) → REJECTED by Ind AS 20\n📌 Income approach (recognise in P&L on systematic basis) → PRESCRIBED\n📌 Grant for expenses/losses ALREADY INCURRED or for IMMEDIATE FINANCIAL SUPPORT → recognised immediately in P&L in the period it becomes receivable", exam:true },

  { id:351, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Recognition Principle & Capital vs Income Approach\n\nWhy does Ind AS 20 REJECT the capital approach?\nState the income approach principle.\nWhen is immediate P&L recognition appropriate?",
    back:"CAPITAL APPROACH (rejected) — arguments for it:\n• Grants are financing devices → should be in B/S, not P&L\n• Not earned, just an incentive → inappropriate to credit P&L\n\nINDIA REJECTS capital approach because:\n(a) Grants from source other than shareholders → should not go directly to equity\n(b) Grants are RARELY GRATUITOUS — entity earns them by complying with conditions → should match with related costs\n(c) Since taxes are expenses, grants (extension of fiscal policy) should also go through P&L\n\nINCOME APPROACH PRINCIPLE:\n→ Grants recognised in P&L on SYSTEMATIC BASIS over periods in which entity recognises as EXPENSES the related costs the grant is intended to compensate.\n\nPractical application:\n• Grants for specific expenses → P&L in same period as the expense\n• Grants for depreciable assets → P&L over periods/proportions in which depreciation is recognised\n• Grants for non-depreciable assets → P&L over periods bearing cost of meeting obligations (e.g., grant of land conditional on erecting building → P&L over life of building)\n\nIMMEDIATE P&L RECOGNITION:\n→ Grant for expenses/losses ALREADY INCURRED\n→ Grant for IMMEDIATE FINANCIAL SUPPORT with no future related costs\n→ Unconditional grant (no conditions attached)\n\n📌 Receipts basis acceptable ONLY if no basis exists for allocating grant to other periods.", exam:true },

  { id:352, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Presentation of Grants Related to Assets\n\nState the 2 methods of presenting asset-related grants in the balance sheet.\nHow is each method reflected in P&L?\nHow is it disclosed in the Statement of Cash Flows?",
    back:"METHOD 1 — Deferred Income:\n→ Present grant as DEFERRED INCOME in balance sheet\n→ Recognise in P&L on systematic basis over USEFUL LIFE of the asset\n→ P&L shows full depreciation; separate grant credit income\n\nMETHOD 2 — Deduct from Asset:\n→ Deduct grant from carrying amount of the asset\n→ Grant recognised in P&L over life of depreciable asset as REDUCED DEPRECIATION EXPENSE\n→ Net asset carried at lower amount; depreciation charged on lower amount\n\nIllustration 7: Solar panels ₹1 crore, useful life 10 years, grant ₹50 lakhs.\nMethod 1: Deferred income ₹50L; credit ₹5L/year to P&L\nMethod 2: Deduct ₹50L from cost; depreciate ₹50L over 10 years\n\nCASH FLOW STATEMENT:\n→ REGARDLESS of which method used for B/S presentation:\n→ Purchase of asset shown GROSS as outflow in INVESTING activities\n→ Receipt of grant shown SEPARATELY as inflow in INVESTING activities\n→ Both disclosed separately to show gross investment in assets\n\n📌 Non-monetary grants at fair value → presented as deferred income (same treatment as Method 1)\n📌 The 2 methods differ in B/S and P&L presentation; both acceptable under Ind AS 20", exam:true },

  { id:353, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Presentation of Grants Related to Income\n\nState the 2 methods. Give the argument for each.\nAre both acceptable?",
    back:"METHOD 1 — Credit in Statement of P&L (as 'Other Income' or separate line):\n→ Grant presented as income (separately or under 'Other Income')\n→ Expense shown gross; grant shown separately\nArguments for:\n• Inappropriate to net income and expense items\n• Separation facilitates comparison with expenses not affected by a grant\n\nMETHOD 2 — Deducted in reporting related expense:\n→ Grant deducted from the related expense → net expense shown\nArguments for:\n• Expenses might not have been incurred if grant had not been available\n• Showing full expense without offsetting grant may be MISLEADING\n\nBOTH methods are ACCEPTABLE under Ind AS 20.\nMethod 2 may be more appropriate when grant can be specifically related to an expenditure.\n\nIllustration 9: Grant ₹10L for environmental protection; costs ₹3L/year for 5 years.\nMethod 1: Recognise ₹2L/year as 'Other Income'; show ₹3L as environmental expense\nMethod 2: Net expense = ₹3L − ₹2L = ₹1L shown as environmental expense\n\n📌 Disclosure of the grant may be necessary for proper understanding even when Method 2 is used.\n📌 Effect of grants on items required to be separately disclosed → appropriate to disclose.", exam:true },

  { id:354, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Repayment of Government Grants\n\nHow is repayment treated?\nDistinguish between repayment of income grant vs asset grant.\n[Illustration 10 — A Ltd]",
    back:"Repayment of government grant → treated as CHANGE IN ACCOUNTING ESTIMATE (Ind AS 8). NOT an error.\n\nREPAYMENT OF INCOME GRANT:\nStep 1: Apply repayment FIRST AGAINST any unamortised DEFERRED CREDIT\nStep 2: If repayment exceeds deferred credit, OR if no deferred credit exists → recognise EXCESS immediately in P&L\n\nREPAYMENT OF ASSET GRANT:\nEITHER:\n(a) REDUCE the deferred income balance by the amount repayable; OR\n(b) INCREASE the carrying amount of the asset by the amount repayable\n→ Cumulative additional depreciation that would have been recognised (in absence of grant) → recognised immediately in P&L\n→ Check asset for possible impairment (Ind AS 36)\n\nIllustration 10 — A Ltd:\n→ Grant ₹10 crores received in 20X1-20X2; recognised as income in 20X1-20X2\n→ In 20X5-20X6, found conditions not met → court order → fully repayable\n→ No deferred credit exists in 20X5-20X6 (already recognised as income)\n→ Journal entries:\n(i) Repayment of Govt Grant Dr. ₹10Cr | To Grant repayable ₹10Cr (P&L expense)\n(ii) Grant repayable Dr. ₹10Cr | To Bank ₹10Cr\n\n📌 Repayment is a CHANGE IN ESTIMATE — no prior period restatement required\n📌 Recognition of grant is not affected by the method of repayment.", exam:true },

  { id:355, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Concept", difficulty:"Basic", exam:false,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Non-Monetary Grants, Government Assistance & Disclosure\n\nHow are non-monetary grants measured?\nWhat is 'government assistance' that escapes grant accounting?\nState the 5 disclosure requirements.",
    back:"NON-MONETARY GRANTS:\nEITHER:\n(a) Assess FAIR VALUE of non-monetary asset → account for both asset AND grant at fair value\nOR\n(b) Record both asset and grant at NOMINAL VALUE\n\nGOVERNMENT ASSISTANCE (not govt grants):\n→ Assistance with no value that can reasonably be assigned: free technical advice, marketing advice, provision of guarantees\n→ Transactions indistinguishable from normal trading: govt procurement policy driving entity's sales; priority bidding status; credit facilities at MARKET RATES (airline example)\n→ Provision of infrastructure for entire communities (roads, irrigation, communication networks)\n→ These CANNOT be recognised as grants — disclosed only if significant\n\nAPPENDIX A: Government assistance with no specific relation to operating activities (e.g., grants for operating in certain region/industry sector) → still meets definition of govt grant → must be recognised in P&L, NOT directly to equity.\n\n5 DISCLOSURES REQUIRED:\n(a) Accounting policy adopted for government grants\n(b) Methods of presentation adopted in financial statements\n(c) Nature and extent of grants recognised\n(d) Indication of other forms of government assistance from which entity directly benefited\n(e) Unfulfilled conditions and other contingencies attaching to recognised government assistance", exam:false },

  { id:356, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Theory Q&A", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 vs AS 12 – Key Differences\n\nState 5 significant differences.",
    back:"1. NON-DEPRECIABLE ASSET GRANTS:\nInd AS 20: Taken to P&L on systematic basis (all grants have conditions)\nAS 12: Credited to CAPITAL RESERVE (part of shareholders' funds)\n\n2. NON-MONETARY GRANTS AT CONCESSIONAL RATE:\nInd AS 20: At FAIR VALUE or nominal value\nAS 12: At ACQUISITION COST; free-of-cost assets at NOMINAL VALUE only\n\n3. PROMOTERS' CONTRIBUTION GRANTS:\nInd AS 20: Does NOT recognise promoters' contribution — all grants treated as income; cannot go directly to shareholders' funds\nAS 12: Credited to capital reserve in shareholders' funds\n\n4. BELOW-MARKET RATE LOANS:\nInd AS 20: Loan measured per Ind AS 109 (fair value); difference = government grant\nAS 12: Does NOT deal with this situation\n\n5. GOVERNMENT ASSISTANCE (not qualifying as grants):\nInd AS 20: Requires DISCLOSURE of other forms of government assistance from which entity directly benefited\nAS 12: Does not deal with such government assistance\n\n📌 Core difference: Ind AS 20 = income approach only (all grants through P&L)\nAS 12 = permits capital approach for certain grants (capital reserve in equity)", exam:true },

  { id:357, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 20 – Illustrations 1, 2 & 3: Recognition Timing\n\n(1) Grant of ₹10L for PAST research of H1N1 vaccine. No condition.\n(2) Grant of ₹10L for R&D of H1N1 vaccine over 2 years (40% cost reduction condition). Reasonable assurance exists.\n(3) Grant of ₹10L to rehabilitate 100 artisans over 3 years. Govt releases ₹2L so far.\n\nHow is each recognised?",
    back:"(1) ₹10L for PAST research — NO condition:\n→ Recognise ENTIRE ₹10L IMMEDIATELY in P&L\n→ Past activity already completed; no future obligation; no deferral needed.\n\n(2) ₹10L for R&D over 2 years — future condition:\n→ Recognise ₹10L as DEFERRED INCOME immediately (reasonable assurance confirmed)\n→ Charge to P&L over 2 years as costs are incurred\n→ (₹5L per year over 2 years)\n\n(3) ₹10L for rehabilitating artisans over 3 years — only ₹2L received so far:\n→ Recognise FULL ₹10L as deferred income (not just ₹2L received)\n→ Recognise in P&L over 3 years as artisans are rehabilitated\n→ Method of receipt (instalment or lump sum) does NOT affect accounting\n→ Any related contingent liability/asset → treated per Ind AS 37\n\n📌 KEY PRINCIPLE: Amount recognised ≠ amount received. Recognition based on reasonable assurance, not cash receipt.\n📌 Receipt alone does NOT confirm conditions are fulfilled.\n📌 For past costs/losses or immediate financial support → recognise in P&L immediately.", exam:true },

  { id:358, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 20 – Illustration 4 & Q2: Below-Market Rate Loan (Government Grant)\n\nIllustration 4: Loan ₹50L @ 5%, market rate 12%, bullet repayment after 5 years, interest payable annually.\nQ2: Loan ₹1 crore @ 5%, same terms.\n\nCalculate: (a) Fair value of loan (b) Government grant (c) Journal entry on receipt",
    back:"ILLUSTRATION 4 (₹50 lakhs):\nPV of interest payments (₹2,50,000/yr × PVAF @ 12%, 5 yrs):\n₹2,50,000 × (0.893+0.797+0.712+0.636+0.567) = ₹2,50,000 × 3.605 = ₹9,01,194\nPV of principal (₹50L × 0.567) = ₹28,37,134\nFair value of loan = ₹37,38,328\nGovernment grant = ₹50,00,000 − ₹37,38,328 = ₹12,61,672\n\nJournal entry on receipt:\nBank A/c Dr. 50,00,000\n  To Deferred Income (Govt Grant) 12,61,672\n  To Loan A/c 37,38,328\n\nGrant recognition: ₹12,61,672 recognised in P&L systematically over periods matching related costs:\n• Immediate relief measure → immediate P&L\n• Staff training over 4 years → ₹3,15,418/year × 4\n• Depreciable asset → over life of asset on same basis as depreciation\n\nQ2 (₹1 crore):\nFair value = ₹74,76,656\nGovernment grant = ₹1,00,00,000 − ₹74,76,656 = ₹25,23,344\nJournal entry:\nBank A/c Dr. 1,00,00,000\n  To Deferred Income 25,23,344\n  To Loan A/c 74,76,656\n\n📌 Loan is recognised at FAIR VALUE (Ind AS 109); discount = government grant\n📌 Subsequent: interest expense at EFFECTIVE RATE (12%), cash paid at contract rate (5%)", exam:true },

  { id:359, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 20 – Illustration 6: Non-Monetary Grant (Land)\n\nA Ltd. establishes manufacturing unit in backward area. Government provides 5 acres of land on leasehold basis at ₹10,000/acre. Fair value = ₹1,00,000/acre.\n\nCalculate the government grant amount and state presentation options.",
    back:"FAIR VALUE METHOD:\nLand recognised at fair value: 5 × ₹1,00,000 = ₹5,00,000\nAmount paid: 5 × ₹10,000 = ₹50,000\nGovernment grant = ₹5,00,000 − ₹50,000 = ₹4,50,000\n→ Land on B/S: ₹5,00,000\n→ Deferred income (grant): ₹4,50,000\n\nNOMINAL VALUE METHOD (alternative):\nLand on B/S: ₹50,000 (nominal cost paid)\nNo grant recognised\n\n📌 Note: Land is usually non-depreciable → grant recognised in P&L over periods of related obligations (e.g., period of employment commitment, operating period in that area)\n📌 Both methods permitted by Ind AS 20\n📌 If government gives land FREE of cost → at nominal value of ₹0 OR at fair value — both acceptable\n\nRelated: Q1 — Two acres of land (FV ₹10L) given free:\n→ Fair value method: land ₹10L, deferred income ₹10L\n→ Nominal value: land at nominal amount", exam:true },

  { id:360, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 20 – Q6: Grant on Depreciable Asset — Both Methods\n\nNew factory. Capital equipment ₹1,00,000. Government grant ₹15,000. Depreciation: 20% SLM.\n\nShow P&L and Balance Sheet extracts for Year 1 under both methods.",
    back:"METHOD 1 — Grant as DEFERRED INCOME:\n\nP&L (Year 1):\nDepreciation: (₹1,00,000 × 20%) = ₹(20,000)\nGovernment grant credit: (₹15,000 × 20%) = ₹3,000\n\nBalance Sheet (Year 1 end):\nNon-current assets:\n  PPE: ₹1,00,000 − ₹20,000 (accum dep) = ₹80,000\nNon-current liabilities:\n  Govt grant (deferred): ₹15,000 − ₹3,000 (current) = ₹12,000\nCurrent liabilities:\n  Govt grant (current year portion): ₹3,000\n\nMETHOD 2 — Grant DEDUCTED FROM ASSET:\n\nP&L (Year 1):\nDepreciation: (₹1,00,000 − ₹15,000) × 20% = ₹(17,000)\n\nBalance Sheet (Year 1 end):\nNon-current assets:\n  PPE: ₹85,000 − ₹17,000 (accum dep) = ₹68,000\n\n📌 Method 1: Asset carried at FULL COST (₹1,00,000), depreciation higher (₹20,000), but grant income offsets.\n📌 Method 2: Asset carried at NET COST (₹85,000), depreciation lower (₹17,000), no separate grant income.\n📌 Net P&L impact: Method 1 = ₹17,000 net expense; Method 2 = ₹17,000 net expense. SAME RESULT.\n📌 Both methods give identical effect on P&L over asset's life.", exam:true },

  { id:361, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Advanced", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 20 – Q5: Rainbow Limited (Multiple Grants + Flood Compensation)\n\nGrant 1 (₹1L): 'Clean River Project' — no major steps commenced as at 31 Mar 20X2.\nGrant 2 (₹1L): Commercial development of eco-friendly equipment — technically feasible, ready for sale April 20X3.\nFlood compensation: State Govt scheme entitles Rainbow Ltd to compensation based on avg 3-month sales. Application form to be filed by 30 Jun 20X2. Financials adopted 31 May 20X2.\n\nAccount for each as at 31 Mar 20X2.",
    back:"GRANT 1 — Clean River Project (₹1,00,000):\nIf UNCONDITIONAL (no conditions for refund mentioned):\n→ Recognise IMMEDIATELY in P&L for year ended 31 Mar 20X2.\n→ Even though research not started, grant is unconditional → immediate recognition.\nIf CONDITIONAL (on expenditure):\n→ Recognise in P&L as expenditure is incurred in future years.\n\nGRANT 2 — Eco-friendly Equipment (₹1,00,000):\n→ Grant related to a DEPRECIABLE ASSET (equipment available from April 20X3).\n→ Until 31 Mar 20X2: recognise as DEFERRED INCOME (asset not yet ready).\n→ From April 20X3: recognise deferred income over asset's useful life (matching depreciation).\n→ B/S at 31 Mar 20X2: Deferred income ₹1,00,000 as liability.\n→ Alternative: Deduct from cost of equipment from April 20X3.\n\nFLOOD COMPENSATION:\n→ Flood occurred Sept 20X1 (within FY 20X1-20X2).\n→ Application form to be filed AFTER 31 May 20X2 (after adoption of financials).\n→ Grant not receivable as at 31 Mar 20X2 — application not yet submitted/approved.\n→ DO NOT recognise in FY 20X1-20X2.\n→ Recognise in FY 20X2-20X3 when application submitted and approved.\n\n📌 KEY: Compensation receivable ≠ recognition criterion. Must meet 'reasonable assurance' test AND be receivable.", exam:true },

  { id:362, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Practical", difficulty:"Intermediate", exam:true,
    front:"📐 Ind AS 20 – Q1: ABC Ltd (Multiple Grants — Recognition)\n\nABC Ltd. receives:\n(a) ₹20L for immediate start-up. No further condition.\n(b) ₹50L for R&D of cardiovascular drugs (conditions: 20% cheaper price + WHO quality).\n(c) 2 acres of land (FV ₹10L) free of cost.\n(d) ₹2L for purchase of ₹10L machinery (5-year life, SLM).\n\nRecommend accounting treatment for each.",
    back:"(a) ₹20 LAKHS — immediate start-up, no condition:\n→ Recognise IMMEDIATELY in P&L.\n→ No deferral needed — no future obligation.\n\n(b) ₹50 LAKHS — R&D with conditions:\n→ Recognise in P&L on SYSTEMATIC BASIS over periods costs are incurred (subject to reasonable assurance of compliance).\n→ Set up as deferred income; release to P&L as related R&D costs are recognised.\n\n(c) LAND (FV ₹10L) — given free of cost:\n→ Fair value method: Land at ₹10L; Deferred income ₹10L.\n→ Alternative (nominal value): Land at nominal amount.\n→ Note: Land in question has no cost to entity (free) — recognised at FV or nominal value.\n\n(d) ₹2L GRANT FOR ₹10L MACHINERY (5 years, SLM):\nMethod 1 — Deferred income:\n→ Set up ₹2L as deferred income.\n→ Credit ₹40,000 (₹2L/5) to P&L each year.\n→ Depreciate ₹10L over 5 years = ₹2,00,000/year\n\nMethod 2 — Deduct from asset:\n→ Carry machinery at ₹8L (₹10L − ₹2L).\n→ Depreciate ₹8L over 5 years = ₹1,60,000/year\n→ Net P&L impact per year: ₹1,60,000 (same as Method 1 net effect of ₹2,00,000 − ₹40,000)\n\n📌 Both methods give identical net P&L effect over the asset's useful life.", exam:true },

  { id:363, subject:"FR", standard:"Ind AS 20", category:"Quick Fire", difficulty:"Basic", exam:true,
    front:"Ind AS 20 – Quick Fire\n\n1. Government grants approach prescribed by Ind AS 20: ___\n2. Recognition condition for grants: ___\n3. Below-market rate loan: grant = ___\n4. Forgivable loan treated as grant when: ___\n5. Repayment of grant = change in ___ (Ind AS ___)\n6. Cash flow: grant shown as ___ activity\n7. Capital approach permitted? ___\n8. Promoters' contribution under Ind AS 20: ___",
    back:"1. INCOME APPROACH — recognised in P&L on systematic basis (capital approach rejected)\n\n2. Reasonable assurance that: (a) entity will comply with conditions AND (b) grant will be received\n\n3. Below-market loan: grant = Proceeds received − FV of loan (per Ind AS 109)\n\n4. Forgivable loan = grant when reasonable assurance entity will meet terms for forgiveness\n\n5. Repayment = CHANGE IN ACCOUNTING ESTIMATE (Ind AS 8) — not an error\n\n6. Cash flow: grant shown as INVESTING activity (receipt = inflow; shown separately from asset purchase)\n\n7. Capital approach: NOT PERMITTED under Ind AS 20\n\n8. Promoters' contribution: NOT permitted to credit to capital reserve — must go through P&L (unlike AS 12)\n\nBonus:\n→ Non-monetary grants: at fair value OR nominal value\n→ Grants for past costs/losses → immediate P&L recognition\n→ Non-depreciable asset grant → P&L over period of meeting obligations (not directly to equity)\n→ Income grant repayment: first vs deferred credit, then P&L", exam:true }
